taxonomicNotes: Diplodus cervinus was previously recognized as comprising three subspecies: Diplodus cervinus cervinus (NE Atlantic and Mediterranean), D. c. hottentotus (SE Atlantic: Angola, South Africa), and D. c. omanensis (Indian Ocean: Oman). Currently, three species are recognized: D. cervinus, D. hottentotus (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004) and D. omanensis (Bauchot and Bianchi 1984, Amir et al. 2013). However, the Diplodus cervinus complex is in need of taxonomic review (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2014).
In Australia, this species is easily confused with Drombus triangularis, with which it is sympatric across the north. The species may also be a synonym of Drombus palackyi described from Samoa.

Published data: This species has two subspecies:  Hyporhamphus roberti hildebrandi and Hyporhamphus roberti roberti.

Two other common and very similar species of western Atlantic Strongylura occur alongside Strongylura marina in the Western Central Atlantic: Strongylura notata and Strongylura timucu. Until the late 1960s, S. timucu was largely considered to be synonymous with S. marina (Berry and Rivas 1962). Collette (1968) notes that S. notata differs from S. marina and S. timucu in having fewer anal rays and fewer predorsal scales, and internal examination also reveals fewer vertebrae and other distinguishing skeletal features. Internal examination also reveals that both gonads are developed in S. tumucu while only the right gonad is developed in S. marina. Typically, S. timucu is also somewhat darker in coloration than S. marina (Hoese and Moore 1977). Strongylura notata differs externally from S. marina, possessing 13-15 dorsal rays and 13-16 anal rays (Hoese and Moore 1977).

This species has recently been placed in the genus Ostorhinchus by Randall (2005) based on L.M.R. Bergman's unpublished PhD thesis (in which Ostorhinchus was shown to be polyphyletic). The generic placement of this species may change.

Genetic studies of Pagrus pagrus have shown Western Atlantic samples to be more closely related to each other than to samples from the Eastern North Atlantic. Within the Western North Atlantic, no significant population differentiation was observed, and within the eastern North Atlantic, only the Azores sample showed detectable differences from those from Crete and Madeira. These data indicate general homogeneity within large areas, and deep divisions between these areas (Ball et al. 2007).
This species appeared in the IUCN Red List prior to 2008 under the generic name Papillogobius.
Has previously been confused with Leucoraja garmani (McEachran and Carvalho 2002).
The similar, but larger, Etmopterus bigelowi was previously confused with this species until described as a distinct species by Shirai and Tachikawa (1993).

Taxonomy remains unresolved for this species, with nominal records from various locations likely to represent other species (Ebert et al. 2013). This species is frequently misidentified with other regional etmopterids, e.g., Etmopterus burgessi (Schaaf-DaSilva and Ebert 2006). Therefore, care should be taken when identifying similar looking lucifer-group lanternsharks.

Toxotes chatareus probably comprises a large species complex; Australian species almost certainly represent a separate species (Heok Hee Ng, pers. comm.). The species is in need of taxonomic review.

Odonteleotris macrodon may consist of two or more species, and further research is required (D. Hoese in litt.). This species was described from West Bengal, India and so if this species is split into more than one species then the name will be associated with the species in India.
Contemporary studies indicate that Tephrinectes is not a member of the family Paralichthyidae (Hensley and Ahlstrom 1984, Hoshino and Amaoka 1998).

This species has been referred to as Lutjanus malabaricus or Lutjanus altifrontalis by many recent authors.
There are several nominal species referred to with the name Cynoglossus puncticeps. The taxonomic status of these nominal species needs to be determined (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2014).

Species formerly known under the genus Poecilophis are synonyms of the genus Echidna. Poecilophis tritor and Poecilophis pikei are synonyms of Echidna polyzona. In addition, Echidna leihala, Echidna obscura, Echidna psalion, Echidna sauvagel, Echidna vincta, Echidna zonata, and Echidna zonophaea are all considered synonyms of Echidna polyzona. Other synonyms also included under Echidna polyzona are Muraena dizona and Muraena fascigula.

Cynoglossus trigrammus is considered a junior synonym of C. abbreviatus by some; however, both are treated as valid species by other workers (e.g., Li and Wang 1995). According to Kottelat (2001), the status of these nominal species needs clarification.
This species may be part of a complex of similar species (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011).

This species was previously considered a junior synonym of D. tumifrons (D. hypselsomus) but is considered as valid by Iwatsuki et al. (2007).

This species was previously confused with Rhabdosargus sarba. Rhabdosargus thorpei was described as a separate species by Margaret Smith in 1979 after being recognized by Mr. Anthony Thorpe. The name R. auriventris has also previously been applied to this fish (van der Elst 1988).

The type locality of this species is in the Red Sea. The Red Sea specimen is significantly genetically different from the Arabian Gulf specimens. Further study is needed to clarify the taxonomic status of this species (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2013).

Both the specific and generic status of this species is under review and likely to change (K. Carpenter pers. comm. 2009).


The phylogeny of sparids, and the taxonomy of snapper in particular, has attracted considerable attention. In Australasia, snapper had previously been assigned to the genus Chrysophrys, formerly as Chrysophrys unicolor and more latterly as C. auratus (Paulin 1990). Paulin (1990) determined Pagrus to be the senior synonym of Chrysophrys, and re-described C. auratus as Pagrus auratus. In addition, he concluded that the species known as red sea bream in Japan, i.e. Pagrus major, was a conspecific and should also be re-described as P. auratus. Researchers in Japan, however, have not adopted this taxonomy (Jackson 2007).

The taxonomic name was changed to Diplodus capensis from Diplodus sargus capensis in 2004 (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). Two disjunct populations exist, one along the eastern seaboard of South Africa from Cape Point to southern Mozambique (Smith and Heemstra 1991, Mann 1992) and another from Namibia to southern Angola (Richardson 2010). These two populations may represent two separate species (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004, Richardson 2010). This evaluation dealt with D. capensis sensu strictu (distributed from False Bay to southern Mozambique).
This species has been misidentified as Acanthopagrus latus (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2009).

The south east and south west Australian populations of this species may represent separate species, or subspecies, and there is a need for genetic studies (Y. Iwatsuki pers comm. 2009). It is known to hybridise with A. australis in southern New South Wales (Rowland 1984).

A number of synonyms have been previously used for Rhabdosargus sarba, including Sparus sarba, Austrosparus sarba, Chrysophrys sarba, etc. (Smith and Smith 1986). In Australia, Whitley (1931) described Roughleyia (=Rhabdosargus) tarwhine to distinguish the eastern Australian species from the east African species. Then Munro (1949) reviewed the genus in Australia and confirmed the name Rhabdosargus sarba for the west and east Indian, and west Pacific Ocean populations. Whitley (1964) persisted with the subspecies status as Rhabdosargus sarba tarwhine for the Australian population, but this was not followed by others. The taxonomy of the Rhabdosargus sarba complex is currently under review by Yukio Iwatsuki, (Miyazaki University, Japan). 

Rhabdosargus sarba might be confused with R. haffara. Taxonomic review is urgently needed (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2013).

Iwatsuki et al. 2007 examined the lectotype of Chrysophrys tumifrons, concluding that the specimen was actually the species recognized as Evynnis japonica (Tanaka 1931), and therefore a senior synonym of that species. Evynnis tumifrons (Temminck and Schlegel 1843) has not been recorded from Australia. Dentex spariformis Ogilby, 1910 (described from Moreton Island) and previously considered a synonym of Dentex tumifrons, was therefore resurrected. All Australian records of Dentex tumifrons most probably refer to Dentex spariformis.

According to Iwatsuki and Maclaine (2013), Crenidens crenidens and C. indicus are two distinct species. Crenidens crenidens occurs from the Red Sea, East Africa along the east coast of Africa to Aliwal Shoal in South Africa. Juvenile C. crenidens have been found in Algoa Bay, South Africa (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). Crenidens indicus occurs from the southern Arabian Peninsula (occasionally in the Red Sea) to the coasts of Iran and Pakistan, including the Gulf. Bauchot and Smith (1984) reported C. indicus from India; however, C. indicus either doesn't occur around India or it is extremely rare in the area (Iwatsuki and Maclaine 2013). 

Previously, two different sub-species were recognized. Crenidens crenidens indicus from the coasts of India and the Arabian Sea and C. crenidens crenidens along the east coast of Africa. In the Red Sea the two subspecies were found to coexist, with a predominance of C. crenidens crenidens (Fischer and Bianchi 1984).

Archosargus probatocephalus is subdivided into three subspecies by some authors: A. probatocephalus probatocephalus for the northern form from Nova Scotia to Cedar Key on the west coast of Florida; A. probatocephalus oviceps Ginsburg (which is associated with muddy bottoms) in the Gulf of Mexico from St. Harks, Florida to the Campeche Bank; and A. probatocephalus aries from Belize to Bahia de Sepetiba, Brazil (Carpenter 2002).

The Chesapeake Bay Sheepshead population is suggested to constitute a separate population, as large differences in vital rates are often indicative of this. The differences observed in growth could arise due to a variety of factors, including differences in mortality rates, environmental conditions, food sources, or genetic variation (Ballenger et al. 2007).

Frequency distributions of each of five meristic counts are significantly different between the subspecies found in the northeastern Gulf of Mexico: A. probatocephalus probatocephalus and A. probatocephalus oviceps (P < 0.05). However, Bayesian structure analysis of microsatellite genotypes indicated that all Gulf of Mexico Sheepshead populations constitute a single stock.Variance partitioning of mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) haplotypes suggests significant but limited divergence between subspecies (genetic differentiation index FST = 0.036, P < 0.005). Molecular data from North American subspecies of  Sheepshead indicate very limited genetic subdivision between the subspecies despite considerable divergence of morphological characters. Genetic structure is defined primarily by the geographic distance between sampling locales from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic. Overall, Sheepshead molecular genetic data indicate very limited genetic subdivision between the subspecies despite considerable divergence of morphological characters (Anderson et al. 2008).

Argyrops spinifer may represent three unique species in the Arabian Gulf (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2013). Iwatsuki and Heemstra (2018) recently described A. flavops from Mutrah, Oman and Karachi, Pakistan and A. caeruleops from the Gulf of Oman, southern Oman, Socotra and Pakistan. Further study of additional specimens is required to determine the extent of their distributions in the western Indian Ocean/Arabian Seas region.

Two color morphs of this species have been observed, and further taxonomic study is needed (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2009). A northern and southern population were originally both described as Acanthopagrus bifasciatus in the Indian Ocean. Iwatsuki and Heemstra (2011) determined that both populations were two valid species, the northern population (Red Sea to the Arabian Gulf) is described as A. bifasciatus, while the southern population (southern Oman to South Africa) is described as A. catenula (Lacepède 1801).

This species was previously misidentified as Dentex tumifrons. However, tumifrons is a senior synonym of Evynnis japonica, and the next available name for this species is hypselosomus (Iwatsuki et al. 2007).
This species was previously recognized as a subspecies of Pagellus bellottii. It is currently valid as Pagellus natalensis (Eschmeyer and Fricke 2009).
This species is nested within Dentex in genetic studies (K. Carpenter pers. comm. 2011).
This species is frequently confused with Pachymetopon grande (Smith and Heemstra 1986).

Diplodus cervinus was previously recognized as comprising three subspecies: Diplodus cervinus cervinus (NE Atlantic and Mediterranean), D. c. hottentotus (SE Atlantic: Angola, South Africa), and D. c. omanensis (Indian Ocean: Oman). Currently, three species are recognized: D. cervinus, D. hottentotus (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004) and D. omanensis (Bauchot and Bianchi 1984, Amir et al. 2013). Diplodus hottentotus is now believed to be an endemic species occurring from Cape Point to Kosi Bay in South Africa (Smith and Heemstra 1986, Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). Diplodus hottentotus sensu strictu. However, the Diplodus cervinus complex is in need of taxonomic review (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2014).

The species D. hottentotus is the same species in southern Angola as it is along the eastern seaboard of southern Africa. However, as with D. capensis, these populations have been separated for ~ two million years by the Benguela Current so can be treated as separate populations for management purposes (Bauchot and Bianchi 1984, Winkler 2013).

Diplodus cervinus was previously recognized as comprising three subspecies: Diplodus cervinus cervinus (NE Atlantic and Mediterranean), D. c. hottentotus (SE Atlantic: Angola, South Africa), and D. c. omanensis (Indian Ocean: Oman). Currently, three species are recognized: D. cervinus, D. hottentotus (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004) and D. omanensis (Bauchot and Bianchi 1984, Amir et al. 2013). However, the Diplodus cervinus complex is in need of taxonomic review (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2014).

The family Centracanthidae will soon be subsumed under the family Sparidae, because the centracanthid fishes are highly polyphyletic with sparid fishes (Chiba et al. 2009, Hanel and Tsigenopoulos 2011, Santini et al. 2014).

Most often, Spicara flexuosa has been confused with S. maena in identifications, and they are typically lumped in fisheries statistics and in markets. Spicara flexuosa is currently considered a synonym of S. maena (Pollard and Pichot 1972, Heemstra 1990, Bilecenoglu et al. 2002, Minos et al. 2012), although genetic studies using the mtDNA 16S rRNA gene are inconclusive. Recent genetic work by Imsiridou et al. (2011) indicates that there is a clear discrimination between the two species, and Minos et al. (2012) distinguished the two based on morphological differences.

However, Turan (2011) found genetic divergence to be only 0.005 and previous work by Arculeo et al. (1996) using protein electrophoresis found no discriminating genetic markers. Pending further taxonomic studies, we here continue to regard S. flexuosa as a synonym of S. maena (Pichot and Pollard 1970, Pollard and Pichot 1971, Pollard and Pichot 1972).

Ambassis gymnocephalus was described as Lutjanus gymnocephalus by Lacepède (1802) from Indo-Pacific region. Although the species has been considered as valid by Day (1875), Talwar and Jhingran (1991) and Jayaram (1999), it is considered as 'nomen dubium' by Anderson and Heemstra (2003) because of the considerable taxonomic confusion and on the basis of the lack of diagnostic features. Further taxonomic studies, preferably involving molecular techniques, are essential.
Pomadasys argenteus was originally described as Sciaena argentea by Forsskål (1775) from Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, Red Sea.
Naso lituratus was observed to be actively hybriding with N. elegans at Cocos-Keeling (J.H. Choat pers. comm. 2010, Klanten 2003).
There was a significant level of genetic structure observed between North and South Atlantic populations, suggesting limited dispersal across the Amazon barrier (Rocha et al. 2002).

This species is a member of the Acanthurus achilles species complex known for their propensity to hybridize (Randall and Frische 2000). The four species in this complex (A. achilles Shaw, A. japonicus Schmidt, A. leucosternon Bennett, and A. nigricans Linnaeus) are thought to hybridize when their distributional ranges overlap (Craig 2008).
There is strong geographical pattern in the genetic structure of Acanthurus triostegus throughout the tropical Pacific but this does not warrant species recognition (Planes and Fauvelot 2002).

Acanthurus nigricans is a member of the A. achilles species complex known for their propensity to hybridize (Randall and Frische 2000). The four species in this complex (A. achilles Shaw, A. japonicus Schmidt, A. leucosternon Bennett, and A. nigricans) are thought to hybridize when their distributional ranges overlap (Craig 2008). Hybrids have been recorded from the Hawaiian Islands (Acanthurus achilles x nigricans), Taiwan (Acanthurus japonicus x nigricans), Indonesia, Christmas and Cocos Island (Acanthurus leucosternon x nigricans) (Randall 2001a, Marie et al. 2007).

Naso unicornis is widespread throughout the Indo-Pacific region, genetic studies conducted by Horne et al. (2008) did not find any evidence of geographic population structure even at the largest spatial scales.

This species is a member of the Acanthurus achilles species complex known for their propensity to hybridize (Randall and Frische 2000). The four species in this complex (A. achilles Shaw, A.japonicus Schmidt, A.leucosternon Bennett, and A.nigricans) are thought to hybridize when their distributional ranges overlap (Craig 2008).

Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) survey reveal strong separation between the Brazilian and Carribean provinces, and no significant population structure across the oceanic gap separating Brazil and the mid-Atlantic ridge. The genetic differences between the Brazilian and Carribean populations is matched by colour differences: in the North Atlantic, individuals show a distinguishing arrow, bluish posterior margin on the caudal and dorsal fins, whereas in the South Atlantic, individuals have a bright yellow margin (Rocha et al. 2002). Morphological and genetic data indicate that Acanthurus bahianus is now split into two species: Acanthurus tractus, which is distributed in the northwestern Atlantic and  A. bahianus distributed from eastern Brazil to Ascension and St. Helena Islands (Bernal and Rocha 2011).
Acanthurus sohal is closely related to the Indo-Pacific species Acanthurus lineatus (Alwany et al. 2005).

Naso brevirostris is widespread throughout the Indo-Pacific region, genetic studies conducted by Horne et al. (2008) did not find any evidence of geographic population structure even at the largest spatial scales.
This species hybridizes with Acanthurus nigricauda in the Marshall Is. and A. tennentii in Bali (Randall 2001a).
[ probably represents 2 different species (K.E. Carpenter pers. comm. 2012) [ check back on the paper with published taxonomic revision]
Acanthurus tennentii hybridizes with A. olivaceus in Bali, Indonesia (Randall 2001a).
Hybrids of Acanthurus trisis with A. pyroferus were observed in Bali, Indonesia (Randall 2001a).

Acanthurus nigroris is an endemic species in the Hawaiian Islands and Johnston Atoll,  Acanthurus nigros is valid for the species elsewhere in Oceania and the Great Barrier Reef. The genetic analyses, based on mtDNA cytochrome b sequences from a total of 544 Acanthurus nigroris samples, revealed a clear separation (d = 0.041) between individuals from the Hawaiian Archipelago and the rest of the Pacific indicating a cryptic species pair (Randall et al. submitted manuscript, DiBattista et al. 2011).

This species is a member of the Acanthurus achilles species complex known for their propensity to hybridize (Randall and Frische 2000). The four species in this complex (A. achilles Shaw, A.japonicus Schmidt, A.leucosternon Bennett, and A.nigricans) are thought to hybridize when their distributional ranges overlap (Craig 2008).

Acanthurus cf. leucosternon, a hybrid between A. leucosternon and A. nigricans has been recognized from the Cocos Keeling and Christmas Islands (Marie et al. 2007).
Zebrasoma scopas hybridizes with Z. flavescens and Z. rostratum (Randall 2001a).
A. nigricauda x olivaceous hybrids have been observed in the Marshall Islands (Randall 2001a).
Ctenochaetus flavicauda is closely related to C. cyanocheilus (K.D. Clements pers. comm. 2010).
Hybrids of this species and A. tristis have been observed in Bali, Indonesia (Randall 2001a).

Many of the currently valid Enneanectes spp. are likely species complexes (J. Williams pers. comm. 2014). There are four valid species present in the Gulf of Mexico as of January 2014: E. altivelis, E. boehlkei, E. jordani, and E. pectoralis, and these have been assessed as currently valid.

Many of the currently valid Enneanectes spp. are likely species complexes (J. Williams pers. comm. 2014). There are four valid species present in the Gulf of Mexico as of January 2014: E. altivelis, E. boehlkei, E. jordani, and E. pectoralis, and these have been assessed as currently valid. This species is described in the genus Pavoclinus, however it should probably be placed in a new genus (W. Holleman pers. comm. 2010).

Ophiclinops hutchinsi appears to be the sister species of O. pardalis, with which it shares generally high counts for meristic characters, a large maximum size, and similarity of colour pattern. Ophiclinops hutchinsi is known only from Western Australia while O. pardalis is known only from eastern Australia. These two species should be synonymized when specimens at localities between the two areas of known distribution are examined and if the populations have intermediate fin-ray and vertebral counts between O. hutchinsi and O. pardalis. (George and Springer 1980, Gomon et al. 1994).
Tripterygion tripteronotum was split into two distinct species, T. tripteronotum and T. tartessicum, based on genetic and morphological characteristics (Carreras-Carbonell et al. 2007).
Molecular work indicates that there is no separation between the Australian species from the New Zealand species, and both are regarded as the same (Hoese, D.F. in prep.).
There are two undescribed sibling species, one from False Bay and the second from just east of False Bay (W. Holleman pers.comm. 2010).

Pellegrin and Chevey (1940) described a species of eye-less sole, Typhlachirus elongatus, based on two specimens collected from estuarine waters of the Mekong River. Subsequently, this species was reassigned to the genus Brachirus (Munroe 2000, Kottelat 2013). However, in a recent revision of the genus Typhlachirus, Evseenko and Bolshakov (2018) provided evidence that this species belongs in Typhlachirus. This taxonomic arrangement is followed herein.

Recent genetic analysis has shown that the Atlantic and Pacific subpopulations of H. steindachneri should be treated as different species. However, a distinctive name has not been attributed to the Atlantic subpopulation as of yet (Rocha et al. 2008).

Whitehead and Rodriguez (1998) consider the population of the Pacific coast of Baja California to be a different species, Anchovia magdalenae; however, this species is currently considered to be a synonym of A. macrolepidota in the Catalog of Fishes (Eschmeyer et al. 2019). Therefore, for the purposes of this Red List assessment, all records of A. magdalenae will be considered to be A. macrolepidota.

This species has previously been identified as Gerres simillimus, however, G. simillimus occurs in the eastern Pacific (Robertson 2006) and Gerres cinereus in the western Atlantic is considered a distinct species.
Western Atlantic subpopulations are now recognized as a separate species (Ophioblennius macclurei).
The western Atlantic subpopulation was described as H. pseudoaequipinnis (Bath 1994).

Acanthemblemaria macrospilus, which formerly included A. hastingsi, was first described as a subspecies of A. hancocki by Brock (1940). Stephens (1963) elevated it to species and reported that its range included the Gulf of California, the coast of southwestern Mexico, Isla del Coco, and Islas Revillagigedo (Lin and Galland 2010). The Isla del Coco population was later described as A. atrata, and the Islas Revillagigedo population was described as A. mangognatha (Hastings and Robertson 1999).
Further taxonomic study is required to determine the status of the eastern Atlantic populations (J.T. Williams pers. comm. 2014).
Phylogenetic analysis has placed this species within the genus Eucinostomus (Chen et al. 2007).
This species was recently re-described following a split to Acyrtus lanthanum (Conway et al. 2014).
This may be a species complex of several species.

This is likely a species complex (Bohlke and Robins 1969).

A revision of the Acyrtops genus is currently under way. Due to questions surrounding the validity of Acyrtops amplicirrus (a very similar species), the distribution of A. beryllinus is not clearly understood at this time (K. Conway pers. comm. 2015).

Robertson and K. Conway pers. comm. 2014).

This species is sometimes misidentified as Coryphopterus tortugae or C. venezuelae. Furthermore, although genetically distinct, C. glaucofraenum and C. venezuelae are extremely similar (Baldwin et al. 2009).
Older records of Coryphopterus in the western Atlantic may need to be verified as the genus has recently been revised (Baldwin et al. 2009).
This species has been confused with C. fasciatus (Gilbert and Randall in Gilbert and Kelso 1971).
This species has been confused with Ctenogobius pseudofasciatus in the past (Gilbert and Randall 1979).
Colin (2010) recognized that this may be a species complex of three to five species. Victor (2014) described the Cayman form as E. cayman.

This species is positively known from Bahamas. The different colour morph in the Cayman Islands, believed to be an undescribed species (Colin 2010), is E. cayman (Victor 2014). For this assessment, we consider only the Bahamas distribution for this species.

Records of this species from Panama refer to Tigrigobius panamensis (Victor 2010). Records from Utila island (Honduras) refer to Tigrigobius rubrigenis (Victor 2010). Much of the literature recognizes the genus Elacatinus with two subgenera, Elacatinus and Tigrigobius. As such, this species may be referred to in the literature as Elacatinus multifasciatus.
Much of the literature recognizes the genus Elacatinus with two subgenera, Elacatinus and Tigrigobius. As such, this species is often referred to in the literature as Elacatinus macrodon.
Much of the literature recognizes the genus Elacatinus with two subgenera: Elacatinus and Tigrigobius. As such, this species is often referred to in the literature as Elacatinus saucrus.
This is thought to be a species complex with two distinct colour morphs (Colin 2010).
This species is likely comprised of a complex of two (Colin 2010).
Elacatinus lobeli was previously misidentified as E. oceanops (Randall and Colin 2009).

Subpopulations from Trindade Island and Fernando de Noronha Archipelago, Brazil have been designated two new species, Elacatinus phthirophagus (Sazima, Carvalho-Filho & Sazima 2008) and Elacatinus pridisi (Guimarães, Gasparini & Rocha 2004).

This species is found in three colour morphs, a yellow-blue, a yellow and a white form which may represent three separate species (Colin 2010). The very similar cryptic species E. cayman has been confused with this species (Victor 2014).
Eleotris perniger has generally been reported as E. pisonis, but the latter is a continental South American species ranging only from southern Brazil to eastern Venezuela (Pezold and Cage 2002).

Unfortunately, members of the Eucinostomus genus are continually being misidentified. This species was once thought to occur in the eastern Pacific Ocean, but these specimens are now treated as E. dowii (Page et al. 2013). It may be conspecific with E. jonesi (Lee et al. 1980).
The name Eugerres awlae, which was once a synonym of E. plumieri, may be a different species. However, there is still some confusion on the validity and range of E. awlae.
The Atlantic and Pacific subpopulations are probably different species (M. Craig pers. comm. 2011).
This species is easily misidentified as Gobiosoma bosc.

This was formerly regarded as a species of Gobionellus. It is now know as the only species of Oxyurichthys in the Atlantic Ocean (Pezold and Larson 2015).
The species is valid. One of the paratypes (the cleared and stained one) may be a different species (J. Van Tassell pers. comm. 2011).
This species is valid, however, the genus may not be monophyletic.

Taxonomic relations between P. helenae and P. randalli need further clarification with sampling and barcoding of specimens from a range of sites in the Greater Caribbean (R. Robertson and B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2015).
Western Atlantic species of this genus are in need of revision (E. Murdy pers. comm. 2009, F. Pezold pers. comm. 2010).
This species was once considered widespread. A recent review split this species into multiple species (Willliams and Tyler 2003).

The taxonomy of species in the Mugilidae family is complex, and under revision (Durand and Borsa 2015). This species is commonly referred to as Valamugil seheli in the literature. According to Eschmeyer's Catalog of Fishes, it is now valid as Crenimugil seheli.
This species better and correctly known as Yongeichthys nebulosus (H.K. Larson pers. comm. 2013).
This species is likely part of a species complex (Whitehead et al. 1988)

This species was described as a species of Akysis in the A. pseudobagarius group from the Mekong delta in southern Viet Nam (Ng and Kottelat 1998). Ferraris (2007) subsequently assigned this species and all other members of the A. pseudobagarius group to the genus Pseudobagarius.
The Brazilian population is genetically distinct and is being described as a different species by a Brazilian group (L.A. Rocha pers. comm. 2010).
Ongoing genetic studies indicate that this species belongs to another genus, as of yet undetermined (L.A. Rocha pers. comm. 2010).
This species as currently defined most likely represents two species: an Indian Ocean form and a west Pacific form (Allen pers. comm. 2010).

Unlike nearly all other members of the family, this species has non-pelagic larvae.  Therefore, many isolated geographic populations exist.  Genetic data indicates a complexity of populations and subpopulations.  Populations separated by as little as 30 km may have drastically different color patterns.  Currently, only a single species is recognized but future genetic/morphological data may result in several valid species.
This species has been sometimes confused with Amphiprion latifasciatus (G.R. Allen pers. comm. 2010).
The Azores Chromis (Chromis limbata) was long considered the same species as the Mediterranean Damselfish (Chromis chromis) (Wirtz 1994).
Stegastes partitus shows weak genetic differentiation across the entire Caribbean basin (Hogan et al. 2012).
This species is sometimes confused with A. chrysopterus.

Rivas (1960) considered Stegastes otophorus (Poey 1860) a junior synonym of S. leucostictus (Müller & Troschel 1848), but Topp (1970) redescribed S. otophorus as a valid species (Garrido and Varela 2011) and both species are considered valid in the Catalog of Fishes (Eschmeyer 2015).

This species is genetically identical to Stegastes sanctahelenae and Stegastes pictus, however, there are consistent colour differences between those species and they will probably retain species recognition (L.A. Rocha pers. comm. 2010).
The population from Cenderawasih Bay, West Papua (Indonesia), may be a separate species on the basis of genetic evidence.
The eastern Atlantic population is genetically distinct from that in the western Atlantic, but the distinction is below the species level (Rocha et al. 2008).
Clinus arborescens was formerly a variety of Clinus supercilious (Holleman 2012, Patzner et al. 2009).
Fricke (1997, 2005) placed E. pallidus into synonym with E. pusillus, but this synonymy is invalid (Holleman 2005).

Previously, this species has been treated as a synonym of Ruanoho decemdigitatus. However, molecular work (e.g. Hickey and Clements 2005, Feary et al. 2009) and ecological studies (Wellenreuther et al. 2008) prove that it is a valid species.

Two subspecies are recognized: Strongylura notata notata (Poey, 1860) from Cuba, Jamaica, Mexico, Belize, and Honduras and Strongylura notata forsythia Breder, 1932 from the Bahamas, Florida Keys, and southern Florida (Collette 2002).
The species was listed in the genus Notarius by Betancur-R. et al. (2007). A revised (unified) nomenclature for Ariidae is currently underway (R. Betancur pers. comm. 2014).

Three distinct lineages of this species have been identified through mitochondrial DNA analysis: 1) a northern type found from the Carolinas south to the Florida Keys, and off Panama City, Florida; 2) a southern form found in the Florida Keys, Yucatan, Belize and Puerto Rico; and 3) a third found exclusively in Trinidad (Chapman et al. 1999).

The genus Canthigaster is hypothesized to undergo fast morphological/colour differentiation and slow mtDNA evolution (Randall et al. 2008).

Genetic analysis revealed no difference between three similar Atlantic species, C. rostrata (Bloch), C. figueiredoi Moura & Castro, and C. supramacula Moura & Castro (L.A. Rocha, unpublished data).

In a study focusing on Colomesus pufferfishes, Amaral et al. (2013) produced evidence suggesting that Sphoeroides pachygaster be excluded from Sphoeroides based on the few species of that genus that this study sampled; further comparative investigations on the molecular and morphological features of all Sphoeroides spp. is highly desirable.
This species may be confused with Sciades couma, although it is much more frequent than S. couma.
The genus Sphoeroides may be paraphyletic, and is in need of revision (Amaral et al. 2013).
The taxonomy of H. bonariense requires review.
The possibility that a subspecies exists is likely as the population in the Gulf of Mexico has significantly fewer vertebrae than those in the Caribbean (D. Smith pers. comm. 2015).
Further study is needed to clarify the differences between this species and U. lepturus (Richardson) from the Indo-West Pacific.
Polydactylus oligodon is difficult to distinguish from P. virginicus (Feltes 2002, B. Smith-Vaniz and R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).
This species presents a superficial ressemblance to Facciolella oxyrhyncha.

This species is recorded here as Ariopsis felis (following Betancur et al. 2007, and Page et al. 2013). A revised (unified) nomenclature for Ariidae is currently underway (R. Betancur pers. comm. 2014).

This species can be distinguished from Lophogobius cristulatus by the lateralis (sensory pore) system (Bouchereau and Gros 2010). Lophogobius androsensis, currently considered a synonym of L. cyprinoides, should be further examined using the lateralis system and 18S RNA sequence (Bouchereau et al. 2010).
This genus is currently being studied using molecular techniques and many additional species are likely to be described and valid species may be redefined.
There are two subspecies recognized: A. l. lyolepis from Bermuda, the Antilles and Brazilian islands, and  A. l. continentalis from the continental shore (Robertson and Van Tassell 2015).
This species was recently split into two with Floridichthys polyommus Hubbs 1936 retained along the Yucatan and F. carpio restricted to Florida (Page et al. 2013).

Elops saurus was recently split into two largely allopatric species, E. saurus and E. smithi (McBride et al. 2010). In Florida waters, E. saurus and E. smithi may occur sympatrically at early life stages, though this does not appear to persist into the adult stage (McBride and Horodysky 2004). Elops saurus and E. smithi can be differentiated by myomere or vertebral counts; the more northern E. saurus is characterized by a higher count while the more southern E. smithi exhibits a lower count (Smith 1989, McBride and Horodysky 2004, McBride et al. 2010). These phenotypic differences are corroborated by genetic data (McBride et al. 2010).
This species is easily confused with Diapterus auratus.

The most recent revision of this species (Watson 1996) considers the species to occur on both sides of Central America, however, there is disagreement. For this assessment we consider only the Western Atlantic species to be Awaous banana. There has not been a genetic analysis that supports the synonomy of A. transandianus (Pacific) and A. banana (Atlantic). It should be noted that the common trend in gobioid fauna is that morphologically similar species that occur on opposite sides of the istmus of Panama have been recognized as distinct species based upon combined morphological and molecular analysis.

This species is regularly confused with other species. Its synonym, Awaous stamineus, is probably another species, endemic to Hawaii and distinct from Awaous guamensis (P. Keith pers. comm. 2011, Lindstrom et al. 2012). Further taxonomic work is needed to clarify this species.
Fin coloration is highly variable between individuals indicating that there are possibly more than one species represented by the population (Allen and Erdmann 2012).
The distribution of T. okinawae possibly represents a complex of several species (Winterbottom pers. comm. in Allen and Erdmann 2012, Winterbottom and Hoese 2015).
Byraninops annella Suzuki and Randall 2014 may be the same as this species.

The precise identity of this species has not been fully determined. It appears that the species, as recognized is a complex of related species, with some having been previously described. Many published images do not match type specimen. Records of this species have been confused with that of Cryptocentrus multicinctus Allen and Randall, 2011, and probably also with Cryptocentrus leonis (Smith, 1931).
This species has been confused with Gobiodon rivulatus, and there are two color forms of Gobiodon quinquestrigatus, which may indicate a cryptic species (Larson in press).

This is a senior synonym of Palutrus reticularis (Smith 1959), P. meteori (Klausewitz and Zander 1967) and possibly P. pusillus (Tortonese 1976) (H. Larson pers. comm. 2015). The entire genus is in need of revision.

The species has been confused with other species and some records are probably based on other species. Some species treated as junior synonyms are probably distinct species (Delventhal and Mooi 2013). Further studies are needed to fully document its identity and distribution.

Colour photographs from Bogorodsky et al (2010) show individuals from the Red Sea that have different colour patterns than those shown in Allen and Erdmann (2012) and Kuiter and Tonozuka (2011). Additionally, specimens from the Red Sea occupy a different micro-habitat (hard corals) to those individuals from Pacific localities, which are found on sponges. Further research is necessary to determine the taxonomic status of the Red Sea population.
The species as recognized is probably a composite of two or more species and is often misidentified as Istigobius nigroocellatus.

The species is often confused with Istigobius spence, which occur in the same habitat and some records are probably based on misidentifications of I. spence. Istigobius spence is more common on coastal reefs, while I. nigroocellatus more common on near shore reefs.
Further research is needed to determine if Ctenogobiops mitodes is different from this species.
Further study is required for the genus Stenogobius.

More research is needed on this species’ taxonomy and distribution, to distinguish it from Cryptocentrus albidorsus. Juveniles are often misidentified as C. albidorsus and it is likely that the two species are largely allopatric.
Amblygobius esakiae is likely closely related to A. nocturnus (Allen and Erdmann 2016).
Has been confused with Amblyeleotris wheeleri Polunin and Lubbock, 1977
There is a probable new species included within this species distribution that is under revision by Naomi Delventhal (Larson pers. comm. 2018).
Oxyurichthys guibei and O. visayanus have recently been synonymized with O. lonchotus (Pezold and Larson 2015).

This species, as currently considered, is widely distributed in the Indo-West Pacific. However, genetic analyses have suggested that there may be distinct species that have not yet been described within Trimma tevegae (Winterbottom and Hoese 2015). The populations in Australia, Indonesia, and New Guinea may retain the name Trimma tevegae (type locality: New Britain), pending further investigation to determine if populations in other areas are distinct species (Winterbottom and Hoese 2015).

This species is often confused with Cryptocentrus melanopus. Further work is needed to determine the distinctiveness of the two species. Also, preserved specimens of this species can easily confused with C. altipinna (Hoese 2019).
This species' taxonomy needs additional research, as there have been a number of misidentifications and this species may be a synonym of Cryptocentrus leucostictus.
This species is sometimes confused with Gobiodon quinquestrigatus (H. Larson in press).
This species has been misidentified as Bathygobius fuscus in Hawaii (Randall et al. 1993).
This species may be synonymous with Eviota susanae (Randall 2005); however as these two species have very different morphology and depth ranges, more research is needed to confirm this.

An in depth analysis of the various populations of this species has not been undertaken, and it remains possible or even probable that more than one species are masquerading under this name (Winterbottom and Hoese 2015).
This is considered to be a junior synonym of Palutrus scapulopunctatus (H. Larson pers. comm. 2015). The entire genus is in great need of revision.
The taxonomy within this genus is in need of revision.
There is potential confusion with Kelloggella oligolepis (H. Larson pers. comm. 2015).
This species is replaced by Eviota guttata in the Indian and west Pacific and as far east as Fiji (Greenfield and Randall 2010).
This species is often confused with Asterropteryx spinosa.

Species of the genus Arothron have been distinguished primarily on the basis of their distinctive colour patterns due to morphological similarities between species, however it is important to note that many species are highly polychromatic (Su and Tyler 1986). Arothron caeruleopunctatus was described on the basis of four specimens in 1994 (Matsuura 1994).
The economically important genus Takifugu has been recommended for further taxonomic studies based on morphological and molecular analyses (Yamanoue et al. 2008)

Puffers of the genus Lagocephalus are globally distributed in warm shallow waters. Lagocephalus wheeleri is considered a junior synonym of L. spadiceus (Matsuura pers. comm. 2014).

Some Brazilian specimens of Chilomycterus antillarum are intermediate in colour between the crisp, dark hexagonal pattern typical of the species and the dark background with vague lighter spots typical of C. spinosus spinosus. The significance of this is unknown, and further investigation is required (Leis 2006).

Records of Lutjanus russelli from the Indian Ocean are now identifiable as L. indicus, a recently described species (Allen et al. 2013).
Lutjanus lutjanus has been previously reported as L. lineolatus (Randall 2005).

This species closely resembles the congener Lutjanus bengalensis, and can be easily confused (Iwatsuki et al. 1999, Barman et al. 2014, Iwatsuki et al. 2016). Lutjanus octolineatus has been misreported as this species (Iwatsuki et al. 2016).
This species has been confused with Lutjanus rufolineatus (Randall 2005).
Some reports of this species may have been based on misidentifications of Lutjanus timoriensis.
This species is sometimes confused with Symphorichthys spilurus (citation send to Gina via Barry).
This species may be more widespread than is currently described, as it is sometimes confused in the literature with Macolor niger (Anderson and Allen 2001).

Paracaesio xanthura, a complex of variable populations, may compose a single or two (or more) species (Allen and Anderson 2001).

This species has been referred to as Lutjanus janthinuropterus and Lutjanus rangus (a junior synonym of Lutjanus bohar) by previous authors.
This species has been referred to as Lutjanus aya by previous authors, but Rivas (1966) concluded that Bodianus aya is not a lutjanid, but probably a sciaenid.
Records of this species from southern Japan and Hong Kong may have been confused with Lutjanus stellatus (Akazaki 1983).

This species closely resembles the congener Lutjanus kasmira, and can be easily confused (Iwatsuki et al. 1999, Barman et al. 2014, Iwatsuki et al. 2016). It has also been confused with L. octolineatus (Iwatsuki et al. 2016).
The recently described L. xanthopinnis has been separated from L. madras (Iwaktsuki et al. 2015).

This species has been confused in the east Asian region with Lutjanus ophuysenii. Lutjanus vitta is widely distributed in the Indo-West Pacific, except for the eastern Asian shelf. It is sympatric with L. ophuysenii in southwestern Taiwan and Hong Kong (Iwatsuki et al. 1993 - from Barry).
The population of this species in the Marquesas Islands shows significant genetic difference from elsewhere in the Indo-West Pacific (Gaither et al. 2010).
The name Etelis carbunculus has been wrongly applied to this species by some previous authors, including Fischer and Bianchi (1989).
This species has been referred to as Lutjanus chrysotaenia previously.
This species can be commonly confused with Lutjanus malabaricus.
This species has been referred to as Lutjanus amabilis by previous authors.
This species is sometimes confused with Symphorus nematophorus (citation send to Gina via Barry).
Two species, Plectorhinchus caeruleonothus and P. unicolor, have long been confused with P. schotaf (Johnson and Wilmer 2015).

Starksia atlantica has recently been shown to be a species complex. The original species has been divided into Starksia atlantica (known from Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), Starksia sangreyae (Belize) and Starksia springeri (Curacao) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Starksia sangreyae has been recently described. It was originally known as S. atlantica, now shown to be a species complex comprised of S. atlantica, (known from Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. sangreyae (Belize) and S. springeri (Curacao) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Starksia lepicoelia has recently been shown to be a species complex. The original species has been divided into S. lepicoelia (known from Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. weigti (Belize), S. williamsi (Saba Bank, Netherland Antilles) and S. robertsoni (Panama) (Baldwin et al. 2011). However, Baldwin et al. (2011) did not sample populations in the Gulf of Mexico. The taxonomic status of the this population needs to be confirmed with DNA barcode data (R. Robertson and B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2015).

Starksia weigti has been only recently described. It was previously known as S. lepicoelia, which is now known to be a species complex comprised of: S. lepicoelia (known from Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. weigti (Belize), S. williamsi (Saba Bank, Netherland Antilles), and S.robertsoni (Panama) (Baldwin et al. 2011). The taxonomic status of the Campeche Bank (Gulf of Mexico) population needs to be confirmed with DNA barcode data (R. Robertson and B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2015).

Starksia robertsoni has been only recently described. It was previously known as S. lepicoelia, now known to be a species complex comprised of: S. lepicoelia (known from Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. weigti (Belize) and S. williamsi (Saba Bank, Netherland Antilles) and S. robertsoni (Panama) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Starksia sluiteri has recently been shown to be a species complex. The original species has been divided into S. sluiterei (known from Curacao), S. greenfieldi (Tobago, Trinidad and Tobago) and S. langi (Belize) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Starksia greenfieldi has been recently described. It was previously known as Starksia sluiteri, now shown to be a species complex. The original species has been divided into Starksia sluiterei (known from Curacao), Starksia greenfieldi (Tobago, Trinidad and Tobago) and Starksia langi (Belize) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Previously Starksia langi was known as Starksia sluiteri, which is now shown to be a species complex. The original species has been divided into S. sluiterei (known from Curacao), S. greenfieldi (Tobago, Trinidad and Tobago) and S. langi (Belize) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

It was previously though that his taxon was likely to include two separate species with widely disjunct distributions - one in the Atlantic/Mediterranean Sea and the other in the west Pacific. However, it is now clear that this species is only present in the Eastern Atlantic Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea (R. Bañón pers. comm. 2014).
This taxon has a curious, disjunct global distribution, recorded from the Mediterranean Sea, Florida and Hawaii. Taxonomic research is needed.
Cottoperca gobio is almost certainly a synonym of C. trigloides (J.M. Díaz de Astarloa pers. comm. 2019).

North Pacific Spiny Dogfish Squalus suckleyi (Girard, 1854) has a rather long and convoluted taxonomic history. It was first described in 1854 as a separate species from the well-known Spiny Dogfish (Squalus acanthias) but was subsequently synonymyzed as the same species even though its life history parameters, meristics, morphometrics, and molecular data suggested otherwise. A comparative study of its morphometrics and meristics, as well as a molecular study on this species complex have revealed it to be distinctive from the North Atlantic and other S. acanthias forms elsewhere (Ebert et al. 2010).

Kaupichthys hyoproroides was previously known as a highly variable, circumglobal species. Recent studies show that the western Pacific distribution is K. japonicus and K. diodontus is known from islands of the central Pacific. The western Atlantic and western Indian Ocean distributions are currently in place for K. hyoproroides, however, these distributions may represent a cryptic species pair. Studies are underway to resolve this taxonomic issue. Until this is published, we accept current taxonomy of this species (K. Tighe pers comm. 2011).
This species is part of a complex found in the Indo-West Pacific.
Anarchias euryurus is a synonym of Anarchias longicauda.
This species may be part of a species complex with A. leucurus (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011).
Gymnothorax dorsalis was assigned to the genus Strophidon on the basis of molecular analysis and morphological characteristics (Loh et al. 2015).
Gymnothorax enigmaticus has been confused with G. patelli in the literature (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011).
More than one species may be passing under the name Gymnothorax eurostus; further research is needed (Smith 2012).
Enchelycore tamarae is now considered a junior synonym of Gymnothorax fimbriatus (Smith 2012).
This species has been confused with G. monochrous in the literature (D. Smith pers. comm. 2011).
This species has been confused with G. pseudoherrei in the literature.
Gymnothorax pescadoris and Muraena melanospilos are considered synonyms of Gymnothorax isingteena (Smith 2012).
Gymnothorax mindonoensis is valid as a synonym of Gymnothorax javanicus.
This species is sometimes confused with a number of white-spotted morays which require further study (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011).
Muraena similis and Gymnothorax mucifer are valid synonyms of Gymnothorax kidako.
Gymnothorax talofa is a valid synonym of Gymnothorax margaritophorus.
This species is very similar to G. fuscomaculatus, although G. marshallensis is not as widely distributed (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011).
Gymnothorax leucostictus is a valid synonym of Gymnothorax meleagris.
This species has been confused with G. reticularis (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011). The current anti-tropical distribution may be indicative of two distinct species. Further study is necessary.
This species is often confused with G. hepaticus (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011). Historical records may be questionable. Further study is needed to confirm the status of this species.
Rabula davisi is a valid synonym of Gymnothorax mordax.
Muraena euptera is a valid synonym of Gymnothorax nubilus.
Muraena tuhua is a valid synonym of Gymnothorax obesus.

The validity of this species has been questioned. For example, Nakabo (2002) suggests that it is a junior synonym of G. pseudothyrsoideus. However, it is treated as valid in Böhlke and Smith (2002) and Smith (2012), and thus is included as valid here.

Muraena atomaria, Muraena elegantissima, Muraena erythroptera, Gymnothorax hilonis, Gymnothorax pictus kowanensis, Muraena lita, Muraenophis pantherina, Muraena pfeifferi, Muraena polyophthalmus, Muraena siderea, Gymnothorax thomsoni, and Muraena variegata are valid synonyms of Gymnothorax pictus
This species is similar to G. burndti and G. ypsilon.

This species may be confused with other white-spotted eels. Gymnothorax leucostigma, Gymnothorax nirosus, Muraena shirleyi, Muraena mieroszewskii, and Lycodontis wooliensis are valid as synonyms of Gymnothorax prionodon.

Gymnothorax makassariensis is a valid synonym of Gymnothorax pseudothyrsoideus.
This species may be confused with other white spotted eel species.

Muraena troschelii, Muraena scoliodon, Muraena venosa, Muraena vermicularis, Muraena diplodon, Muraena chrysops, Muraena florisiana, Muraena modesta, Muraena ceramensis, and Thyrsoidea multifasciata are synonyms of Gymnothorax richardsonii.

Muraena acutirostris, Muraena agassizi, Muraena blochii, Muraena cancellata, Thyrsoidea kaupii, and Muraena valenciennii are valid as Gymnothorax undulatus.

Gymnomuraena fascia, Anarchias insuetus, and Anarchias vermiformis are considered synonyms of Uropterygius concolor. This species apparently occurs from the Red Sea and East Africa to Polynesia. However, this range may represent a species complex (Smith pers. comm. 2011).

The Hawaiian population, described as Uropterygius dentatus (Schultz 1953), is morphologically distinct from U. supraforatus (Smith 2012). Although U. dentatus is currently treated as a junior synonym of U. supraforatus, following Bölke and Randall (2000), further taxonomic work may recognize it as a valid species in the future (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2011, Smith 2012).

The subpopulations in the Atlantic and Pacific may represent two different species. More research is needed concerning their taxonomy.

Spelling of Gymnothorax rueppellii has been changed to Gymnothorax rueppelliae. Muraena interrupta, Gymnothorax leucacme, Muraena petelli, Gymnothorax signifer, and Gymnothorax waialuae are synonyms of Gymnothorax rueppelliae.

According to the results of a morphological study by Wiley (1986), the sister group of Fundulus plus Lucania is a group composed of the genera Adinia and Leptolucania. The genus Adinia was synonomized with Fundulus by Ghedotti and Davis (2013).

Bagre marinus is a species complex that includes two species, Bagre marinus sensu strictu and Bagre bahiensis (Betancur and Marceniuk pers. comm. 2011). This assessment refers to Bagre marinus sensu strictu. A revised (unified) nomenclature for Ariidae is currently underway (R. Betancur pers. comm. 2014).
This species was formerly placed in the genus Arius. The genus Carlarius was recently described (Marceniuk and Menezes 2007).

Cathorops spixii is often treated as the only coastal marine species in the genus from the western Atlantic. There are at least eight species widely cited in the literature as C. spixii. The taxonomic revisions follow Betancur and Acero (2005), Marceniuk and Betancur (2008), Marceniuk (2007) and Marceniuk et al. (in press). A revised (unified) nomenclature for Ariidae is currently underway (R. Betancur pers. comm. 2014).
Among the Cathorops species in the Atlantic, Cathorops arenatus is the most similar, and frequently confused with Cathorops spixii.
This is a newly described species (Marceniuk and Betancur 2008). A revised (unified) nomenclature for Ariidae is currently underway (R. Betancur pers. comm. 2014).

Chelon bispinosus and Chelon labrosus may be conspecific, but further review of the eastern Atlantic and Mediterranean populations should be completed before declaring synonymisation (Harrison in press). Heemstra and Heemstra (2004) describes the taxonomy of the Mugilidae family as confused and the genera as obscurely defined.

The taxonomy of species in the Mugilidae family is complex and under revision (Durand and Borsa 2015). This species has previously been considered a synonym of Liza tade (e.g.,Talwar and Jhingran 1991, Thomson 1997, Kottelat 2013). The relationship between these two nominal species requires further investigation, as does the potential for cryptic species within the genus Planiliza. At present, it is considered a valid species (Fricke et al. 2020), and based on the most recent molecular work, it belongs in the genus Planiliza. However, some authors continue to place this species in the genus Chelon (e.g., Suresh et al. 2018, Psomadakis et al. 2020).

The species Mugil gaimardianus was supressed. Many specimens misidentified as M. gaimardianus are actually M. rubrioculus (Harrison et al. 2007).

Mugil rubrioculus can easily be confused with Mugil curema. They are very similar morphologically, but separation is easier in fresh specimens due to coloration differences.  They are however clearly separated genetically both by karyotype and molecular analysis (Nirchio et al. 2005, Fraga et al. 2007, Gonzalez-Castro et al. 2009).
The taxonomy of species in the Mugilidae family is complex, and under revision (Durand and Borsa 2015).

There are several Gnathophis species in the area, and it is impossible to know which adult matches the holotype due to the poor condition of the type specimen (D.G. Smith pers. comm. 2012).

The Galapagos Shark is extremely similar genetically and morphologically to the Dusky Shark (Carcharhinus obscurus). These species share mitochondrial DNA haplotypes but are distinguishable based on single nuclear polymorphisms (SNPs) (Corrigan et al. 2017) and also occupy different habitats (insular vs. continental).
There is a single extant species in the family Mitsukurinidae.

Yano and Musick (1992) showed that morphometric characters used to separate Pacific Pseudotriakis acrales Jordan & Snyder, 1904 from Atlantic P. microdon de Brito Capello, 1868 did not differ significantly, and these authors confirmed P. acrales as a junior synonym of P. microdon. Pseudotriakis is thus a mono-specific genus.
There are a number of errors in the original description (Hulley and Penrith 1966) which led Stehmann and Krefft (1988) to provide a detailed and accurate redescription.

Squaliolus laticaudus is sympatric with S. aliae in some regions.

Etmopterus baxteri Garrick, 1957 is a junior synonym of E. granulosus (Straube et al. 2015). Etmopterus tasmaniensis Myagkov & Pavlov, 1986 is a probable junior synonym of E. granulosus (Weigmann 2016).

Based on geographical separation and differences in tooth row counts and coloration, Carvalho (1999) considered Narcine bancroftii and N. brasiliensis to be distinct species. However, intraspecific differences in tooth row counts among individuals of varying sizes were observed. Genetic analyses of Narcine specimens from throughout their range in the Western Atlantic Ocean are needed to confirm the presence of two species. Narcine bancrofti is a frequent misspelling of the species name.

Compagno (1999, 2005) reallocated this species from Bathyraja to the genus Rhinoraja but the validity of this move remains unconfirmed. Both are currently in use, until a definitive systematic revision of these genera is conducted.
The variability (morphological and ecological) reported for K. caucasica suggests that this is a complex of several species.
M. nonultimus (nape scaled) from Caspian basin, usually listed as a subspecies of M. batrachocephalus, is a distinct species. It does not enter freshwaters.

In the 2008 Red List assessment, a total of 75 extant and five extinct 'subpopulations' were identified across the natural range of O. nerka. In the 2011 Red List assessment, several of these subpopulations were further subdivided based on additional input from salmon specialists (Pacific Salmon Commission, PSC, and Fisheries and Oceans Canada, DFO), resulting in a total of 98 subpopulations, of which 93 are extant. The subpopulations in this assessment are considered independent and reproductively isolated from each other.

The assessors used a combination of ecoregional (i.e., marine and freshwater habitat-based) classification and the degree of genetic divergence between known spawning 'locations', using an FST value of 0.04, representing a threshold level of gene flow between putative 'subpopulations' of less than or equal to one effective migrant per year. The five extinct subpopulations were based on Gustafson et al. 2007. While the assessors acknowledge that it is not straightforward to ascribe demographic or geographic distinctness to a subpopulation based on observed genetic distances, they feel it is the most appropriate methodology given the scale of the assessment and the paucity of observations of stray rates among the spawning locations considered in this assessment.
Previously recognized as Pleuronectes glacialis (Kells et al. 2016).

Molecular studies have demonstrated evidence for the existence of  distinct northeast Atlantic and Mediterranean evolutionary lineages, which probably originated through allopatric  isolation during the  Pleistocene.  Some studies have suggested that these represent semi‐isolated species (i.e., independent lineages in which speciation remains incomplete)  rather than differentiated  populations of the same taxon. The two lineages hybridise throughout a post-glacial secondary contact  zone located in the Alboran Sea, with a sharp divide at the Almeria-Oran Front (AOF). The AOF serves as a barrier by separating colder, less-saline Atlantic water from the denser Mediterranean. This phenomenon has generated a supplementary layer of genetic subdivision between sea bass inhabiting the eastern and western Mediterranean. Additional genetic diversity has been detected within individual Mediterranean basins, e.g., the Adriatic and Levantine seas, and is potentially present in the Black Sea.
In need of critical taxonomic revision; several species seem to be confused under the name P. flesus.

There has been much disagreement concerning the relationships of the one family placed in order Mugiliformes (Nelson 2006). Although reasons exist for regarding mugilids as perciform, rather than being related to the Atherinomorpha, there seems to be insufficient reason to change the classification from that given in Nelson (1994), based on Stiassny (1993) and Johnson and Patterson (1993) (Nelson 2006). A recent molecular phylogeny of grey mullets by Durand & Borsa (2015) has erected the genus Myxus to Pseudomyxus.

Chelinus trilobatus is a misspelling of the species name that should not be used (FishBase 2008).

Synonymous with Coelorinchus labiatus, however C. occa may be the separate species found in the western Atlantic (Marshall 1973)

It is likely that this species represents a species complex with one or more distinct species in the Caribbean region.  The nominal species occurs in southeastern Brazil (J. Williams pers. comm. 2009).
