The taxonomy and key characteristics of Brama spp. are in need of review (FAO ECA guide in prep RL Haedrich).

This species is often confused with Ostorhinchus aureus (R. Fricke pers. comm. 2008).

According to Allen and Erdmann (2013), this species is valid as Ostorhinchus fleurieu.
Heteroclinus fasciatus is a synonym of Heteroclinus whiteleggii (Ogilby 1894).
Early records (before 1943) were recorded under Scomberomorus guttatus.

What is currently known as Acyrtops amplicirrus may be two distinct species; one from the western Caribbean and one from Florida. The differences between the two sub-populations are slight, and may be due to environmental factors; a synoptic study is needed to clarify the taxonomy of this (these) species (Johnson and Greenfield 1983). A revision of the Acyrtops genus is currently underway; some workers question the validity of A. amplicirrus and its distribution is not clearly understood as a result (K. Conway pers. comm. 2015).
There are multiple undescribed species in this group which may have been confused with this species (Moore, Polanco, Russell, McEachran pers. comm. 2013).

Formerly believed to have a widespread Western Pacific distribution but apparently restricted to southern Japan (G.R. Allen pers. comm. 2009). Populations from other areas are currently assignable to A. jenkinsi (Everman and Seale 1907).
Creediidae tauensis may be conspecific with Chalixodytes chameleontoculis of the western Indian Ocean (J. Nelson pers. comm. 2009). There is doubt as to whether this is in fact a valid species.
Potential taxonomic problem: Amphichthys hildebrandi (Breder 1925) may be a valid species, although Collette (2003) considered it as a junior synonym of A. cryptocentrus.
There is some genetic differentiation between samples from the Atlantic and those from the Mediterranean, but not at the species level (Vinas et al. 2010).

This species also seems to be sympatric with Macroramphosus gracilis around the world (Dyer and Westneat 2010). However, there is still some debate about the taxonomic separation of the two species (Granadeiro and Silva 2000). The latest research suggests that M. gracilis represents a different ontological stage of M. scolopax rather than a separate species (Robalo et al. 2009, Noguchi et al. 2015), and this approach is followed here.

However, Noguchi et al. (2016) have foreshadowed that it is likely two different species in the Atlantic and Pacific. Noting that M. scolopax was described from the Mediterranean and that M. gracilis was described from Madeira in the eastern Atlantic, there is probably an undescribed species from the Pacific. The description of this Pacific species of Macroramphosus may be forthcoming from Noguchi et al., but this needs to be confirmed with those authors.

This species has been divided into several subspecies (Shakhovskoy 2007): Cheilopogon pinnatibarbatus pinnatibarbus (Bennett 1831), Cheilopogon pinnatibarbatus altipennis (Valenciennes 1847), Cheilopogon pinnatibarbatus californicus (Cooper 1863), Cheilopogon pinnatibarbatus japonicus (Franz 1910), Cheilopogon pinnatibarbatus melanocercus (Ogilby 1885).

The temporal and spatial genetic structure of this species, or species complex, is still under debate, and presents challenges for fisheries management. Clupea harengus stocks have traditionally been delineated on the basis of differences in spawning behavior and meristic or morphological characters. However, there is little concordance between these characters and genetic differentiation (André et al. 2011, Ruzzante et al. 2006, Ryman et al. 1984, Clausen et al. 2007). Morphological differences may be expressions of phenotypic plasticity resulting from early ontogentic exposure to differing environmental regimes (Anokina 1971, Aneer 1985, Rajasilta 1992). The extent to which there is genetic differentiation between NW and NE Atlantic is unresolved. 

In the NE Atlantic, there is some structuring between the population in the English Channel and that found in the remainder of the North Sea (Mariani et al. 2005). Concordant structuring has been found between the North Sea and Baltic spawning populations, and it is hypothesized that the relatively low salinity in the Baltic Sea is driving this divergence (Ruzzante et al. 2006; Bekkevold et al. 2005; Mariani et al. 2005; Larsson et al. 2007, 2010). Spring-spawning populations and autumn spawning populations within the Baltic Sea appear to differ from each other morphologically (Heincke 1898) and genetically (Jøgensen et al. 2005); however, genetic variation within the Baltic Sea is generally low (Johannesson and André 2006). Additionally, there is structuring between the northern and southern populations within the largest, most commercially important stock, the Norwegian Spring spawning stock, which is found in the Barents and Norwegian Sea (Shaw et al. 1999, Reiss et al. 2009). 

The Baltic herring Clupea harengus membras is widely regarded as subspecies of the Atlantic herring Clupea harengus. Baltic herring as a subspecies includes populations of autumn-spawning herrings mainly in the western and southern Baltic Sea and spring-spawning herring mainly in the eastern and northern parts of the sea basin. There is wide overlap in the distribution of the different forms (HELCOM Red List Project). Differences between the two forms (spatial distribution, meristic and morphometric, temporal spawning) are not supported by genetic differentiation when using either allozyme or microsatellite markers. However, some studies employing high-throughput sequencing revealed high levels of genetic differentiation at loci which may under selection, which may suggest the existence of locally adapted populations within the Baltic Sea which are connected by some gene flow (Corander et al. 2013).
This species may be a junior synonym of Amblyeleotris delicatulus (Smith, 1958); However, Smith’s type specimen is not in good condition so this cannot yet be verified (H.K. Larson pers. comm. 2015).
Previously in Remorina, but is currently placed in Remora (Gray et al. 2009).
Closely related to Anampses lineatus from the Indian Ocean (Kuiter 2002).
Closely related to Apogon cyanosoma (Bleeker 1853). DNA studies are required to verify the validity of this species (G.R. Allen and O. Gon pers. comm. 2009).
Atherion elymus is comprised of three subspecies; Atherion elymus aphrozoicus, Atherion elymus freyi, and Atherion elymus asper.
Although in appearance this species resembles the juvenile Cirripectes polyzona, it is most closely related to Cirripectes filamentosus.

The Hawaiian population is likely a distinct species (Randall and Rocha 2008 submitted). Kuiter 2002 describes the Indian Ocean subpopulation as H. schwartzii (Bleeker 1847), but there is no formal authority for this.
This species has been described as belonging to a species complex. Other members of this species complex include Starksia ocellata, S. culebrae, S. brasiliensis, S. variabilis, and S. occidentalis.

Entomacrodus stellifer used to be considered to have two sub-species; Entomacrodus stellifer stellifer and Entomacrodus stellifer lighti, but Entomacrodus stellifer lighti is now considered to be a separate species.

This species was previously accessed as its synonym Antennarius analis (Schultz 1957). In their most recent revision of the family, Pietsch and Arnold (2020) resurrected the genus Abantennarius recognizing it is probably paraphyletic and further molecular analysis may lead to a future revision of its validity.
Specimens from the Marquesas Island lack the vertical black bars (Pyle 2001).
This species has formerly been included within Chaetodon modestus (now Roa modestus).
This species is a synonym with Hemitaurichthy multispinus. Hemitaurichthy multispinosus was named in 1975, H. multispinus was named in 1978. Hemitaurichthy multispinosus is the valid species name.

The taxonomic status of populations recorded from areas in the eastern parts of the range (e.g.the Marshall Islands) needs further research to better understand the presence of this species in these areas.
This species is easily confused with Heniochus diphreutes.
Closely related to Chaetodon decussatus and pictus (latter formerly regarded as a synonym).

The Red Sea population generally lacks the dark spot on the soft dorsal fin. This population has been described as the sub-species C. auriga setifer Ahl 1923. However most recent authors regard it a conspecific with C. auriga.
This species has formerly been included within Chaetodon modestus (now Roa modestus).
Was previously treated as a synonym of Chaetodon vagabundus Linnaeus, 1758.
Records in the Indian Ocean west of Cocos Keeling are based on its sister species Chaetodon falcula.
Pacific populations formerly referred to as Chaetodon trifasciatus are now considered to be distinct as Chaetodon lunulatus.

Chaetodon modestus is the oldest available name for this species. Sometimes it is broken up into three separate species, C. modestus has a broad Pacific Ocean distribution, C. jayakari is found in the Indian Ocean and the Red Sea and C. excelsa is found in Hawaii and Marianas Islands. Currently, all three species are placed under the genus Roa.
This species is frequently confused with Heniochus acuminatus.
This species has formerly been considered to be a subspecies of Chaetodon unimaculatus.

Chaetodon tinkeri is here defined as comprising the Hawaiian, Johnston Atoll and Raratonga populations. The taxonomic status of populations recorded from areas in the western parts of the range needs further taxonomic research.

Very similar to Prognathus carlhubbsi, which is found in the southern part of the eastern tropical Pacific region. Genetic and morphological studies are needed to confirm whether specifically distinct from P. carlhubbsi.
Widely cited in the literature as Chaetodon trifasciatus, a species now regarded as being restricted to the Indian Ocean and Coral Triangle.
Indian Ocean records west of Coco-Keeling, Christmas Island and Java are based on the sister species Chaetodon interruptus.
This species is often included within the genus Paracentropyge (R. Pyle pers. comm. 2009).
Specimens of this species may be the adult male form of Chaetodontoplus septentrionalis, or might possibly represent hybrids (Carpenter and Niem 1999).

The entire population in Bermuda, Florida Keys, and the east coast of Florida may consist of hybrids between this species and Holacanthus ciliaris (L. Rocha pers. comm. 2009).

H. bermudensis and H. passer may, in fact, be sister species (thus potentially breaking up the subgenera Plitops and Angelichthys) (Alva-Campbell et al. 2010)
Apolemichthys armitagei Smith, 1955, is a hybrid between A. trimaculatus and A. xanthurus (Pyle and Randall 1994).
Apolemichthys armitagei Smith, 1955, is a hybrid between A. trimaculatus and A. xanthurus (Pyle and Randall 1994).

Some populations (e.g. Fiji and Coral Sea) have a black marking on the soft dorsal fin and are sometimes referred to as a different species Centropyge woodheadi, however most taxonomists do no consider these populations to be a distinct (L. Rocha and R. Pyle pers. comm. 2009).
An unusually coloured population of what appears to be this species occurs at Rowley Shoals off Western Australia and may represent a distinct species (Debelius et al. 2003).
Indian Ocean and Pacific Ocean populations may represent separate species.
This species has previously been considered to be a colour form of Chaetodontoplus melanosoma (Steene 1978).
Populations from the Indian Ocean have slight colour differences and are possibly a distinct species (L. Rocha pers. comm. 2009).
Holacanthus ciliaris are closely related to blue angelfish Holacanthus bermudensis Goode, and colouration is the only reliable character to separate these species (Feeley et al. 2009).
The species Chaetodontoplus poliourus was recently separated from C. mesoleucus (Randall and Rocha 2009).

The Pacific and Indian Ocean population of this species may eventually be regarded as distinct species based on differences in colour patterns and potential genetic differences (R. Pyle pers. comm. 2009).
This species is often included within the genus Paracentropyge.
The mis-applied name Hyporhampus gaimardi has frequently been used for this species in the Persian Gulf and adjacent waters (B. Collette pers. comm. 2013).
The placement of this species within the genus Centropyge is uncertain (R. Pyle pers. comm. 2009).

The Pacific Chub Mackerel (Scomber japonicus) has a Pacific distribution,and is replaced in the Atlantic by Scomber colias (Scoles et al. 1998, Collette 1999). Microsatellite and mitochondrial cyt b confirm that Scomber australasicus and S. japonicus are also separate species (Tzeng et al. 2009). Scomber japonicus is apparently absent from Indonesia and Australia, where it is replaced by Scomber australasicus (Collette 2001). The population from the Red Sea and northern Indian Ocean (the Gulf of Aden and Oman) is Scomber australasicus (Baker and Collette 1998).
Confused with the eastern Atlantic T. belone until described as a distinct species by Robins and de Sylva (1963).
Before 1983, this species was sometimes confused with Grammatorcynus bilineatus (Collette and Nauen 1983).

Three species have often been confused with S. maculatus, namely: Scomberomorus tritor in the eastern Atlantic; S. sierra in the eastern Pacific; and S. brasiliensis in the Caribbean and along the Atlantic coast of South America.
Sometimes this species has been erroneously considered a synonym of the western Atlantic Scomberomorus maculatus.
This species has been erroneously considered as a synonym of Scomberomorus maculatus by many authors (Collette and Russo 1985).
Recent genetic information suggests that this species is one highly connected population worldwide (Garber et al. 2005, Theisen et al. 2008).

Literature records previous to 1978 for Scomberomorus maculatus from the Caribbean and the Atlantic coasts of Central and South America apply to Scomberomorus brasiliensis, which was previously considered as Scomberomorus maculatus by many authors (Collette and Russo 1985).

There is no genetic evidence in the mtDNA control region to indicate that the Atlantic (Istiophorus albicans) and Indo-Pacific (Istiophorus platypterus) Sailfishes are separate species (Collette et al. 2006). However, there are two distinct mtDNA clades, both evident in the Atlantic while only one is found in the Indo-Pacific (McDowell 2002). There is also no difference in pectoral fin length or in any other morphometric or meristic characters between Atlantic and Indo-Pacific populations of sailfish (Morrow and Harbo 1969, McDowell 2002).
This species has been described four times in three different monotypic genera.
In India this species was confused with Scomberomorus lineolatus until 1976 (Devaraj 1976).
Prior to 1960, many authors have used the name Auxis thazard as including Auxis rochei in the belief that there was only a single worldwide species of Auxis.
Auxis rochei rochei (Risso, 1810) is worldwide except for the eastern tropical Pacific where it is replaced by A. r. eudorax Collette and Aadland, 1996.

This species is frequently misidentified as juvenile or female of Coryphaena hippurus.

The specific name is sometimes misspelled as equisetis instead of equiselis (Gibbs and Collette 1959).

Two subspecies are recognized: Sarda chiliensis lineolata occurs from Alaska to the tip of Baja California and the southwest Gulf of California, and the Revillagigedo Islands. Sarda chiliensis chiliensis occurs from Ecuador to Chile (Collette and Chao 1975).
In Madagascar and East Africa, this species name has been used for Scomberomorus plurilinealatus.

Before 1960, many researchers thought that there was only one world-wide species in the genus Auxis, which was recorded as Auxis thazard (Collette and Aaland, 1996).

The species contains two subspecies;  A. rochei rochei (Risso, 1810) worldwide except for the eastern tropical Pacific where it is replaced by A. r. eudorax Collette and Aadland, 1996.
This species is now recognized as distinct from the Indo-Pacific Scomber japonicus (Collette 1999, Infante et al. 2007).
Before 1983, often confused in the literature with Grammatorcynus bicarinatus (Collette and Nauen 1983).
Aplocheilus blockii was described by Arnold (1911) from Sri Lanka.

Ambassis dussumieri Cuvier was described from Malabar, India (Cuvier and Valenciennes 1828). Although two species, A. bleekeri (from Indonessia) and A. denticulata (from Egypt) are placed under the synonymy of A. dussumieri, it is highly unlikely that these are conspecific. Further taxonomic studies, preferably involving molecular techniques, are essential.
Parambassis thomassi was originally described as Ambassis thomassi by Day (1870) from Calicut and Mangalore, India.
Parambassis dayi was originally described as Ambassis dayi by Bleeker (1874) from Cochin (Kochi), Kerala, India.

Robertson and Allen (2006) treat the Eastern Pacific population as a separate species. However, the taxonomy of this group is in need of revision and the Eastern Pacific population may in fact belong to the circumglobal species Lobotes surinamensis.

Frequently misidentified as Albula vulpes, an Atlantic species. It has also been previously identified as A. neoguinaica (a synonym of the Indo-central Pacific species A. forsteri). However, genetic data indicate the eastern Pacific form is a separate species (Colborn et al. 2001), for which A. esuncula is the oldest name. There is recent genetic evidence that this species may in fact represent two species: Albula esuncula from south of Mazatlan, Mexico, and a yet to be named Albula species from Southern California to Mazatlan (Pfeiler et al. 2008).
This species may have some taxonomic confusion with Centropomus armatus.
This species was previously considered as Eucinostomus argenteus.
This species has a disjunct distribution that may involve two species, one distributed in the Gulf of California and the other in southern Mexico.

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species in Kyphosidae, as well as one Neoscorpis, which is considered a distinct genus within Kyphosidae. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix. Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis. K. pacificus/sandwicensis is a synonym of K. elegans. Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there are in fact four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis/incisor, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens.

The juvenile of Opistognathus punctatus was described as O. mexicanus by Allen and Robertson (1991). Opistognathus mexicanus is considered the junior synonym of O. punctatus (Bussing and Lavenberg 2003).
This species is sometimes mispelled as Stathmonotus culebrae, but the original orthography is with an '-ai' ending.
Also known as Japanoconger proriger (Robertson and Allen 2006). Ophisoma prorigerum is an objective synonym of Ariosoma prorigerum, and is listed as valid but the genus uncertain.
Newly discovered species in 2005.
A recent study showed significant genetic structure within the species (Riginos and Nachman 2001).
Newly discovered species in 2005.
The Gruchy (1970) record of Prionotus loxias from the Galapagos is a misidentification of this species.

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species in Kyphosidae, as well as one Neoscorpis, which is considered a distinct genus within Kyphosidae. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix. Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis. K. pacificus/sandwicensis is a synonym of K. elegans. Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there are in fact four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis/incisor, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens.
Previously this species has sometimes been referred to as Caranx hippos.

This species may represent two species given that no records known between them. Proposed names are Xenistius californiensis from southern California to the Gulf of California, and Xenistius peruanus from Lobos Islands Peru to central Peru (Roberston pers. comm.).

Lythrypnus pulchellus was separated from L. rhizophora based on island vs. coastal distribution by Bussing (1990). However unpublished current molecular data indicates that they may be the same species.
Springer (1958) recognized two subspecies: Malacoctenus zonifer zonifer from Mexico, and M. zonifer sudensis from Nicaragua to Ecuador.
Most recently, Sciades has been used as the genus for this species (Marceniuk and Menezes 2007).
This species has been incorrectly reported as far north as Mexico (e.g. Nelson et al. 2004, ASIH fish names).

This species has been considered a synonym of Abudefduf concolor, but a recent molecular study by Lessios et al. (1995) confirmed that it is a separate species. It is closely related to A. concolor and is easily confused in the field during visual surveys. The distributions of the two species overlap between El Salvador and Costa Rica, and a combination of morphological and genetic comparisons throughout the ranges of both species are needed to establish the full range of each.
Sometimes incorrectly amended as Protemblemaria bicirris.

This species has been considered a synonym of Abudefduf declivifrons, but a recent molecular study by Lessios et al. (1995) confirmed that it is a separate species. It is closely related to A. declivifrons and is easily confused in the field during visual surveys. The distributions of the two species overlap between El Salvador and Costa Rica, and a combination of morphological and genetic comparisons throughout the ranges of both species are needed to establish the full range of each.
Springer (1958) recognized two subspecies: Malacoctenus margaritae mexicanus from the Gulf of California, and M. margaritae margaritae from the remainder of its range.
Original orthography is scudderii.
Separate species for Scorpaena mystes and S. plumieri is more commonly accepted.
This species is also known as Notarius osculus by some authors, but Arius osculus is the nomen dubium (Betancur and Acero 2004). Other generic names used for this species are Ariopsis and Aspistor.
Sciades has also been used recently as the genus for this species.
The form in the extreme southern tip of Baja is genetically distinct from the remainder of the forms within its range (Lin et al. 2009).

Pleuronichthys guttulatus was described by Girard (1856). This species was later placed in the genus Hypsopsetta by Gill (1863). Based on a cladistic analysis of morphological features, Cooper and Chapleau (1998) recognized Pleuronichthys as the appropriate genus for this species. This arrangement was confirmed in the molecular work of Vinnikov et al. (2018). Although some authors as recent as Kells et al. (2016) have continued to recognize Hypsopsetta as the appropriate genus, this species is treated herein as Pleuronichthys guttulatus following Cooper and Chapleau (1998).

Dawson (1975) recognized three subspecies: Dactyloscopus pectoralis pectoralis from the Gulf of California and outer coast of Baja California; D. pectoralis fallax from Sinaloa, Mexico to Ecuador, including Isla del Coco; and D. pectoralis insulatus from Islas Revillagigedos.
This species is also known as Eucinostomus californiensis, but E. gracilis is apparently the senior synonym.
This genus has undergone recent taxonomic revision in the Eastern Tropical Pacific (Miller and Stefanni 2001).
May include Heteroconger canabus in its synonomy.

Springer (1959) recognized the populations from Baja California / the Gulf and the remainder of the range as a separate subspecies, Malacoctenus tetranemus multipunctatus and M. tetranemus tetranemus respectively.
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus striatus to the genus Brockius.
This species is also more commonly known as Caranx caballus. This species is probably a junior synonym of Caranx crysos.
Gymnothorax equatorialis is similar, but has three pores below the eye, a narrower tail, and the spots at the rear of the tail are elongate and much larger than the eye.
Specimens from central Mexico have been assigned to this species, but require confirmation and are not included here.
Newly discovered species in 2005.

There are two described subspecies: Myxodagnus opercularis walkeri from the Tres Marias Islands and Costa Rica; and M. opercularis opercularis form from the Gulf of California and Islas Revillagigedos (Dawson 1976).
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).

According to Miller and Steffani (2001) there are two subspecies - Bathygobius r. longipinnis from the Revillagigedos and Tres Marias Islands, and Bathygobius r. ramosus from the remainder of the range.
There are two described subspecies: Malacoctenus hubbsi hubbsi occurs in the Gulf, and M. h. polysporosus occurs in central and southern Mexico.
Taxonomic studies are needed to confirm this as a single species.
Gymneleotris is feminine and should be 'a', not 'us' ending.
This species was synonomised with Elacatinus digueti by Hoese and Reade. According to Van Tassell (pers. comm.) this was in error and both are valid species.
Closely related to Rypticus saponaceus (Bloch and Schneider) from the western Atlantic.

Some authors (Hensley 1995, Evseenko 1999, Robertson et al. 2017) consider this species to be a possible senior subjective synonym of M. asaedae. Other authors consider M. asaedae to be valid (Castro-Aguirre et al. 1992, Bussing and López 1994, De La Cruz Agüero et al. 1997, Evseenko 1998, Amaoka and Imamura 2000, Nelson et al. 2004, Page et al. 2013). The most recent evidence (Robertson et al. 2017), based on both morphology and molecular evidence, indicate that M. asaedae is a junior synonym of M. dubiosa. {Ask RLU to merge M. asaedae into this account}
Letharcus opercularis and Letharcus pacificus constitute the new genus Paraletharcus (McCosker 1974).
Trachurus murphyi which occurs in the southern part of this region is the sister species of T. symmetricus.
More information should be obtained from Pietch and Grobecker (1987).
This species is also known as Mnierpes macrocephalus.
This species was previously considered to be a subspecies of the Atlantic species Fodiator acutus (Parin and Belyanina 2002).
Xyrichtys perlas is a synonym of this species.
Newly discovered species in 2005.

The H. rondeletii superspecies complex of the subgenus Danichthys is now recognized as containing four allopatric species: H. volador (western Atlantic), H. rondeletii (Mediterranean), H. gilberti (northern Pacific), and H. rufipinnis (Southern Hemisphere). The other two species, Hirundichthys marginatus (eastern tropical Pacific) and H. albimaculatus(west & central Pacific) are both distinct species in the subgenus, but are not part of the rondeletii superspecies complex (Parin and Belyanina 2002, B. Collette pers. comm. 2014).

Merluccius hernandezi can be a distinct species from ,i>M. angustimanus (Nelson et al. 2004) However, Lloris D., J. Matallanas and P. Oliver (2003) consider both species as the same. Further taxonomic research is needed.
This species can be confused with an undescribed congener known from Baja California, Costa Rica and Panama.
Also listed as Caranx otrynter.

This species is commonly misidentified as Anchoa panamensis (which occurs only in Panama Bay); thus most records of Anchoa panamensis north of Panama Bay refer to Anchoa mundeola (Palacios and Phillips 1984).
Species described in 2005.
Most recently, Sciades has been used as the genus for this species (Marceniuk and Menezes 2007). Further research is needed to confirm that this represents a single species.
Although Kailola (2004) treat this species as a synonym of Sciades hymenorrhinos, it is accepted here as Sciades dowii following Betancur-R. et al. (2007).

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species in Kyphosidae, as well as one Neoscorpis, which is considered a distinct genus within Kyphosidae. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix. Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis. K. pacificus/sandwicensis is a synonym of K. elegans. Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there are in fact four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis/incisor, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens.
There are two recognized subspecies: Dactyloscopus byersi heraldi, from Baja California; and D. byersi byersi from the remainder of the range.
It is possible that the southern range of this species may represent a separate, undescribed species.

This species is divided into three geographically isolated subspecies on the basis of morphological differences: one from central west Baja California and the Gulf of California (Lepophidium microlepis microlepis); one from northern Costa Rica to central Colombia (L. m. hubbsi); and one from southern Ecuador and northern Peru (L. m. inca) (Robins and Lea 1978). There is continued debate as to whether these subspecies should be recognized at the specific level.
This species was described in 2001.
This species seems to have two forms or subspecies: Harengula thrissina thrissina from the Gulf of California to Panama and Harengula thrissina peruana from Panama to Peru (Watson and Sandknop 1996).
Newly discovered species in 2005.
One form from California has been recognized as a distinct subspecies (Bohlke 1952).
This genus is in need of revision.
References to this species prior to 2001 are to Hyporhamphus unifasciatus which is a western Atlantic species (Banford and Collette 2001).
Genetic studies indicate difference between Gulf of California and coastal Californian populations.

According to van der Heiden et al. (2009), two very similar species, Citharichthys fragilis Gilbert, 1890, and C. gordae Beebe and Tee-Van, 1938, were originally described from the Gulf of California. The original description of C. fragilis was limited and no illustration was provided. Mussot-Pérez and van der Heiden (1985) recognized C. gordae as a valid species and extended its geographic range based on additional specimens; however, Castro-Aguirre et al. (1992) did not agree with this decision and treated C. gordae as a junior synonym of C. fragilis. van der Heiden et al. (2009) conducted a detailed study wherein they demonstrated that both species are valid. This decision is followed herein.

Molecular evidence has demonstrated that the traditional concept of this species comprises five distinct geographical lineages , one of which has been described as Aphanius almiriensis Kottelat, Barbieri & Stoumboudi 2007.
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006). Bodianus dictynna was long thought to be conspecific with B. diana but the two are separable on colour pattern (B. Russell pers. comm.. 2008).

Hemigymnus sexfasciatus is almost certainly a valid Red Sea endemic and sister species of H. fasciatus (Kuiter 2002). Color differences are significant and consistent and Kuiter's color photos make a convincing argument. H. sexfaciatus is not recognized by Parenti and Randall (2000) (J.H. Choat pers. comm.. 2008). A detailed comparison of specimens and genetic material is needed (R. Myers pers. comm.. 2008).
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).
This name has been wrongly used in the past for the Indo-West Pacific species C. batuensis (D. Pollard pers. comm.. 2008).

According to Parenti and Randall (2000), Julis ventralis (De Vis 1885), was determined by Paolo Parenti and Jeff Johnson of the Queensland Museum, and Thalassoma cupido bipunctatum (Vasiliu 1931) is a sub-adult of Thalassoma lunare.

This widespread species may consist of Indian and Pacific Ocean sister species. Although Parenti and Randall (2000) list this as a single species extending from the Red Sea to the central Pacific, Kuiter (2002) reserves the name marginatus for the Red Sea population of this species and identified the Indian and Pacific Ocean populations as Halichoeres lamarii and further suggests that the Pacific Ocean populations are Halichoeres annularis. Barber and Bellwood (2005) use molecular evidence to show that there are two clades in this species, Indian and Pacific Ocean, but did not discuss the Red Sea populations. No formal taxonomic resolution has been published.

For taxonomic treatment see Mabuchi and Nakabo (1997). This species has in part previously been identified as Pseudolabrus japonicus, a species now regarded as a nomen dubium by Mabuchi and Nakabo (1997). It is closely related and confused with P. eoethinus (B. Russell pers. comm.. 2008).

Halichoeres poecilopterus has often been used in literature in Japan, such as Kinoshita (1936), Okada (1962), Fukui et al. (1991), Kimura and Kiriyama (1992), Kobayashi and Suzuki (1994) and Miyake et al. (2008).

Parenti and Randall (2000) stated that Parajulis is a distinct genus from Halichoeres, although this has not been always followed by other authors.
For taxonomic treatment see Russell (1985).

There is some taxonomic confusion between the species under Xyrichtys and Iniistius. The genus Iniistius has been considered a synonym of Xyrichtys by some authors but it is now recognized as a separate genus, distinct from Xyrichtys (Randall and Earle 2002, Randall et al. 2002). Seventeen species are included in Iniistius and they are: I. aneitensis, I. auropunctatus, I. baldwini, I. bimaculatus, I. cyanifrons, I. dea, I. evides, I. griffithsi, I. jacksoniensis, I. melanopus, I. pavo, I. pentadactylus, I. spilonotus, I. trivittatus, I. twistii, I. umbrilatus, and I. verrens.
This species was previously known as Labrus bimaculatus, e.g. in Golani et al. 2006 (D. Pollard pers. comm. 2008).
Some records of this species from the Mediterranean Sea may have been misidentifications of Labrus viridis (D. Pollard pers. comm. 2008).

There is some taxonomic confusion between the species under Xyrichtys and Iniistius. For taxonomic treatment see Mabuchi and Nakabo (1997). This species has in part been previously identified as Pseudolabrus japonicus, regarded as a nomen dubium by Mabuchi and Nakabo (1997). It is closely related and confused with P. sieboldi (B. Russell pers. comm.. 2008).

This species was formerly lumped with Cheilinus fasciatus. The true fasciatus does not occur in the North Red Sea. Populations of C. fasciatus recorded from the Gulf of Aden, Socotra and NE Somalia are probably C. quinquecinctus, but this needs to be researched.

This species has in the past been confused with Thalassoma pavo, which occurs off the West African coast to the north of the Gulf of Guinea and in the Mediterranean Sea, and to which it is closely related (Bernardi et al. 2004, Costagliola et al. 2004). For taxonomic treatment see Russell (1988).
According to Randall (1999), Halochoeres bleekeri and H. tenuispinis are separate species. However, it is difficult to interpret survey data on this species previous to this change.

Halochoeres chrysotaenia is considered to be the senior synonym of H. vrolikii (Kuiter 2002). Based on type locality (Java) and photographs taken there (R. Myers pers. comm.. 2008). This needs to be checked for its relationship with H. richmondi and H. melanurus.

Although Halichoeres purpurescens has often been recognized as valid, we follow de Beaufort (1940) in regarding it as a synonym of H. leucurus. Labrus leucurus and Anampses moniliger are based on the figure and description of Seba (1761: 95 pl. 31) (Parenti and Randall 2008).

Russell pers. comm.. 2008).

There is taxonomic confusion between H. chrysotaenia in the Pacific and H. vrolikii in the Indian Ocean.

H. chrysotaenia is considered to be a synonym of H. melanurus, a W. Pacific species (J. Randall pers. Comm. 2008). This relationship was based on an initial phase specimen of H. chrysotaenia collected in Java near Jakarta. The initial phases of H. vrolikii and H. melanurus, both W. Pacific species, are nearly indistinguishable. H. melanurus is a Pacific species based on the terminal phase and H. vrolikii is the terminal phase of its East Indian Ocean sister species. Since H. melanurus is considered a Pacific species based on the terminal phase, it is unlikely that H. chrysotaenia is the initial phase of H. melanurus. This species requires genetic research to positively link the type material of H. chrysotaenia to either H. melanurus or H. vrolikii (R. Myers pers. Comm. 2009).

This species has been confused with the north-western Pacific species Coris musume, which occurrs in southern Japan, Taiwan and the Philippines. This latter northern hemisphere species is now regarded as a separate and valid sibling species (Kuiter 2002), even though it was synonymised with C. picta by Randall and Araga (1978).
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).
This species is replaced by Thalassoma grammaticum in the tropical Eastern Pacific.
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).

This species has only relatively been newly described (Randall 2003), and is closely related to Thalassoma jansenii (Bernardi et al. 2004). These two species may be confused. The molecular sequences of 16S rRNA in the two species are the same, though they differ in one nucleotide of the cytochrome b sequence (Bernardi et al. 2004). Although there are no significant colour differences between these two species, and they have overlapping scale counts, the former is most probably a separate and valid species (J. Randall pers. comm.. 2009). Therefore, there may be confusion over the identity of this species in previous distribution records.

Halichoeres sazimai, n. sp. is described from the Western South Atlantic. There has been some confusion with the naming of this species. Hector in 1884 named this species as Cymolutes sandeyeri after the collector F.S. Sandeyer, however, this was a misspelling of the collector's real name, Sandager. Since then, both the names sandeyeri and sandageri have been used by various authors, although Mr. Sandager in a paper in 1888 on fishes of Mokohinau Islands listed this species as Cymolutes sandageri. Randall (1999), noted that although the name sandeyeri is inappropriate, the rules of the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature indicate that this name correct. See also Parenti and Randall (2000). From Eschmeyer's Catalogue of Fishes, the current status is: Coris sandeyeri (Hector 1884). Sandageri should therefore not be used (K. Carpenter pers. comm.. 2009).

For taxonomic treatment see Russell (1988).
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006).
For taxonomic treatment see Gomon (2006). This species was previously confused with Bodianus vulpinus and B. oxycephalus (B. Russell pers. comm.. 2008).

There is some taxonomic confusion between the species under Xyrichtys and Iniistius. The genus Iniistius has been considered a synonym of Xyrichtys by some authors but it is now recognized as a separate genus, distinct from Xyrichtys (Randall and Earle 2002, Randall et al. 2002). Seventeen species are included in Iniistius and they are: I. aneitensis, I. auropunctatus, I. baldwini, I. bimaculatus, I. cyanifrons, I. dea, I. evides, I. griffithsi, I. jacksoniensis, I. melanopus, I. pavo, I. pentadactylus, I. spilonotus, I. trivittatus, I. twistii, I. umbrilatus, and I. verrens.
Described by Cuvier in Cuvier and Valenciennes (1829). Genus reviewed by Vari (1978).
Recently transferred from Neogobius to Ponticola.
May occasionally be confused with Bathypterois dubius.

According to Fernholm and Wheeler (1983), four specimens in the Naturhistoriska Riksmuseet (Swedish Museum of Natural History) are probably the original material examined by Linnaeus (1758) to describe the species and they should be accorded type status.

The western North Atlantic population was at one time assigned to a separate species, Myxine limosa Girard (1859), and Wisner and McMillan (1995) suggested a return to this practice based on differences in size at maturity (eastern North Atlantic are smaller) and colour differences in preserved specimens. In the absence of other supporting morphological data, these features seem insufficient to justify dividing the eastern and western Atlantic populations into separate species (Martini et al. 1998, Martini and Flescher 2002). More conclusive studies involving morphological and molecular data are necessary to resolve this taxonomic question.

Myxine ios is known from two populations as defined by Fernholm (1981). The Irish population is mainly known from Porcupine Seabight, southwestern Ireland (Fernholm 1981, Merrett et al. 1991, Priede et al. 1994). The West African population is known off Western Sahara, from Cap Boujdour to Cap Blanc (Fernholm 1981). Two specimens were recently trawled off Angolan waters and they present very similar characters to those of the Western Sahara population (Tweddle and Anderson 2008). The populations differ slightly in coloration (Fernholm 1981), and it is unknown if they may represent separate species.
According to Møller et al. (2005), some records of M. ios from the Denmark Strait (Fernholm and Vladykov 1984) and West Greenland (collected by Jørgensen in 2003) might belong to M. jespersenae.
This species is identified by Robertson and Allen (2006) as Gerres simillimus, which considers the Atlantic and Pacific species to be separate. However, it is also known as Gerres peruvianus.

Fernholm treats the genus Paramyxine Dean, 1908 as a synonym of Eptatretus Cloquet 1819 (Fernholm 1998, Fernholm and Quattrini 2008), while other authors treat Paramyxine as a valid genus (Wisner 1999, McMillan and Wisner 2004, Kuo et al. 2010). Eschmeyer and Fricke (2011) follow Fernholm's advice on this and place all Paramyxine species within Eptatretus. This results in some duplicate names: E. wisneri McMillan 1999 and E. wisneri (Kuo, Huang & Mok 1994) (formerly Paramyxine wisneri Kuo, Huang & Mok 1994); and E. fernholmi McMillan & Wisner, 2004 and E. fernholmi (Kuo, Huang & Mok, 1994) (formerly Paramyxine fernholmi Kuo, Huang & Mok, 1994). To resolve this issue, both E. wisneri McMillan 1999 and E. fernholmi McMillan & Wisner, 2004, as the more recent descriptions, need to be renamed.

The current IUCN Red List retains the genus Paramyxine until the above taxonomic work has been completed.

Fernholm treats the genus Paramyxine Dean, 1908 as a synonym of Eptatretus Cloquet 1819 (Fernholm 1998, Fernholm and Quattrini 2008), while other authors treat Paramyxine as a valid genus (Wisner 1999, McMillan and Wisner 2004, Kuo et al. 2010). To resolve this issue, both E. wisneri McMillan 1999 and E. fernholmi McMillan & Wisner, 2004, as the more recent descriptions, need to be renamed.

The current IUCN Red List retains the genus Paramyxine until the above taxonomic work has been completed.

Bdellostoma-hexatrema was briefly described by Müller (1836) as having six gill apertures on both left and right sides. Based on this character, he also described Bdellostoma heterotrema, which had seven and six gill apertures on the left and right sides, respectively. However, in some specimens of hexatrema, the last branchial duct is not confluent with the pharyngocutaneous duct on the left side. This is the case of the type of Bdellostoma heterotrema, which has six gill apertures plus the pharyngocutaneous opening on the left side.

In the second part of his work, Müller (1838) believed that all the species described by him in 1836, including Bdellostoma heptatrema from southern seas, were just simple varieties of Bdellostoma forsteri (Müller, 1836) (junior synonym of Eptatretus cirrhatus). Recently, the combinations Bdellostoma forsteri var. heterotrema and Bdellostoma forsteri var. hexatrema were treated incorrectly as original descriptions in Müller (1838) by Paepke and Schmidt (1988).

The species name was misspelled once by Wongratana (1983) as E. indambaryai in the species heading and indrambaryi in Table 1. This species is named after Mr. Boon Indrambarya, therefore E. indrambaryai is the correct spelling.

The name was corrected to Eptatretus laurahubbsae by Wisner and McMillan (1988). Morphological evidence suggests that specimens of E. laurahubbsae could be juveniles of E. carlhubbsi. Further analyses are necessary to confirm this suspicion.

The holotype of Myxine affinis (BMNH 1951.10.4.3) was examined, but it was not possible to take any measurement or count (except teeth), as the specimen was totally dried. Three paralectotypes of Myxine tridentiger Garman, 1899 (BMNH 1868.6.15.5-6) were recently examined and re-identified as Myxine affinis. They were formerly misidentified as Myxine australis by Günther (1870).

Muraenoblenna olivacea La Cepède (1803) from Strait of Magellan was placed in the synonymy of the younger Myxine affinis as nomen dubium by Wisner and McMillan (1995). It is an undoubted Myxine, but can’t be referred with certainty to any species due to the fact that La Cepède’s description was very short and no type material is available for examination.

Shimizu (1983) reported three specimens of an undescribed Myxine off Suriname at 310 m depth. According to Wisner and McMillan (1995), the short description given by Shimizu (1983) is very similar to that of M. mccoskeri, except by the color pattern. However, the colour described by Shimizu was based on fresh specimens, and therefore, is different from those preserved specimens described by Wisner and McMillan (1995).
The species name robinsi was corrected to robinsorum by Fernholm (1998).

Lepadogaster lepadogaster was separated in two subspecies (Brigg 1986): L. l. lepadogaster in the Mediterranean region only, and L. l. purpurea in the western Mediterranean and eastern Atlantic.

In 2002, Henriques et al. investigated the relationships between L. l. lepadogaster, L. l. purpurea and L. zebrina. They noted significant differences in microhabitat preferences and their breeding seasons between the two subspecies. They concluded that L. l. purpurea is a valid species, L. purpurea (Bonnaterre, 1788), different from L. l. lepadogaster, which is now designated L. lepadogaster (Bonnaterre, 1788). Lepadogaster zebrina was found to be a synonym of L. lepadogaster.
This species is said to be conspecific with Coregonus autumnalis, but is treated separately here. It appeared on the Red List from 1996 to 2006 incorrectly spelt as Coregonus artedii.

There are no recent synonyms. In terms of identification, juvenile spotted rays can be confused with the morphologically similar blonde ray (Raja brachyura) and thornback ray (Raja clavata). Some spotted rays have fewer spots that are concentrated in the centres of the wings and can be misidentified as cuckoo rays (Leucoraja naevus).
Species of the Acropomatidae family are ill-defined (FAO ECA guide in prep PC Heemstra).
Species of the Acropomatidae family are ill-defined (Heemstra in press).
This species is also reported as Gobius (Awaous) aeneofuscus (antiquated name).
Species-level identification of Arnoglossus is problematic and the taxonomy of this genus requires further clarification.

There are issues of taxonomic quality within the family Ammodytidae. Gymnammodytes capensis and G. cicerelus do not significantly differ morphologically and therefore, their status is uncertain. They were described as separate species due to differences in geographic distribution of regional populations, however a systematic revision is needed (Nizinski in press).

A second morphotype found in the Gulf of Guinea, with larger eyes and a narrower interorbital width, is currently considered, with some question, as part of this species but may represent another valid species, Halobatrachus conspicillum (Cuvier, 1829) according to Collette et al. (2006).

Three subspecies are recognized (Collette and Parin 1970, Collette 2003): Belone belone belone (Linnaeus, 1761) from northeastern Atlantic Ocean, Belone belone euxini Günther, 1866 from the Black Sea and the Sea of Azov, and Belone belone acus Risso, 1826 from the Mediterranean Sea and adjacent parts of the Atlantic, Madeira, Canary Islands, Azores, and south to the Cape Verde Islands.

Four subspecies are recognised:
  • T. a. acus (Lacepède, 1803) in the western Atlantic (Massachusetts, USA to Brazil) and east Atlantic (off Morocco and the western Mediterranean Sea);
  • T. a. imperialis (Rafinesque, 1810) in the Mediterranean Sea and Cape Verde Islands);
  • T. a. rafale Collette and Parin 1970 from the Gulf of Guinea; and
  • T. a melanotus (Bleeker, 1850) in the the Indo-West Pacific and oceanic islands in the eastern tropical Pacific (Revillagigedos, Clipperton, and Cocos).
There are three subspecies B. p. podas, B. p. maderensis, and B. p. africanus, and there some questions regarding the taxonomic status of these subspecies.
There is confusion as to whether C. rubescens is the true valid species name.

Morphological studies based on gill raker counts and head length supported the designation of two sub-species within Sardina pilchardus: S.p. pilchardus (Eastern Atlantic from the North Sea to southern Portugal) and S. p. sardina (Mediterranean Sea and Northwest African coast)(Parrish et al. 1989). Genetic analysis using nuclear micro satellites supports S. pilchardus as a single evolutionary unit with present day gene flow among subpopulations, with some weak but significant structuring best explained by an isolation-by-distance model (Gonzalez and Zardoya 2007). Sardina pilchardus is treated as a single evolutionary unit by fisheries managers, and the various stocks have been designated arbitrarily as magnitude of exchange between areas continues to be uncovered. This species does not appear to be as commercially important in the southeastern Mediterranean. Long-term changes in the environment are related to productivity of S. pilchardus and other sardine and anchovy species in the Mediterranean (ICES 2010).

Exocoetus obtusirostris is endemic to the Atlantic Ocean and showed no significant differences from different parts of this ocean. It was thought to occur circumglobally before it was split into three other closely related species (Parin and Shakhovskoy 2000).

This may represent a species complex (Tomio pers. comm. 2012).
Coelorinchus caelorhincus was formerly considered as having a number of subspecies, but those are here recognized as full species. Eschmeyer and Bailey in Eschmeyer (1990:70) changed the spelling of the name from Coelorinchus coelorhincus (or Coelorhynchus coelorhynchus) to Caelorinchus caelorhincus, based on their interpretation. Iwamoto (2008: xi) agreed with the “ae” spelling of the species name (i.e., caelorhincus) but disagreed with the use of that dipthong in the generic name. He considered “Coelorinchus” to be the correct spelling, but accepted that there is room for doubt and agreed that the International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature should be petitioned to fix the spellings of the generic and specific names (Iwamoto 2016).
Subpopulations south of Mauritania may represent another species; further taxonomic research is warranted (T. Iwamoto pers. comm. 2012).
This species is often confused with Nezumia aequlis.
Gadella maraldi is quite often misidentified as G. imberbis in tropical waters where G. maraldi probably does not occur (Iwamoto in press).
The subpopulation in the Gulf of Guinea may prove to be a distinct species Perisedion macronema (Cadenat, 1951).

Two subspecies are recognized, Scomberesox saurus saurus (Walbaum, 1792) from the Northern Hemisphere and S. saurus scombroides (Richardson, 1843) from the Southern Hemisphere (Hubbs and Wisner 1980, Collette 2004).
This species is often confused with P. impar.

After several years of confusion and mistake, the underwater identification of S. viridensis is now correct. Consequently, Dufour et al. (2007) gives accurate repartition of S. sphyraena and S. viridensis (P. Francour pers. comm. 2007).

Two subspecies are recognized by Collette (2003), T. crocodilus crocodilus (Peron and Lesueur 1821) from the Atlantic and Indo-West Pacific and T. crocodilus fodiator (Jordan and Gilbert 1882) in the eastern tropical Pacific.

This species has two subspecies, T. cristulata cristulata in the Western Atlantic, and T. cristulata echinata in the Eastern Atlantic. Specimens from Peru and Australia/New Zealand likely represent a different, distinct species or subspecies of a different species (Poss in press).
Subpopulations of this species should be further investigated as they may represent separate species (Tomio pers. comm. 2012).

Cheilopogon melanurus has been reported from the eastern Atlantic, from Senegal to Angola (Parin 1999). The eastern tropical Atlantic population was studied earlier by Gibbs and Staiger (1970). They discovered significant differences in pectoral-fin pigmentation and barbel structure between juvenile specimens of this population and similar-sized western Atlantic specimens and suspected, even not finding any distinctions between adults of both populations, the presence of yet undescribed species near the shores of West Africa. Parin and Belyanina (2000) reexamined three of these smaller eastern Atlantic specimens (USNM 203903, 203905 and 218912) and re-identified them as C. milleri (Gibbs and Staiger 1970). However, the western and eastern populations are so different in predorsal-scale number (25-33, mean 28.4, by 8 specimens, vs. 31-36, mean 33.7) that recognition of another species is highly probable (Parin in prep).

Parin and Belyanina (1998) separated the subspecies Cheilopogon furcatus furcatus from two new subspecies in the Indian and Pacific oceans. Another subspecies, C. furcatus neimani Parin & Belyanina occurs in the Indian Ocean and the third subspecies C. furcatus fisunovi Parin & Belyanina is widely distributed in the Pacific Ocean from western to eastern Pacific.
This species has been sometimes been recorded as E. indica, but all records of this species from the Atlantic are now known to be E. melanoderma (Swinney 1994).
This species has been previously recorded as Gigantura vorax but this is now regarded as a synonym of G. chuni.
Within the Mediterranean, this species has also been reported as Bathypterois mediterraneus, a junior synonym of B. dubius (Quéro and Ribes 1999).
The correct spelling for this species is Omosudis lowii (Günther, 1887), though other spellings are in use (Eschmeyer 2014). This species is also referred to as Omosudis loweii by FAO.

The name S. brasiliensis (type locality: Cape Frio, Brazil) has been generally used for this species.  However, genetic evidence indicates approximately 5-6% divergence in CO1 between eastern and western Atlantic populations, which suggests the populations on either side of the Atlantic are distinct species [Baldwin et al. in press]. Thus, the name S. parri Norman 1935 (type locality: Angola) should be applied to this species.

Gymnammodytes capensis and Gymnammodytes cicerelus do not significantly differ morphologically and therefore, their status is uncertain. They were described as separate species due to differences in geographic distribution of regional populations. A systematic revision is needed. (Nizinski in press).
Hemiramphus balao is frequently misidentified as Hemiramphus brasiliensis.

Oxyporhamphus micropterus similis is replaced in the Indo-Pacific by the nominal species Oxyporhamphus micropterus micropterus.  It is considered to be Exocoetidae by some authors (Collette 2002). The recent acceptance of Oxyporhamphus similis as a species by Eschmeyer should be reviewed (B. Collette pers. comm. 2012).
This species is sometimes placed in its own genus, Nanichthys (Collette 2004). It is also often confused as the juvenile form of Scomberesox saurus scombroides (Bianchi et al. 1999).

This nominal species, Etrumeus teres (DeKay 1842), was described based on specimens collected off New York. Whitehead (1985) included all populations of round herrings that were identified as this species in a single species, which was thought to be  globally distributed. However, in a recent taxonomic revision (Randall and DiBattista 2012), this nominal species, Etrumeus teres (sensu Whitehead 1985) was split into four distinct species: E. makiawa Randall and DiBattista 2012, restricted to the Hawaiian Islands; E. micropus (Temminck and Schlegel 1846), from Japan, and perhaps south to Indonesia; E. acuminatus Gilbert 1890 from the eastern tropical Pacific; and E. sadina (Mitchill 1814) from the northwestern Atlantic (with Etrumeus teres (DeKay 1842) as a junior synonym).

The taxonomy of the genus Nansenia needs revision, as there may be one to two hidden synonymies among the currently recognized species (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014). Further, the importance of vertebral counts to the correct identification of Nansenia species can be overlooked, resulting in misidentification of specimens in museum collections. These misidentifications have been perpetuated through checklists, and thus the true distribution of these species is often uncertain (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014).

The taxonomy of the genus Nansenia needs revision, as there may be one to two hidden synonymies among the currently recognized species (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014). Further, the importance of vertebral counts to the correct identification of Nansenia species can be overlooked, resulting in misidentification of specimens in museum collections. These misidentifications have been perpetuated through checklists, and thus the true distribution of these species is often uncertain (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014).
The Caristiidae family is in need of a thorough revision (Moore et al. 2003, Stevenson et al. 2016).

There are three co-occurring species of the genus Syacium in the western Atlantic. Identification of specimens to species is difficult because the species are morphologically similar and there is a significant amount of sexual dimorphism. Often times, these fishes are not identified to the species level and it is likely that in some studies catches consist of more than one species (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015).
Ophidion josephi is a senior synonym of O. welshi. The O. marginatum/josephi complex is in need of review (Lea and Robins 2003).
The genus of this species was recently changed from Carangoides to Caranx (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2012, Page et al. 2012).
There are no relevant taxonomic limitations.
Synodus bondi was recently resurrected from synonymy under S. foetens and both were redescribed by Frable et al. (2013).
Dornburg et al. (2012) proposed changing the genus of this species to Flammeo, however, this has not yet been generally accepted.
The genus of this species was previously Hypoatherina, but is now Atherina.
This species can be commonly misidentified as B. maculiferus (Weigt et al. 2012).

Many specimens historically identified as A. maculatus that have been found off the coast of Brazil around St. Paul's Rocks may have been misidentifications of A. strigosus, which has been recorded there based on molecular evidence (Bowen et al. 2001).
Dornburg et al. (2012) proposed changing the genus of this species to Neoniphon, however, this has not yet been generally accepted.
Dornburg et al. (2012) proposed changing the genus of this species to Neoniphon, however, this has not yet been generally accepted.
Lepophidium profundorum reported from the Southern Caribbean are referable to as L. cultratum (R. Robins pers. comm. 2013).
There are multiple undescribed species in this group which may have been confused with this species.
Page et al. (in press) accept the present taxonomic standing of Foetorepus agassizii.
In Brazilian waters, this species has been previously misidentified as Saurida suspicio (Carvalho-Filho et al. 2010).
There are multiple undescribed species in this group which may have been confused with this species.
Foetorepus agassizii and F. dagmarae were previously recognized as subspecies but have relatively recently been determined to be full species (Nakabo and Hartel 1999).
In the Gulf of Mexico, this species is known as the subspecies C. striata melana. In the Atlantic, it is known as C. striata striata (Roy et al. 2012).
The West Pacific population may represent another species.
Brotula barbata may be a species complex (Nielsen et al. 1999, de Paiva et al. 2010, R. Robins pers. comm. 2013).
This species may represent a complex of more than one species and further work is required to resolve it taxonomic status of S. suspicio and its distribution in the region (A. Polanco 2006).
Specimens of Opsanus dichrostomus may easily be misidentified as O. phobetron.

Species of the Ogilbichthys genus are easily confused with A. minyomma due to very similar morphologies and sympatric occurrences, therefore, extra care should be taken to determine an accurate identification (Moller et al. 2004).
The O. marginatum/josephi complex is in need of review (Lea and Robins 2003).

Böhlke and Thomas (1961) discussed geographic variation in Opistognathus aurifrons, especially with regard to color pattern. Although they noted that specimens from the Bahamas and Florida can be consistently distinguished from each other by the presence or absence of black markings on the head, their observation that these markings are inconsistent in Virgin Island specimens led them to synonymize Gnathypops bermudezi. Subsequently, Ho et al. (2012) examined population genetics and color pattern of four Caribbean populations of O. aurifrons; although each population exhibited high levels of genetic differentiation, phenotype variation and genetics were not congruent.

Specimens from Brazil, including Trinidade Island and Fernando de Noronha, possibly represent a geminate species of O. aurifrons. They cannot be distinguished genetically and have virtually identical color patterns, but differ in vertebral counts. The taxonomic status of the Brazilian population is presently unresolved.

There is some uncertainty surrounding the taxonomic status of this species. There are two recognized species: Bathyanthias mexicanus and B. cubensis. A third, not yet described species occurs in the southern part of the Caribbean, and it is unknown if this confuses the distribution of B. cubensis. However, specimens examined from Colombia by A. Polanco pers. comm. (2018) are recognized as B. cubensis. The genus Bathyanthias requires further taxonomic study and it is not known how the ranges of B. mexicanus and B. cubensis overlap in the Gulf of Mexico (R. Robertson pers. comm. 2018).
Some workers consider the genus of this species to be valid as Serranus, not Centropristis.

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.
This species should be regarded as valid as Ancyclopsetta quadrocellata, not as A. ommata (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015).

There are three co-occurring species of the genus Syacium in the western Atlantic. Identification of specimens to species is difficult because the species are morphologically similar and there is a significant amount of sexual dimorphism. Often times, these fishes are not identified to the species level and it is likely that in some studies catches consist of more than one species (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015).
Lonchopisthus meadi (Menezes and Figueiredo 1971) is a junior synonym of L. lemur (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2012).
Lonchopisthus linderi Ginsburg, 1942 is a junior synonym of L. micrognathus.
Common names and scientific names for non-Atlantic and non-South African localities are probably missapplied (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2013).

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species of Kyphosus in Kyphosidae, and the monotypic Neoscorpis. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix (Knudsen and Clements 2013). Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis (Knudsen and Clements 2013). Kyphosus sandwicensis is a junior synonym of K. elegans (Knudsen and Clements 2013). 

Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there may in fact be four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens. However, Sakai and Nakbo (2014) have presented an alternative view on the kyphosids occurring in the Atlantic.

Individuals from the western Indian Ocean appear to be genetically distinct from individuals from the rest of its distribution (BOLD; Ratnasingham and Hebert 2007); additional material is needed to determine whether these specimens represent two geographically isolated populations and to determine the limits of their respective distributions.

Lethrinus nebulosus may represent a complex of species, and further taxonomic work is required (K. Carpenter pers. comm. 2015). A cryptic species under L. nebulosus was detected in a study off southeastern Africa, but further study is required to resolve the taxonomy and distribution (Healey et al. 2018).
This name was frequently applied to what is now recognized as Lethrinus rubrioperculatus and its use prior to 1989 is probably not reliable (K. Carpenter pers. comm. 2015).

Morphological and genetic variability of the nominal species Lethrinus olivaceus support the presence of two distinct species (Lethrinus sp. A in the Indian Ocean and Lethrinus sp. B in the western Pacific Ocean) whose distribution ranges meet or overlap in the Coral Triangle (Borsa et al. 2013). This species complex will be treated as one species until further taxonomic revision has been completed.
The genus of this species was recently changed from Hemanthias to Baldwinella (Anderson and Heemstra 2012)

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.

Etropus crossotus was originally described from specimens collected in the eastern Pacific Ocean. Populations identified as this species from the western Atlantic, though morphologically similiar, have not been examined from a genetic perspective to determine if they are conspecific with the eastern Pacific populations (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015). For now, we continue to use E. crossotus for Atlantic populations.

The generic assignment of Pleuronectes oblongus Mitchill 1815 has been questioned. Some authors consider the appropriate placement to be in the genus Hippoglossina, while others consider this species to be a member of the genus Paralichthys. A comprehensive revision of these genera is necessary to resolve this conundrum.

There are three co-occurring species of the genus Syacium in the western Atlantic. Identification of specimens to species is difficult because the species are morphologically similar and there is a significant amount of sexual dimorphism. Often times, these fishes are not identified to the species level and it is likely that in some studies catches consist of more than one species (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2015).

The east and west Atlantic populations of N. usta were designated as separate subspecies by Schultz (1968) on the basis of minor morphometric divergences in preserved fishes (Nicholsina usta usta and Nicholsina usta collettei ).

Recent data show that these two forms are highly divergent genetically, more so than many of the Sparisoma species are from each other (Robertson et al. 2006). Hence, the east and west Atlantic forms represent a sister pair of species, N. collettei and N. usta, respectively (Parenti and Randall unpublished).

This species' taxonomy remains partially unresolved, with molecular studies demonstrating the current concept to comprise at least three potentially distinct taxa in the western Meditearranean alone. Some authors refer to the subpopulation inhabiting the Azov and Black Sea basins, including their affluent rivers, as S. nigrolineatus Eichwald 1831, but this view had not gained wide acceptance at time of writing. The subpopulation from the Caspian Sea basin is currently valid as S. caspius Eichwald 1831, however.

Acanthopagrus schlegelii was divided into two subspecies: A. schlegelii czerskii and A. schlegelii schlegelii. However, these subspecies have overlapping distributions (Akazaki 1962, Lindberg and Krasyukova 1969) which contradicts the criterion of a subspecies and suggests that these taxa belong to a single species (Mayr 1971, Dolganov et al. 2008). Further taxonomic work needs to be conducted for the A. schlegelii complex. This species is currently recognized as Acanthopagrus schlegelii.

Fundulus majalis is in the subgenus Fontinus (E.O. Wiley 1986). The Gulf of Mexico population of this form has often been referred to a separate species, F. similis. Ross (2001) and Relyea (1983) consider the Atlantic and Gulf populations to be conspecific. According to McEachran and Fechhelm (1998), there is an allopatric population of F. majalis in the Florida Keys and Florida Bay which may represent a distinct species. If F. similis is valid, then all Gulf of Mexico F. majalis should be considered F. similis (Duggins et al. 1995).
A recent taxonomic revision of this genus was conducted by Ho et al. (2010).
A subspecies, Hoplostethus mediterraneus trunovi, has been reported off of Namibia (Moore in press).
Howella atlantica is considered by some a subspecies of Howella brodiei Ogilby, 1899, although accepted by Eschmeyer (2015).
Previous to the description of Lepophidium cultratum many workers applied the name Lepophidium profundorum to the undescribed species (Rob Robins pers comm 2013).

Lepophidium entomelan and L. zophochir are similar, disjunctly distributed species. Further sampling in the Southern Caribbean may reveal an adjacency or overlap in distribution that will clarify relationships between the species (R. Robins pers. comm. 2012).

L. zophochir and L. entomelan are similar, disjunctly distributed species. Further sampling in the Southern Caribbean may reveal an adjacency or overlap in distribution that will clarify relationships between the species (Rob Robins pers comm 2013).
According to Ghedotti et al. (2015), this species should be placed in the family Lestidiidae.

Neobythites ocellatus was split into two species based on differences in color patterns, which resulted in the naming of a new species (Neobythites multiocellatus) and restricted the distribution of N. ocellatus to Brazil between 233-641 m depth (Nielsen et al. 2009).
Records in the northwestern Gulf of Mexico are suspected to be O. pantostictus due to taxonomic issues within the genus (R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).
Populations of this species in the Western Atlantic versus the Pacific may represent two separate species (Kotlyar 2001).
This species was previously known as Parexocoetus brachypterus or Parexocoetus brachypterus hillianus, but the Atlantic population was raised to species level by Parin (2003).
Before its description by Parin in 1999, it was usually misidentified as Prognichthys gibbifrons (Valenciennes 1846).

Previously known as Prognichthys gibbifrons throughout the Atlantic, but Parin (1999) described P. occidentalis for the western Atlantic population and P. glaphyrae for open waters of the tropical Atlantic, leaving the eastern Atlantic population to retain the name of Prognichthys gibbifrons.
This species had a genus change in 2016 according to Poulsen et al., and should now be considered as Monacoa grimaldii. need to request change in SIS

Lepadogaster lepadogaster was separated in two subspecies (Brigg 1986): L. l. lepadogaster in the Mediterranean region only, and L. l. purpurea in the western Mediterranean and eastern Atlantic.

In 2002, Henriques et al. investigated the relationships between L. l. lepadogaster, L. l. purpurea and L. zebrina. They noted significant differences in microhabitat preferences and their breeding seasons between the two subspecies. They concluded that L. l. purpurea is a valid species, L. purpurea (Bonnaterre, 1788), different from L. l. lepadogaster, which is now designated L. lepadogaster (Bonnaterre, 1788). Lepadogaster zebrina was found to be a synonym of L. lepadogaster.
This species was originally described as Dactylostomias ater.

Leptostomias gracilis, Leptostomias macropogon,Leptostomias longibarba, Leptostomias bermudensis, Leptostomias analis and Leptostomias leptobolus are probably synonyms of a single species. The entire complex needs a thorough study (Gibbs and Barnett 1990).
This species was first described as Echiostoma micripnus.
The Trachipteridae family needs revision (Olney in press).
The Trachipteridae family needs revision (Olney in press).
This species may be a misidentification of C. suttkus.
Heemstra and Heemstra (2004) describes the taxonomy of Callionymidae as unsettled and the genera as poorly defined.
Heemstra and Heemstra (2004) describes the taxonomy of Callionymidae as unsettled and the genera as poorly defined.
The Trachipteridae family needs revision (Olney in press).
The Trachipteridae family needs revision (Olney in press).

About eleven species are recognized in Watson (1992) included Chonophorus and Euctenogobius as subgenera of Awaous. Watson (1996) recognizes one species, A. (Chonophorus) lateristriga from West Africa.
According to Maugé (1986), reports of the Western Atlantic species Guavina guavina from Senegal are probably based on misidentifications of Bostrychus africanus
E. cyanescens, previously considered a synonym of E. nitidus, has recently been recognized as a valid species (Fricke et al. 2014 description of marisrubri).
Gobius strictus Fage, 1907 is considered a synonym of C. cruentatus according to Miller (1986) and Kovačić (2004).
Gobius pappenheimi is a questionable synonym of Porogobius schlegelii (Eschmeyer 2013).
This species is sometimes referred to as Argyropelecus olfersi.
Maurolicus muelleri is recognized here in the restricted sense based on the most recent review of the genus by Parin and Kobyliansky (1993).

Marceniuk and Menezes (2007) reviewed the phylogeny of the Ariidae and applied the genus Carlarius to this species. Historically, misidentifications of species in the genus Arius were common: for example, Golani and Sonin (1996) reidentified a specimen reportedly of A. thalassinus as A. parkii. Further, many records of this species have been reported as Arius heudelotii (Taylor 1990).
Preliminary molecular studies suggest that the genus Schedophilus is not monophyletic (Milana et al. 2011)

The family Cheilodactylidae has long been the subject of taxonomic debate along with its type species, Cheilodactylus fasciatus. Recently, Ludt and colleagues (2019) performed extensive taxonomic sampling analyzing morphological characters and molecular data and determined C. fasciatus is a valid species.

The taxonomy of C. niger does not appear to be resolved; while Melo (2009) recognizes seven species in the genus, Prokofiev and Kukuev (2009) placed many of these species in synonymy with C. niger, only recognizing two species in genus.
Barcode of Life Database (BOLD) lists Schedophilus labrinthicus a distinct species. Eschmeyer lists Schedophilus labrinthicus as a synonym (Milana et al. 2011).
The Trachipteridae family needs revision (Olney and Hartel 2016).
Breviraja marklei McEachran & Miyake, 1987 is now recognised as a synonym of Rajella fyllae (Dyldin 2015, Weigmann 2016, Last 2016).
The species that has previously been referred to as Squatina dumeril in the southern Caribbean has recently been described as Squatina david by Acero et al. (2016).

The characters thought to differentiate Zenion longipinnis from Z. hololepis are erroneous. The course of the lateral line is the same for both species. The isthmus of Z. hololepis is completely scaly, but scales were missing on the holotype from abrasion in the trawl. The membrane joining the pelvic-fin spine to the rays is fragile and easily torn in trawl-caught specimens (Heemstra in press).

Smith (1964) redescribed Cruriraja parcomaculata from the Eastern Cape of South Africa, assuming that the Cruriraja present in the Western and Eastern Cape was the same as von Bonde and Swart's R. parcomaculata from KwaZulu-Natal (Compagno and Ebert 2007). Smith also described C. triangularis from two specimens off Durban, as distinct from C. parcomaculata Smith, 1964. Re-examination of the type material by Compagno and Ebert (2007) and Aschliman et al. (2010) found that C. triangularis Smith, 1964 is in fact a junior synonym of C. parcomaculata (von Bonde and Swart, 1923), and concluded that the Cruriraja species common along the south and west coasts referred to as C. parcomaculata was an undescribed species. Aschliman et al. (2010) after a reviewing these species described a new species C. hulleyi while synonymizing C. triangularis as a junior synonym of C. parcomaculata. Therefore, information on the life history and distribution of C. triangularis prior to 2010 should now be referred to as C. parcomaculata, and life history and distribution information previously referred to for west coast C. parcomaculata is referable to as C. hulleyi. See Aschliman et al. (2010) for further explanation of this issue.
