Aphanopus intermedius is easily confused with A. carbo the areas where both species occur, because there are no conspicuous external characteristics that differentiate the two species (Nakamura and Parin 1993, Parin 1995). Biscoito et al. (2011), analysed both species in terms of genetic and morphological features and stated that they could not be correctly identified in a classical taxonomic way and a full separation of the two species could only be achieved through the use of a combination of morphometric and meristic characters in a numerical taxonomic approach.

Sequences of two markers (control region and cytochrome b) of A. intermedius from Angola were extremely similar to the A. carbo phylogroup corresponding with the southern coast of Pico Island, Azores, suggesting that the two species may exist in sympatry in the Azores (Stefanni and Knutsen 2007). Aphanopus carbo and A. intermedius differ by geographic distribution, maximum adult size and vertebral count; and external distinguishing characters are absent (Parin 1983, Stefanni and Knutsen 2007). A PCR-based method for the rapid identification of A. intermedius and A. carbo has recently been developed (Stefanni et al. 2009).
The narrow distribution of this species is uncommon for this family (Iwamoto pers. comm. 2013).
This assessment includes M. b. barbatus and M. b. ponticus.
The subpopulation in the Gulf of Guinea may prove to be a distinct species Perisedion macronema (Iwamoto pers. comm. 2013).

Craig and Hastings (2007) suggested changing the genus to Cephalopholis, but it remains under Paranthias for the purposes of this Red List assessment. Hybrid specimens of C. fulva and C. furcifer have been observed in the Brazilian oceanic islands of Trindade (Pinheiro et al. 2009), Atol das Rocas (Batista et al. 2012) and Fernando de Noronha (B. P. Ferreira and A.A. Bertoncini pers. comm. 2016) and in the North Atlantic from Cuba and Bermuda (Smith 1966, Bostrom et al. 2002). These were initially described by Poey in 1860 and 1875 as Menephorus dubius and M. punctiferus (Smith 1966, Bostrom et al. 2002).
This species is also known as Chelidoperca africana (Heemstra and Anderson in press, Iwamoto pers. comm. 2013).

Diplodus sargus as presently recognized is an assemblage of genetically closely related species whose current taxonomic assignments of species and subspecies are somewhat inconsistent and require further work (Summerer et al. 2001, Domingues et al. 2007). Pending more detailed population genetic work, the six subspecies of D. sargus, are retained in individual species accounts but are not separated in the parents species account.  

Two geographic subspecies of Diplodus sargus have been recognised in the European region: Diplodus sargus subspecies sargus in the Mediterranean; and Diplodus sargus subspecies cadeneti in the northeastern Atlantic - from the Bay of Biscay to Senegal, including the Azores, Madeira and the Canary Islands (Summerer et al. 2001). Only weak genetic differentiation is found for the European subspecies of D. sargus (Bargelloni et al. 2005) that is not associated with the transition between the Atlantic and the Mediterranean, contradicting the separation into distinct sub-species of the Mediterranean and Atlantic D. sargus populations, classified as D. s. sargus and D. s. cadenati, respectively (De la Paz et al. 1973, Bauchot and Hureau 1986).

Diplodus sargus requires taxonomic revisions and there may also be two forms in the Persian Gulf (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2013).

The Caristiidae family is in urgent need of revision due to confusion of the number of genera, species and distributions (Britz in press). This issue has recently been remedied by Stevenson and Kenaley (2011) and Kukuev et al. (2012).

This circumglobal species is restricted to subtropical waters, and consisting of a series of disjunct subpopulations, many of which until recently were considered to represent distinct species. Until recently, most of the literature in the eastern Pacific referred to this species are Seriola dorsalis.

Some workers consider Trachurus capensis to be a subspecies under Trachurus trachurus (Smith-Vaniz 2016). Bianchi et al. (1993) notes 'W. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. (1992) does not believe that Trachurus capensis is a valid species, but admits that an adequate series of this species along the coast of Africa is not available'. For the purposes of this assessment, it is considered a valid species.

Caranx hippos from the eastern Atlantic and Mediterranean was recently split into two species. A new species, C. fischeri, was recently described by Smith-Vaniz and Carpenter (2007). Caranx hippos and C. fischeri are largely sympatric, however it is C. fischeri which is found in the Mediterranean. There have been no confirmed records of C. hippos in the Mediterranean.
This species is likely to belong to a monotypic genus (B. Smith-Vaniz pers. comm. 2014).

The taxonomy of Trygonorrhina spp. was previously confused because of problems with type information (Last and Stevens 2009, White and Last 2012). Two similarly patterned species were considered allopatric off southern Australia, i.e. the Southern Fiddler Ray (Trygonorrhina fasciata) off southern and southwestern Australia and the Eastern Fiddler Ray (T. sp. A) (Last and Stevens 1994) off eastern Australia. Based on the locality and the illustration of the T. fasciata type specimen, it was identified as the Eastern Fiddler Ray, thus replacing T. sp. A as the name for the eastern species. The Southern Fiddler Ray, previously called T. fasciata, was renamed as T. dumerilii Castelnau, 1873 based on the oldest available name which could be accurately attributed to the southern species (White and Last 2012). 

The Magpie Fiddler Ray (T. melaleuca) is now considered to be a colour variant of T. dumerilii (Donnellan et al. 2015).

Trygonorrhina fasciata differs from T. dumerilii by having a diamond-shaped marking behind the eyes, which are parallel in T. dumerilii.

The taxonomy of Trygonorrhina spp. was previously confused because of problems with type information (Last and Stevens 2009, White and Last 2012). Two similarly patterned species were considered allopatric off southern Australia, i.e. the Southern Fiddler Ray (Trygonorrhina fasciata) off southern and southwestern Australia and the Eastern Fiddler Ray (T. sp. A) (Last and Stevens 1994) off eastern Australia. Based on the locality and the illustration of the T. fasciata type specimen, it was identified as the Eastern Fiddler Ray, thus replacing T. sp. A as the name for the eastern species. The Southern Fiddler Ray, previously called T. fasciata, was renamed as T. dumerilii Castelnau, 1873 based on the oldest available name which could be accurately attributed to the southern species (White and Last 2012). 

Trygonorrhina fasciata differs from T. dumerilii by having a diamond-shaped marking behind the eyes, which are parallel in T. dumerilii.
Records of this species from the Cook Islands and Society Islands (French Polynesia) may refer to an undescribed species (Woodland et al. 2001). Further taxonomic research is required.

There are issues of taxonomic quality within the family Ammodytidae (Nizinski in press). Prior to the revision by Sabatés et al. (1990), the accepted description of G. cicerelus included two species: G. cicerelus and G. semisquamatus.
There are issues of taxonomic quality within the family Ammodytidae (Nizinski in press).

Based on molecular data, Parablennius ruber is a sister species of Parablennius gattorugine, with which it forms a very differentiated clade within the genus Parablennius (Almada et al. 2005). Its validity as a separate species has been confirmed by Almeida (1982) and Bath (1982).
The subpopulations in French Mediterranean coastal lagoons may comprise a separate subspecies (J.P. Quignard pers. comm. 2008).
Syngnathus temminckii is a valid species, and the southern African portion of the previously assessed S. acus is in fact under that name (Mwale et al. 2013).
In Georgia and Romania (Black Sea), the subspecies M. m. euxinus (Nordmann, 1840) is recorded.
Herler et al. (2005) clarified the status of G. fallax Sarato (1889).
This species was previously (prior to 1992) identified as Gobius auratus (Risso 1810). This species is easily misidentified, especially with the yellow morph of G. auratus.
This species has been confused with Lebetus guilleti, Le Danois, 1913 (Herler and Kovacic 2002).
Stefanni et al. (2003) found that populations from the Atlantic and the western Mediterranean differs from those in the Adriatic (Venice).
Pomatoschistus norvegicus was previously considered a subspecies of P. minutus (P. minutus norvegicus) but has since been elevated to a valid species (Webb and Miller 1975).

Vanneaugobius dollfusi Brownell, 1878 was considered a synonym of Vanneaugobius pruvoti, however Pallaoro and Kovačić (2000) collected additional specimens that are thought to belong to the valid species V. dollfusi.
This species was classified as a subspecies (Molva dypterygia macrophthalma) but is now recognized as a species (Cohen 1990).

Previously two subspecies were recognised; Monochirus hispidus with a distribution in the Mediterranean and M. atlanticus with a distribution from Portugal to the Gulf of Guinea. Hoenywell et al. (in review) elevated a subspecies to species status. They considered M. hispidus to be a Mediterranean endemic and M. atlanticus to have a distribution from Portugal to Guinea not including the Mediterranean (Hoenywell et al. in review).
Ophioblennius steindachneri clippertonensis from Clipperton is now recognised as a distinct species (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Cirripectes heemstraorum is closely related to C. auritus, an Indo-Pacific species ranging from Kenya to South Africa to the Philippines and Line Islands (Williams 2010).
Although several geographic populations have been named as species, morphological and genetic data show there is one world-wide panmictic species (Gibbs and Collette 1967, Scoles and Graves 1993).

There has been taxonomic confusion and misidentifications between Epinephelus coioides, E. tauvina and E. malabaricus (Heemstra and Randall 1993). Therefore, historical data for E. malabaricus can be uncertain.
Prior to this species' formal description in 1991, it was identified as Epinephelus chlorostigma, particularly in India.

Recent genetic and demographic evidence suggests that the population of Cephalopholis hemistiktos in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden may be a distinct species from the population in the Arabian Gulf and Gulf of Oman (Priest et al. 2016).
The generic name of this species was changed to Hyporthodus by Craig and Hastings (2007), and the family name to Epinephelidae by Smith and Craig (2007).
This species has been confused with Epinephelus stictus in the western Pacific and with E. rivulatus in South Africa (Heemstra and Randall 1993).

Craig and Hastings (2007) changed the genus of this species to Epinephelus. However, until workers reach agreement on this taxonomic revision, Anyperodon leucogrammicus is retained here for the purposes of this Red List assessment.
This species can be confused with Epinephelus rivulatus, which is superficially similar.
Based on molecular phylogenetic analysis, Craig and Hastings (2007) included the species Aetheloperca rogaa within the genus Cephalopholis.
This species is sometimes misidentified as Epinephelus magniscuttis or Epinephelus heniochus.

Terapon jarbua was originally described as Scieana jarbua by Forsskål (1775) from Djedda, Red Sea. Golani and Appelbaum-Golani (2010) have suggested that the specimens from Red Sea and Mediterranean Sea differ slightly from the specimens collected from far east (Hong Kong and Japan) indicating that further molecular taxonomy research is necessary to clarify the identity of this taxon.

Gerres filamentosus forms part of a species complex and new species have been described (Iwatsuki et al. 2002), and some records of this species may be confused with these (Gerres infasciatus, G. macracanthus and G. microphthalmus).
Some authors have included Skipjack Tuna in the genus Euthynnus, but recent authors agree with its placement in the monotypic genus Katsuwonus (Collette and Graves 2019).
Hippichthys penicillus was originally described as Syngnathus penicillus by Cantor (1849) from Sea of Pinang (Penang), Malaysia.
There is a disagreement with the generic placement of this species. The species has also been confused with Liza macrolepis and some records may be misidentifcations.

In the past, there has been confusion from the use of the names D. acuta and D. elopsoides. Records of D. acuta in the eastern Mediterranean may refer instead to D. elopsoides (Whitehead 1985). However, this confusion has since been resolved (H. Hata pers. comm. 2017).
The record for Siganus spinus in Woodland (1984) is a misidentification of S. luridus (Randall 1995).
Caesio varilineata has previously been identified and recorded as Caesio caerulaurea (Carpenter 1988).
This species has been previously referred to in the literature as Formio niger.

Saurida tumbil has been widely misidentified in the literature, and has been misapplied to other species of Saurida. The true Saurida tumbil is probably restricted in range to India, the Arabian Sea, the Persian/Arabian Gulf and the Red Sea (B. Russell pers. comm. 2015).
This species is often misidentified as Herklotsichthys quadrimaculatus in the Arabian Gulf.

Based on a recent taxonomic study of the Antennariidae (Arnold and Pietsch 2012), both Antennarius and Antennatus are valid genera, but Antennarius nummifer is now valid as Antennatus nummifer. Specifically, it is stated that: "Antennatus was recovered nested within the Antennarius nummifer group, requiring reallocation of all members of the later, resulting in a much expanded Antennatus."
There may be several species within this complex (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
The generic placement of this species is under revision (H.K. Larson pers. comm. 2017).

Knudsen and Clements (2013) recently revised the family Kyphosidae. They determined that microcanthids, oplegnathids, kuhliids and terapontids are more closely related to Kyphosus than is Girella. Knudsen and Clements (2013) concluded that Girella, Scorpis, and Kyphosus should not be included within the same family and instead, be separated as individual families. Their study recognized 11 species of Kyphosus in Kyphosidae, and the monotypic Neoscorpis. Thus, there are 12 species total in the family Kyphosidae. 

Kyphosus lutescens and K. pacificus are now treated as synonyms of K. sectatrix (Knudsen and Clements 2013). Both K. incisor and K. analogus are now considered synonyms of K. vaigiensis (Knudsen and Clements 2013). Kyphosus sandwicensis is a junior synonym of K. elegans (Knudsen and Clements 2013). 

Before Knudsen and Clements (2013) it was thought that only two Kyphosids occurred in the Atlantic, but there may in fact be four species, K. sectatrix, K. vaigiensis, K. bigibbus, and K. cinerascens. However, Sakai and Nakbo (2014) have presented an alternative view on the kyphosids occurring in the Atlantic.
More taxonomic research is needed to clarify the status of the paratype specimen from off Madras, India (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
Nemipterus bipunctatus has been previously recorded as N. bleekeri, a junior synonym, in some reports from the Persian Gulf (B. Russell pers. comm. 2013)

There may be nomenclature implications for the Indian Ocean population of Nemipterus japonicus due to a 2.7% genetic difference between the western Pacific and Indian Ocean populations, but further investigation is needed (Ping et al. 2015). According to Hung et al. (2017), Nemipterus japonicus contains two distinct cryptic species, and further taxonomic work is needed.

Nemipterus randalli was not described until 1986 and it may previously have been confused with N. japonicus (B. Russell pers. comm. 2013). This species was identified as N. mesoprion in India prior to its description, but it continues to be misidentified as N. mesoprion by some workers to the present (B. Russell pers. comm. 2018).
Kuronuma and Abe (1986) mistakenly recorded Scolopsis bimaculata as S. phaeops [=S. frenata].
Scolopsis vosmeri is a complex of two or three species (two forms of S. vosmeri and S. torquata), and the taxonomic status of this complex requires further study (B. Russell pers. comm. 2018).
This species has been confused with Pseudochromis dutoiti in east Africa, and it is possible that it constitutes two species given future taxonomic work (Gill 2003).
Pseudochromis caudalis forms a species-complex (Gill and Zajonz 2011).
There is much taxonomic uncertainty surrounding this species (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2014).
The taxonomic status of Cynoglossus kopsii requires further study as there are several nominal species currently referred to under the name Cynoglossus kopsii (T. Munroe pers. comm. 2019).

Cantor (1849) considered Brachirus Swainson 1839 to be preoccupied by Brachyrus Swainson 1838 and proposed the replacement name Synaptura. Subsequently, Brachirus Swainson was determined to be a valid genus name (Jordan 1923). Bleeker (1875) distinguished Brachirus Swainson from Synaptura, but did not designate a type species. Later, Chabanaud (1928) restricted the name Synaptura to accommodate four nominal species of elongate soles, Synaptura albomaculata Kaup 1858, Pleuronectes commersonnii Lacepede 1802, S. lusitanica Brito Capello 1868, and S. marginata Boulenger 1900. 


Desoutter et al. (2001) commented that Synaptura sensu Chabanaud was not a valid genus name. In a revision of members of the genus Synaptura sensu Chabanaud, Vachon et al. (2007) also stated that Synaptura sensu Chabanaud was not valid. Based on the results of their study, the five nominal species (including Synaptura cadenati Chabanaud 1948) formally placed in Synaptura sensu Chabanaud were found to be closely related to Dagetichthys lakdoensis Stauch and Blanc 1964 and they transferred these species to Dagetichthys. This generic assignment is recognized herein.
Historically synonymised with M. longimanus, however clearly defined as two distinct species in the 1980s (Amaoka and Kanayama 1981).

Acentronura tentaculata subsumes A. breviperula. Dawson (1985) examined the specimens and concluded that there were no substantial differences, and thus synonymized the two under A. tentaculata. Western Pacific specimens were originally attributed to A. breviperula. Subsequent authors (e.g., Fricke 2004; Kuiter 2009; Fricke et al. 2011, 2014; Allen and Erdmann 2012) have all resurrected Acentronura breviperula in species checklists or picture guides with no justification.
There has been some confusion surrounding the correct name for this species. It is now placed as Paramonacanthus oblongus, separate from P. japonicus, by Gill and Hutchins (2002).

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.
This species is often confused with juvenile Thunnus obesus, which also has very long pectorals, but with rounded tips.
This is now considered to be a separate species from the Pacific bluefin, Thunnus orientalis (Collette 1999).

The Eastern Pacific population may be a distinct species, and further future taxonomic work is planned (M. Craig pers. comm. 2018). Craig and Hastings (2007) changed the generic name of this species to Hyporthodus and Smith and Craig (2007) changed the family name to Epinephelidae.
This species can be misidentified in Brazil as Mycteroperca rubra.

This species was originally described as Syngnathus dendriticum by Thomas Barbour in 1905. The genus Amphelikturus was subsequently described by Parr (1930), with this species subsumed within it. Dawson (1984) later subsumed Amphelikturus and Idiotropiscis as subgenera of Acentronura based on morphology.
This species should not to be confused with Briggs’ Crested Pipefish (Histiogamphelus briggsii), which is found in southern Australia.
This species was recently resurrected from synonymy under S. foetens (Frable et al. 2013).

This species was previously considered a synonym of E. plumieri by Deckert (1973), Deckert and Geenfield (1987), and González-Acosta (2005), because the original description was based on juveniles of this species.  Eugerres awlae has been re-described and considered a valid gerreid species from the western Atlantic by González-Acosta et al. (2007). It was recently reviewed in 2014 with conclusion that this species is valid (R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).

Both the specific and generic status of this species is under review and likely to change (K. Carpenter pers. comm. 2009).

The phylogeny of sparids, and the taxonomy of snapper in particular, has attracted considerable attention. In Australasia, snapper had previously been assigned to the genus Chrysophrys, formerly as Chrysophrys unicolor and more latterly as C. auratus (Paulin 1990). Paulin (1990) determined Pagrus to be the senior synonym of Chrysophrys, and re-described C. auratus as Pagrus auratus. In addition, he concluded that the species known as red sea bream in Japan, i.e. Pagrus major, was a conspecific and should also be re-described as P. auratus. Researchers in Japan, however, have not adopted this taxonomy (Jackson 2007).

Tweddle and Willoughby (1982) synonymised the Lake Malawi species M. nyasensis (Worthington, 1933) with M. livingstonii from the Rovuma River. This was based on the overlap of key characters, with the two key character differences used by Worthington (1933) shown to be invalid.Two specimens were collected by Tweddle and Willoughby (1982) from Lake Chilwa streams, i.e. the headwaters of the Rovuma River. These authors did, however, caution that only the small holotype of M. livingstonii was available from the type locality for examination and that "Further collecting from the Ruvuma system is needed for confirmation". The synonomy of the Malawi and Rovuma species therefore needs to be verified using modern methods of electrical organ discharge and genetics.
This species is also reported as Lophotus lacepedei (Quignard and Tomasini 2000).

This species is commonly confused with Laemonema barbatulum, particularly when small. This introduces uncertainty in assessing the distribution and habitat utilization of L. goodebeanorum (S. Ross pers. comm. 2018).
Previously considered conspecific with Hyporhamphus unifasciatus.
Further taxonomic work is needed on western Atlantic members of this family.

Neobythites ocellatus was recently split into two species based on differences in color patterns, which resulted in the naming of a new species (Neobythites multiocellatus) and restricted the distribution of N. ocellatus to Brazil between 233-641m depth (Nielsen et al. 2009).

Species in the genus Urophycis are difficult to identify, and therefore, determining the limits of individual species' distributions can be problematic. For example, Lemes et al. (2016) questions the presence of this species in the South Atlantic (Brazil, Uruguay and Argentina).

There is an ongoing discussion on the validity of the hamlets as biological species (Domeier 1994). Hamlet "species" are defined primarily on differences in color patterns. They are known to interbreed and hybridize freely with very little consistent genetic differentiation amongst them.

A recent taxonomic revision of Hippocmpus suggests that H. planifrons Peters 1877 and H. biocellatus refer to the same species. H. planifrons takes precedence, subsuming H. biocellatus as a junior synonym (Lourie et al. 2016)
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus kalisherae to the genus Gobioclinus.
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus filamentosus to the genus Gobioclinus.
Formerly this species was considered a subspecies of Malacoctenus hubbsi (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Previously this species was recognized as a subspecies of Omobranchus rotundiceps.
This species has three colour forms: frontalis and albicaudatus forms, occur throughout the species' range, but nigrovittatus form is unknown from the Red Sea and Gulf of Aqaba.

Until recently this species included Aspidontus tractus. The validity of A. tractus is questioned by Smith-Vaniz (1976) based on the fact that it is a mimic of Labriodes dimidiatus (Smith-Vaniz pers comm. 2009).
Parablennius tasmanianus postoculomaculatus was recently been elevated to a full species (Bath 2008).
Previously this species was considered a subspecies of Dactyloscopus byersi (Hastings and Springer 2009).
This species was formerly considered a subspecies of Malacoctenus margaritae (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Until recently, this species was recognized only as an allopatric subspecies of Plagiotremus laudandus (Hastings and Springer 2009).
This species was previously considered a subspecies of Stathmonotus stahli (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus bucciferus to the genus Gobioclinus.
Parablennius tasmanianus caledoniensis is a junior synonym of P. intermedius (Bath 2008).

Scartella cristata is generally recognized to be a species complex. Currently it is under taxonomic review. The eastern Atlantic and Brazillian populations may represent separate species (Williams pers. comm. 2009).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus gobio to the genus Gobioclinus.
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus guppyi to the genus Gobioclinus.
There are only two species in the genus Omox but they are easily distinguished (Springer 1981).
Formerly this species was considered a subspecies of Dactyloscopus pectoralis (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Previously, this species was considered a subspecies of Entomacrodus thalassinus, but is now recognized as a valid species (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Specimens recorded from Oman were tentatively identified and there is a possibility these could represent a different species.
Previously, this species was considered a subspecies of Entomacrodus stellifer, but is now recognized as a valid species (Hastings and Springer 2009).
A report of Meiacanthus lineatus from Sulu Archipelago (Smith-Vaniz 1976) was subsequently shown to be based on a misidentification of M. abditus (Smith-Vaniz 1987).
This species used to be considered as a subspecies of Alticus kirkii; it is now known as a distinct species (J.T. Williams pers comm. 2009).

Baldwin et al. 2011 revealed that most broadly distributed species of Starksia are comprised of a complex of species with discrete distributions. Assignment to a specific species requires barcode data for specimens outside the type locality. Since no barcode data are available for the Gulf of Mexico, all that can be concluded is that the population is a member of the S. nanodes species complex (B. Smith-Vaniz and R. Robertson pers. comm. 2015).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus albigenys to the genus Brockius.

Labrisomus nuchipinnis is likely a species complex and there is only one species in the Gulf of Mexico (J. Williams pers. comm. 2014). The holotype of L. nuchipinnis is from Brazil, so the name will change.
Blennius maoricus is now a junior synonym of Parablennius tasmanianus (Bath 2008).
Previously this species was recognized as a subspecies of Meiacanthus atrodorsalis (Smith-Vaniz 1976); it is now recognized as a separate species (Smith-Vaniz 1987).

Malacoctenus triangulatus is a species complex. There is at least one species in the Gulf. Further work is needed to determine how many species and where they are found, however, we assessed M. triangulatus as one species that is endemic to the Western Central Atlantic.

Acanthemblemaria spinosa is commonly misidentified as A. maria in photo guides (Humann and DeLoach 2002, Wilk 2003), and on the internet. The "Punk Blenny" (Wilk 2003) is actually A. maria. (R. Eytan pers. comm). This may also be a species complex.

Until recently this species included Aspidontus tractus. The validity of A. tractus is questioned by Smith-Vaniz (1976) based on the fact that it is a mimic of Labriodes dimidiatus (Smith-Vaniz pers comm. 2009).
Previously this species was considered a subspecies of Atrosalarias fuscus (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus nigricinctus to the genus Brockius.
This species was formerly considered a subspecies of Malacoctenus zonifer (Hastings and Springer 2009).
Many pictures identified as Acanthemblemaria maria in guidebooks and on the internet are actually A. spinosa (R. Eytan pers. comm).
Lin and Hastings (2013) reallocated Labrisomus haitiensis to the genus Gobioclinus.

Western Atlantic records of Tetrapturus belone through the early 1960s are of T. pfluegeri (Robins and de Sylva 1963). Tetrapturus belone is very close to T. pfluegeri (Collette et al. 2006, Hanner et al. 2011).

Previously thought to be endemic to the Mediterranean Sea, an International Game Fish Association record from Madeira (June 1980), outside the Mediterranean has been identified, based on a photograph, Tetrapturus belone; identification is uncertain, however expert opinion (B. Collette, J. Graves, J. Schratwieser pers. comm. 2013) is that the record is likely to refer to Tetrapturus belone.
Originally described in the genus Breviraja.

In some areas of the Mediterranean Sea (particularly along the Italian coasts) this species is probably misidentified with Raja montagui. Further investigation is required into this and morphometric and genetic studies are still in progress (Mancusi et al. 2005).
This species is most closely related to Hydrolagus affinis (Moura et al. 2005).

The genus Apristurus contains at least 32 described species and a relatively large number of potentially undescribed ones. Morphological conservatism and, until recently, a lack of objectively defined characters makes this one of the most taxonomically confused shark genera (Compagno 1984, Nakaya and Sato 1999).

Nakaya and Sato (1999) defined three species-groups within Apristurus: the longicephalus-group (two species), brunneus-group (20 species), and spongiceps-group (10 species). A. aphyodes belongs to the spongiceps-group, characterized by: a short, wide snout (prenarial length < 6% total length(TL)); 7 to 12 valves in the spiral intestine; upper labial furrows subequal to, or shorter than the lower furrows; a continuous supraorbital sensory canal.

This species may have been confused with one other, and possibly two other species, causing uncertainty in some of the literature. Pristiurus jenseni Saemundsson, 1922, is considered a junior synonym of this species. Recent analyses indicate that life-history data collected from specimens of Galeus murinus are incompatible with Saemundsson’s (1922) description of Pristiurus jenseni and data on Galeus murinus, provided in Magnússon’s (2000) fishery survey. Consequently, two possibilities require investigation: (1) The synonym P. jenseni is a valid species from Iceland, larger than G. murinus, and commonly confused with it and/or (2) G. murinus is in part confused in Magnússon et al. (2000) with a larger species of Apristurus present in Iceland. Molecular phylogenetic analysis of G. murinus was conducted by Iglésias et al. (2005) and Pristiurus jenseni requires critical taxonomic examination.
This species was previously referred to as Raja naevus. Early papers often confused Cuckoo Ray with Sandy Ray (Lecoraja (Raja) circularis).

Some authors (Ben-Tuvia 1990, Tinti and Piccinetti 2000) claim that S. aegyptica is a synonym of S. solea. Some other authors consider S. aegyptica a valid species (Desoutter 1997, Borsa and Quignard 2001, Vachon et al. 2008). It is currently accepted as a valid species (Eschmeyer 2014).

It is often confused with the sympatric Solea vulgaris (Quensel, 1806), a junior synonym of Solea solea (Linnaeus, 1758).
Although there have been concerns as to the taxonomic status of Eretmophorus kleinenbergi (Cohen 1986), it is currently considered a valid species (Eschmeyer 2014).

Miller (1971) described two subspecies of Chromogobius zebratus, Chromogobius zebratus zebratus (Kolombatović, 1891) and Chromogobius zebratus levanticus Miller, 1971. Ahnelt and Patzner (1996) showed that there is no real morphological differences in supposed subspecies populations of C. zebratus, and that separation into two subspecies is not justified.
The two juvenile specimens that are known for this species in the Mediterranean Sea, off Banyuls, France, may be juveniles of Buenia jeffreysii (Kovacic and La Mesa 2010).
It was inventoried under the name Oligopus ater in Risso (1810), and was recorded in Algeria under the name Grammonus armatus Dodelein (Dieuziede and Roland 1958).
Lipophrys basiliscus (Valenciennes, 1836) is a commonly used synonym in the literature.

All freshwater taxa of Proteorhinus were previously included under the name P. marmoratus, but morphological and molecular data show that the real P. marmorata does not enter pure freshwaters (Kottelat and Freyhof 2007).

As a result, in 2007 the freshwater taxa P. nasalis, P. semilunaris and P. tataricus were split from P. marmoratus and raised to species level. Nielson and Stepien (2009) identified a further freshwater species of the genus, which may be P. semipellucidus,  from the Caspian.Therefore any data on P. marmoratus may include data on these four taxa. Further work is required to clarify the taxonimic status of the Caspian Sea Proterorhinus.
Tripterygion tripteronotum was split into two distinct species, T. tripteronotum and T. tartessicum, based on genetic and morphological characteristics (Carreras-Carbonell et al. 2007).
Records of this species along the western coast of the Malaysian peninsula refer to Pennahia ovata (Sasaki 1996, 2001).
<span>
Johnius vogleri (Bleeker 1853) is a junior synonym of  this species.
This species was previously known as Johnius dussumieri in the Western Indian Ocean (Sasaki 1997).
Macrodon atricauda was revalidated by Carvalho-Filho et al. (2010). Macrodon ancylodon (Bloch & Schneider 1801) was used prior to 2010.

Records of this species from western Indian Ocean may represent a new, undescribed species based on genetic (Zemlek et al. 2009) and morphological data (Sasaki 2001). There is evidence of northern and southern subpopulations in the western Indian Ocean (Kiper 2014).

Smith and Heemstra (1986) placed Atrobucca marleyi in the synonymy of A. nibe, but Sasaki and Kailola (1988) regard the former as a separate species. There appear to be two genetic lineages of A. nibe in Taiwan (Lo et al. 2017; Wei-Jen Chen, National Taiwan University, pers. comm.); and South African A. nibe samples group together genetically, but appear to be a separate lineage from the Taiwanese Atrobucca spp (Wei-Jen Chen, National Taiwan University, pers. comm.). Thus either A. nibe represents a species complex and A. nibe in South Africa is a new species, or the South African specimens are another Atrobucca species - probably A. marleyi (Norman, 1922; Wei-Jen Chen, National Taiwan University, pers. comm.) Sasaki and Kailola 1988 were hesitant to designate Indian Bay of Bengal Atrobucca as A. nibe until more material was examined, as there were different gill raker and dorsal ray counts to East China Sea specimens.
In the Western Indian Ocean, previously referred to as Johnius amblycephalus, which only occurs east of Pakistan (Sasaki 1997); see also Lo et al. (2017)
This species may represent a new genus but further examination is needed (Lo et al. 2017).
Lutjanus indicus, previously recorded in the Indian Ocean as L. russellii, has recently been described as a new species (Allen et al. 2013).

Acanthopagrus latus was recently split in to five cryptic species: A. latus (distributed in east Asia), A. longispinnis (Valenciennes in Cuvier and Valenciennes 1830) (northern Gulf of Bengal Bay), and three new species, A. morrisoni, A. arabicus, and A. sheim. The five species can be distinguished from one another by the counts of dorsal-fin rays, pore lateral-line scales, scale rows between the fifth dorsal-fin spine base and lateral line, and other distinguishing morphological characteristics and body and fin coloration (Iwatsuki 2013).

Acanthopagrus latus was recently split in to five cryptic species: A. latus (distributed in east Asia), A. longispinnis (Valenciennes in Cuvier and Valenciennes 1830) (northern Gulf of Bengal Bay), and three new species, A. morrisoni, A. arabicus, and A. sheim. The five species can be distinguished from one another by the counts of dorsal-fin rays, pore lateral-line scales, scale rows between the fifth dorsal-fin spine base and lateral line, and other distinguishing morphological characteristics and body and fin coloration (Iwatsuki 2013).

Acanthopagrus latus was recently split in to five cryptic species: A. latus (distributed in east Asia), Acanthopagrus longispinnis (Valenciennes in Cuvier and Valenciennes 1830) (northern Gulf of Bengal Bay), and three new species, Acanthopagrus morrisoni, Acanthopagrus arabicus, and Acanthopagrus sheim. The five species can be distinguished from one another by the counts of dorsal-fin rays, pore lateral-line scales, scale rows between the fifth dorsal-fin spine base and lateral line, and other distinguishing morphological characteristics and body and fin coloration (Iwatsuki 2013).

According to Iwatsuki and Maclaine (2013) and Bogorodsky et al. (2017), Crenidens crenidens and C. indicus are two distinct species. Crenidens crenidens occurs from the Red Sea, East Africa along the east coast of Africa to Aliwal Shoal in South Africa. Juvenile C. crenidens have been found in Algoa Bay, South Africa (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). Crenidens indicus occurs from the southern Arabian Peninsula (occasionally in the Red Sea) to the coasts of Iran and Pakistan, including the Gulf. Bauchot and Smith (1984) reported C. indicus from India; however, C. indicus either does not occur around India or is extremely rare in the area (Iwatsuki and Maclaine 2013).

Trisopterus capelanus was previously considered the Mediterranean sub-species of T. minutus (T. m. capelanus) and has since been elevated to the status of a fully valid species (Mattiangeli et al. 2000, Delling et al. 2011, Gonzalez et al. 2012).

Despite the occurrence of separate sub-populations of plaice within the continental shelf populations, no significant differentiation was found using microsatellites (Hoarau et al. 2002, Was et al. 2010, Watts et al. 2010). Only mitochondrial DNA, which has a higher resolution, revealed that the North Sea-Irish Sea samples were weakly distinguishable from Norway, the Baltic and the Bay of Biscay samples (Hoarau et al. 2004). Clear genetic differentiation was found between the populations of Iceland, the Faroes, and the continental shelf of western Europe, that are separated by deep ocean channels (Hoarau et al. 2002, Was et al. 2010).
Acanthopagrus pacificus is recently described and was previously known as and confused with A. berda in the western Pacific (Iwatsuki et al. 2010), including northern Australia.

Differences between adults of Uraspis helvola and U. secunda are virtually impossible to distinguish. If subsequent studies indicated that these two nominal species are conspecific, the oldest available name is Uraspis helvola (Smith-Vaniz 1984).
Previously this species was considered a synonym of Chromis flavicauda (Smith-Vaniz and Collette 2013).
This species can be confused with Pseudochromis aldabraensis (Gill 2003).

Dawson (1985) recognizes three subspecies, Doryrhamphus excisus abbreviatus (from the Red Sea), D. e. excisus (pan-Indo-Pacific), and D. e. paulus (endemic to the Revillagigedo Islands off the west coast of Mexico). In contemporary literature subspecific designations are no longer followed but as Dawson (1985) recommended more research is needed to understand the systematic status of these populations. All are treated here as subspecies of D. excisus.
This species is closely related to Hippocampus histrix (Lourie et al. 2016). Molecular work is needed to confirm that this is in fact a distinct species.

Hippocampus abdominalis was first described from New Zealand and there is a question as to whether specimens from Australia represent the same species. Studies that have addressed this question do not support the existence of multiple species based on morphological, meristic, and genetic data (357 bp, cyt b) and show more variation within populations than among populations (Armstrong 2001, Lourie et al. 2016). There is some genetic divergence between Australian and New Zealand populations (814bp cytb, 624bp CO1, 404bp CR, plus four microsatellite loci), however, the level of divergence is low (1.4–1.7%, Nickel and Cursons 2012). Divergence within New Zealand is 0.7–2.2% without any clear geographical structure (Nickel 2009; Nickel and Cursons 2012). The name H. abdominalis takes precedence with H. agnesae and H. bleekeri being treated as synonyms. Hippocampus graciliformis is a juvenile specimen of H. abdominalis and therefore is also synonymized.
This species has often been misidentified as H. coronatus or H. mohnikei.
Lourie et al. (2016) placed H. grandiceps Kuiter 2001, H. hendriki Kuiter 2001, and H. multispinus Kuiter 2001 into synonymy with H. angustus.

Specimens from Lord Howe Island, Australia and New Caledonia that were previously tentatively assigned to this species have subsequently been described as Hippocampus jugumus and H. pusillus (Kuiter 2001, Fricke 2004, Lourie et al. 2016).
This species is named in honour of Hence Pontoh, an Indonesian dive guide. Lourie et al. (2016) placed Hippocampus severnsi into synonymy with H. pontohi.
The name Saurida undosquamis has been widely misapplied in the literature. The true Saurida undosquamis is probably restricted in range to northwestern Australia (B. Russell pers. comm. 2015).

Specimens nominally identified as this species from the Philippines and Indonesia are likely to be incorrect identifications of the similar species Sardinella lemuru (Willette and Santos 2013). 


Recent analysis of micro-satellite markers suggests genetic differentiation of this species between the Gulf of Oman and the coast of India (Sebastian et al. 2017). Subsequent sub-structuring of this species within India revealed genetic differentiation between samples obtained from Mumbai and Mangalore on the western coast of India and the samples obtained from the southwest and eastern coast of India (Calicut, Kollam, Trivandrum, Chennai and Vizag: Sebastian et al. 2017).
Chakrabarty et al. (2009) discuss generic placement of this species.
Along northern and western Australia, Arnoglossus aspilos is often treated as a distinct subspecies: Arnoglossus aspilos praeteritus (Whitley, 1950) (Hensley and Amaoka 2001).

The presence of Ilisha megaloptera in the Persian Gulf is questionable as it may be confused with  I. melastoma and I. compressa. Due to the uncertainty, reports from the Persian Gulf are not considered for the purposes of this assessment.

A recent taxonomic revision of the genus Brachypterus (Matsunuma et al. 2013) resulted in three valid species: B. serrulifer Fowler 1936, widely distributed in the Indo-West Pacific; B. serrulata (Richardson 1846), restricted to the northwestern Pacific Ocean; and B. curvispina Matsunuma, Sakurai & Motomura 2013, restricted to northeastern Australia.
Some individuals from Taiwan that have been identified as P. eriomma may represent a cryptic species (B. Russell pers. comm. 2018).
This species had been separated in G. aculeatus and G. gymnurus, but G. gymnurus is now treated as a synonym.

This genus was reviewed by Larson (2010), and the current limits of the species may comprise several taxa. Genetic and morphological studies covering all habitat types and geographic localities may help to clarify if there are cryptic species within R. bikolanus.
This species was submitted as Chonophorus macrorhynchus and subsequently corrected to Awaous macrorhynchus on recommendation of Paul Loiselle.

Ambassis ambassis was originally described as Centropomus ambassis by Lacepède (1802) from Réunion, western Mascarenes, southwestern Indian Ocean. Günther (1859), Talwar and Jhingran (1991) and Jayaram (1999) considered Ambassis ambassis as a synonym of Ambassis commersoni, which should be other way round (Anderson and Heemstra 2003). This widespread species is likely to be a complex and further taxonomic studies, preferably involving molecular techniques, are essential.

Dawson (1984, 1985) and most later authors consider Coelonotus to be a subgenus of Microphis based on morphology and meristics. Kottelat (2013) and Delrieu-Trottin et al. (2015) resurrect Coelonotus with no annotation or justification. See Hamilton et al. (2016) for a molecular phylogeny which includes this species.

Kuiter (2009) resurrects Microphis vaillantii Juillerat 1880 with no annotation or justification. That species was synonymized by Dawson (1984, 1985).
Numerous synonyms all outside the southern African region.

Elops machnata and E. hawaiensis occur sympatrically in the Western Pacific and possibly the Hawaiian Islands, so further research appears warranted. In the northern south China Sea, for example, Shao et al. (2008) claim that E. hawaiensis historically reported in the region are misidentifications of E. machnata. Wang et al. (2002) state that genetic data are now available to discriminate between E. machnata and E. hawaiensis.
It is very likely to be a species complex and work is ongoing.
This species consists of three subspecies: Sarotherodon melanotheron melanotheron, Sarotherodon melanotheron leonensis and Sarotherodon melanotheron heudolotii (Paugy et al. 2003).

Subgenus (Chrysichthys): C. auratus exhibits pronounced intraspecific variability, and a clinal series can be demonstrated in the size of the adipose fin and the number of gill rakers (Risch 1986): subpopulations from the Nile, Chad, Senegal and the upper reaches of Niger River, Comoe, Benue and Volta have a lower number of gill rakers and a larger adipose fin than the populations of the coastal areas from Liberia to Cabinda. The subpopulations of the middle and lower reaches of the Niger, the Comoe, the Benue and the Volta are more or less intermediate between the two. Therefore we consider all populations to represent a single, highly variable, species (Geerinckx et al. 2007).

Chrysichthys persimilis and Chrysichthys rueppelli are considered to be males of Chrysichthys auratus (Risch and Vreven 2007).
This species previously appeared in the genus Tilapia but is now considered valid in the genus Pelmatolapia (Eschmeyer et al. 2018).
This species previously appeared on the IUCN Red List in the genus Tilapia but is now considered valid in the genus Coptodon (Eschmeyer et al. 2018).
The taxonomy of this species has never been reviewed and it may represent more than one species.
The genus Eleotris is feminine, but Kottelat (1993) accepts acanthopomus as a noun, which does not need to change gender when combined with Eleotris.
The species in the synonymy were listed by Keith et al. (2015).
This species can be easily confused with Drombus halei which can co-occur (Larson pers comm. 2018).

The placement of this species in the Macrouridae is not supported by current morphological and genetic analyses; rather, it belongs in the family Bathygadidae (Howes and Crimmen 1990, Roa-Varón and Ortí 2009, Nelson et al. 2016).
Notopterus notopterus is a very widespread species that most likely represents a species complex.
Dayella malabarica was described by Day (1873) from erstwhile Malabar.

Oryzias dancena was originally described as Cyprnus dancena from Estuary below Calcutta, India by Hamilton (1822). While revising this genus, Parenti (2008) has placed several questionable synonym under this species. Therefore, this widespread species is likely to be a complex and further taxonomic studies, preferably involving molecular techniques, are essential.
Ambassis nalua was originally described as Chanda nalua by Hamilton (1822) from fresh waters of lower Bengal. The species was reviewed by Allen and Burgess (1990).
Ambassis interrupta was reviewed by Allen and Burgess (1990) for the Australia/Pacific and by Anderson and Heemstra (2003) for the western Indian Ocean.

This species was described as Aplocheilus carnaticus Jerdon (1849) from 'river that passes by Waniambaddy [= Vaniyambadi], 'Carnatic', southern India. This widespread species is likely to be a complex and further taxonomic studies, preferably involving molecular techniques, are essential.

A few early references use the name Oxyeleotris gyrinoides. There are several other species names (Bunaka pelewensis and Bunaka pinguis) that may or may not apply to this species. Taxonomic work is required.

One of its common names, Green-backed Guavina, is often misspelled as Gauvina (by later references quoting the original misspelling by Allen (1991)). Guavina is an American term for gudgeon (therefore not very appropriate for a non-American species).
Ichthyocampus carce was described by Hamilton (1822) from the tide way of Ganges River, India.
It is in need of a taxonomic revision (Poulsen et al. 2009).
The genus Narcetes, and Rinoctes and Bathytroctes are in need of a taxonomic revision (Poulsen et al. 2009).
The genus Narcetes, and Rinoctes and Bathytroctes are in need of a taxonomic revision (Poulsen et al. 2009).
The genus Narcetes, and Rinoctes and Bathytroctes are in need of a taxonomic revision (Poulsen et al. 2009).
Until recently, Melanolagus bericoides was assigned to the genus Bathylagus, and it is often confused with Bathylagus euryops (Møller et al. 2010).

The taxonomy of the genus Nansenia needs revision, as there may be 1-2 hidden synonymies among the currently recognized species. The importance of vertebral counts to the correct identification of Nansenia species can be overlooked, resulting in misidentification of specimens in museum collections. These misidentifications have been perpetuated through check lists, and thus the true distribution of these species is often uncertain (O. Gon pers. comm. 2014).
The genus Dicrolene is in need of taxonomic revision.
Nielsen (2009) revised the genus Luciobrotula, finding three species in the Atlantic Ocean: L. brasiliensis, L. corethromycter, and L. nolfi.
Mentodus perforatus Sazonov and Trunov, 1978 was described as a separate species, distinct from M. rostratus (Quéro et al. 1990).
Mentodus perforatus Sazonov and Trunov, 1978 was described as a separate species, distinct from M. rostratus (Quéro et al. 1990).
Sutton et al. (2013) report that recent molecular analyses suggest this species may be aheteromorphic synonym of Maurolicus muelleri.
The genus Conocara is in need of a taxonomic revision (Poulsen et al. 2009).

There remains some uncertainty as to the taxonomic status of Gnatholepis thompsoni. It has previously been considered a synonym of Gnatholepis cauerensis.

The taxonomic concept of Gnatholepis cauerensis is undergoing revision. Gnatholepis has often been misidentified and confused for many years. Previously, there were four proposed subspecies (G. c. cauerensis, G. c. australis, G. c. hawaiiensis and G. c. pascuensis), and G. thompsoni was considered a synonym (Randall and Greenfield 2001). Thacker (2004) shows G. thompsoni to be a separate species and also concludes that G. cauerensis should be synonymised with G. anjerensis. Variation in mitochondrial DNA suggested that G. thompsoni is a valid species that is widespread in the Atlantic Ocean and separate from G. cauerensis (Rocha et al. 2005). However, Randall and Greenfield (2007) consider G. thompsoni a synonym of G. cauerensis. Randall (2009) elevated three subspecies to the species level (resulting in four species: G. cauerensis, G. australis, G. hawaiiensis and G. pascuensis). During a recent revision of Gnatholepis, the classification presented by Rocha et al. was discussed and validated with meristic and other morphological characters by Larson and Buckle (2012). Larson and Buckle (2012) concluded that G. cauerensis includes subspecies G. c. cauerensis, G. c. australis and G. c. hawaiiensis and G. inconsequens is considered a synonym. They elevated G. thompsoni and G. pascuensis to valid species. Gnatholepis thompsoni, as valid in Larson and Buckle (2012), is restricted to the Atlantic Ocean. Rocha et al. (2005) examined genetic differences between the Atlantic G. thompsoni and the Indo-Pacific G. cauerensis, concluding that G. thompsoni is the result of a relatively recent (~ 145,000 years ago) invasion of the Atlantic by G. cauerensis. However, Smith-Vaniz and Collette (2013) recorded G. cauerensis, not G. thompsoni, in Bermuda, as "the meristic and other morphological characters purported to separate these two 'species' have broadly over-lapping values". Despite the issues with the characters used by Larson and Buckle (2012), G. thompsoni likely forms its own monophyletic group in an isolated ocean basin, and with threats and evolutionary trajectory separate from that of G. cauerensis. Therefore, G. thompsoni is retained as a valid species.
Some authors (e.g., Akazaki in Masuda et al. 1984, Chen et al. 1997) recognize two species: Caesio cuning and C. erythrogaster; however, this is doubtful (K. Carpenter pers. comm. 2015).

Westneat and Alfaro (2005) recognize the Scarini as a tribe within the family Labridae. The genera Chlororus and Scarus are two distinct monophyletic lineages (Smith et al. 2008).

Terminal males closely resemble those of S. tricolor, differing primarily by lacking a yellow blotch on the inner pectoral axil (R.F. Myers pers comm. 2009).

This assessment was updated to reflect current taxonomic knowledge, namely that populations sometimes referred to as subspecies of C. arctus (C. arctus coccineus and C. arctus heraldi - Dawson 1985) are distinct species (i.e., C. coccineus and C. heraldi) (Fritzsche 1980). Further morphometric and molecular analyses are needed in order to confirm this.
The Order for this Family has changed  from Syngnathiformes to Gasterosteiformes (Nelson 2006).

Further DNA data could provide greater detail on whether the southern population is in fact a separate species (in which case the name Syngnathus griseolineatus would be resurrected for that purpose).

Due to the large range of distribution of Syngnathus leptorhynchus, scientists are debating whether there is a single species of Bay Pipefish or several subspecies. Genetic evidence suggests that the southern population has been separated (with a biogeographic boundary near Point Conception, CA) from the northern populations for a significant period of time, although there is not enough evidence to conclude that the southern population is a genetically distinct species from the northern populations (Wilson 2006). The northern population ranges from Alaska to Monterey Bay, California, and the southern population from Morro Bay, CA to its southern extent in Baja California, Mexico (Wilson 2006).
Synonym = Phycodurus glauerti Whitley, 1939.

Various authors ascribe the name Dunckerocampus to either a separate genus (Kuiter 2000, 2009) or as a subgenus of Doryrhamphus (Dawson 1985). Dunckerocampus is treated here as a separate genus.

Dunckerocampus naia is likely a synonym of D. dactyliophorus. The species was described as different based on the colour pattern on the caudal fin, with very little in the way of morphological comparisons between the two (Allen and Kuiter 2004). Further morphological and molecular work are needed in order to clarify the taxonomic status of this species, but until further analyses are undertaken the species is treated as valid.
This species is easily confused with Pseudocaranx georgianus and P. dentex (Smith-Vaniz and Jelks 2006).
The genus of Decapterus koheru is under revision (Smith-Vaniz 2015).
This species can be easily confused with Pseudocaranx georgianus (Smith-Vaniz 2008).
The taxonomy of this species has recently been clarified by (Kimura et al. 2013).
This species has been referred to as Decapterus kurroides in the past (Kimura et al. 2013).
Saurida flamma was separated from S. gracilis on the basis of morphological characters (Waples 1981).
This species is often wrongly identified as Saurida gracilis (Russell 1999). Therefore, the exact distribution of this species requires confirmation.

This species has been misidentified by most recent authors as Synodus variegatus (Randall 2005). The type locality of this species is Hawaii, but it has been widely reported throughout the Indo-West Pacific. Therefore, the exact distribution of this species needs to be verified. Synodus amaranthus, described by Waples and Randall (1988), is now considered a junior synonym of S. dermatogenys (Randall 2007).

This species has been widely mis-identified in the literature. Two paratypes of S. doaki taken by trawl off coast of Kenya are missing from the Smithsonian fish collection and presumed lost, but it is likely that these specimens are S. randalli (Randall 2009).The specimen identified as S. doaki from the Red Sea by Baranes and Golani (1993) was re-identified as S. randalli (Randall 2009). The specimens recorded from Easter Island by Randall (2005) were determined to represent a new species, S. isolatus (Randall 2009) and those reported from Hawaii by Waples and Randall (1988), Mundy (2005), and Randall (2007) were determined to represent a new species, S. mundyi (Randall 2009).
Synodus janus, described by Waples and Randall (1988) from a single specimen collected from Hawai'i Island, is likely a synonym of S. falcatus (Randall 2007).
Synodus hoshinonis is part of a species complex, which includes S. tectus, S. similis and S. indicus, and may have been misidentified.
Records of Synodus lobeli from Taiwan and southern Japan were based on another species, S. orientalis (Randall and Pyle 2008).
This species has been previously confused with S. macrops (Cressey 1981). The replacement name S. cresseyi proposed by Prokofiev (2008) for S. macrocephalis is invalid (Ho et al. 2010).
This species has previously been confused with Synodus hoshinonis, but was regarded as distinct by Cressey (1981).

The name Synodus variegatus was wrongly used for nearly two centuries by many authors (Randall 2007). This species has been confused with S. dermatogenys and S. ulae (Waples and Randall 1988). Cressey (1981) considered S. dermatogenys to be a synonym of S. variegatus, but Waples and Randall (1988) regarded both of these species as distinct.
The genus Sphoeroides may be paraphyletic, and is in need of revision (Amaral et al. 2013).
Emblemariopsis carib was recently described as a distinct species from Emblemariopsis signifer (Victor 2010).

Starksia williamsi has been only recently described. It was previously known as S. lepicoelia, now known to be a species complex comprised of: S. lepicoelia (known from Bahamas and Turks and Caicos), S. weigti (Belize),  S. williamsi (Saba Bank, Netherland Antilles), and S. robertsoni (Panama) (Baldwin et al. 2011).

Many of the currently valid Enneanectes spp. are likely species complexes (J. Williams pers. comm. 2014). This species was recently split from E. boehlkei (Victor 2013). Enneanectes flavus replaces E. matador in Venezuela, Aruba, Bonaire, Curacao, Tobago and up to St. Vincent, and both species occur at St. Vincent (Victor 2019).
Many of the currently valid Enneanectes spp. are likely species complexes (J. Williams pers. comm. 2014).This species was recently split from E. boehlkei (Victor 2013).
This species was described from the Halieutichthys aculeatus species complex (Ho et al. 2010).

The H. rondeletii superspecies complex of the subgenus Danichthys is now recognized as containing four allopatric species: H. volador (western Atlantic), H. rondeletii (Mediterranean), H. gilberti (northern Pacific), and H. rufipinnis (Southern Hemisphere). The other two species, Hirundichthys marginatus (eastern tropical Pacific) and H. albimaculatus (west & central Pacific) are both distinct species in the subgenus, but are not part of the rondeletii superspecies complex (Parin and Belyanina 2002).
Ongoing genetic studies indicate that populations from Brazil and the Caribbean represent two different species (Smith-Vaniz and Jelks 2014, Rocha et al. in prep).
It is unclear if the species belongs to the genus Arenigobius, Amoya or Acentrogobius (H.K. Larson and D.F. Hoese pers. comm. 2015).  It is a good (valid) species.
This species may be a synonym of Gobiodon heterospilos (Shibukawa et al. 2013).
This species may belong in a separate genus, Amblygobius.
This species may belong in the genus Amblygobius (H. Larson pers. comm. 2016).
This species has been confused with Oxyurichthys nuchalis in east Africa.

This species can be confused with other Amblyraja species with different distributions, such as Amblyraja georgiana (M. Stehmann pers. comm). In the northwest Atlantic, it is easily confused with Jensen' s skate (A. jenseni). Refer to Bigelow and Shroeder (1953), Jensen (1948) and Stehman and Burkel (1984).

Last and Stevens (2009) suggest that there are subtle shape differences between populations in the southwest of Western Australia compared to those in the northwest of Western Australia (the Pilbara region). They also suggest that habitat differences exist, with those in the north being found found well offshore, while those in the south are found near the shore. This warrants further investigation.

The Reticulate Swellshark (Cephaloscyllium hiscosellum) was considered by Last and Stevens (1994) to be conspecific with C. fasciatum Chan, 1966. White and Ebert (2008), however, described it as a distinct species, which is endemic to northwestern Australia.

In the past, the Whitefin Chimaera (Chimaera argiloba) has been confused with the northern Pacific Silver Chimaera (Chimaera phantasma), however the Whitefin Chimaera differs in some morphological traits and lacks the dark stripes that characterise the Silver Chimaera (Last et al. 2008).

Confusion between this species and the Shortspine Chimaera (Chimaera obscura) has existed in the past, however the two species differ in some morphological traits; C. fulva is notably lighter in colour compared to C. obscura, and the two are genetically distinct (Didier et al. 2008).

Although only recently described (in 2002) this species has long been known to occur on deep-water slopes and fishing grounds around New Zealand and Tasmania (Paulin et al. 1989, Hardy 1990, Last and Stevens 1994).
The Southern African Frilled Shark C. africana Ebert & Compagno, 2009 is distinct from C. anguineus.

Together with the closely related Pygmy Thornback Skate Dentiraja flindersi, D. lemprieri differs from other Australian skates in having a prominent blackish patch on the undersurface of the snout tip.
The Deepwater Skate (Dipturus acrobelus) was previously misidentified as Bight Skate Raja gudgeri (Last et al. 1983).

Last (2008) considered the previously wider-ranging Dipturus polyommata (Ogilby, 1910) to consist of two species, the southern form was described as Dipturus endeavouri Last, 2008 and the northern form (that considered here) is the Argus Skate (D. polyommata). Last (2008) outlines in detail the justification for this taxonomic change and explains nomenclature.

Weng’s Skate (Dipturus wengi) appears to belong to a complex of closely related skate species that differ only slightly in their morphology (Last and Stevens 2009). Records of this species from off Indonesia and the Philippines are likely a different species.

The Australian Butterfly Ray has two distinct morphological variants which are principally separated by the presence or absence of a small dorsal fin (Jacobsen and Bennett 2009). Dorsal surface colouration can vary in this species from a uniform light green to a dark olive or grey-green and is highly dependent on the surrounding environment.
Previously this species was considered to be conspecific with H. boesemani but its taxonomy was recently resolved (White et al. 2007).

Hemigaleus australiensis is described as having substantially lower vertebral counts, much higher tooth counts in lower jaw, and a black-tipped second dorsal fin, separating it from Hemigaleus microstoma (White et al. 2005).

Several species of sixgill stingrays have been named from the Western Pacific; H. longirostris, H. yangi, H. taiwanensis and H. brievirostra, mainly on snout length and shape. However, these forms may be based on variation with growth and state of preservation. The current opinion of the occurrence of a single species of sixgill stingray, H. bickelli based on morphological comparisons, should be confirmed by genetic analyses.

The Black Ghostshark (Hydrolagus homonycteris) is probably closely related to Abyssal Ghostshark (H. trolli), but the two differ in that the Black Ghostshark has a longer dorsal spine, smaller claspers and is darker in colour.

The Marbled Ghostshark differs from other species within the genus Hydrolagus through several morphological characteristics, by being lighter in colour and possessing a distinctive reticulated pattern (Didier 2008). Tissue samples for molecular sequencing have not been obtained to genetically distinguish the Marbled Ghostshark from other species (Didier 2008).

Shape differences are evident between populations across its range and need further investigation (Last and Compagno 1998). There is a need to ascertain if this species is conspecific with the population in the type locality (i.e., the Philippines).

The Western Spotted Gummy Shark (Mustelus stevensi) was recently described by White and Last (2008). It appeared in Last and Stevens (1994) as the undescribed Mustelus sp. nov. B, which was reported to occur both off western and eastern Australia. However, White and Last (2008) described the western form as M. stevensi, and the eastern form as M. walkeri.

The Ornate Numbfish (Narcine ornata) is a recently described species of numbfish (Carvalho 2008). It has previously been confused with Banded Numbfish (Narcine westraliensis) that is found further south in Western Australia outside the range of this species (Last and Stevens 2009).

The Painted Maskray (Neotrygon leylandi) was formerly Dasyatis leylandi until resurrection of the genus Neotrygon by Last and White (2008). The Painted Maskray was previously considered to be more wide-ranging off northern Australia, before the eastern form was recently (2008) described as a new species, the Speckled Maskray (N. picta).

The Speckled Maskray (Neotrygon picta) was thought to be a regional colour variant of Neotrygon (formerly Dasyatis) leylandi (Last, 1987) until described as a new species by Last and White (2008). The latter publication also resurrected the genus Neotrygon for the maskray species, Bluespotted Maskray (N. kuhlii), Painted Maskray (N. leylandi), Plain Maskray (N. annotata), Ningaloo Maskray (N. ningalooensis) and the Speckled Maskray.

The Blue Skate (Notoraja azurea) is a recently described species of Notoraja first recognized as distinct by Last and Stevens (1994). There is some regional variation in color pattern and meristics of this species that could result in separate species being described (Last and Stevens 2009).
Four Notoraja species were previously identified by Last and Stevens (1994) but remained undescribed until recently (McEachran and Last 2008, Last and Stevens 2009).

The Arafura Skate (Okamajei arafurensis) is a recently described species (Last and Gledhill 2008), not previously recognised. It is a new skate of the Indo–Pacific genus Okamejei. The species is morphologically similar to theYellow-spotted Skate (O. hollandi) from the western North Pacific and is also superficially similar to some Australian short-snout Dipturus species (Last and Gledhill 2008).

Orectolobus halei was previously synonymized with O. ornatus and was believed to be the adult form of O. ornatus. Taxonomic revision of New South Wales species showed that O. halei differs from O. ornatus in colour pattern (O. halei has black edges around saddles and is less freckled), an adult size larger than 120 cm total length, more dermal lobes at the posterior preorbital group (4–6), precaudal vertebrae count (>106), spiral valve count (>25), and two supraorbital knob. Morphometrically, O. halei has a shorter pelvic fin to anal fin interspace, larger pectoral fins, larger head dimensions, and relatively larger claspers in mature specimens (Huveneers 2006).

Orectolobus halei is also often confused with O. maculatus but differs with less dermal lobes at the posterior preorbital group (4-6) and a distinctive brownish upper body colouration with well-defined, darker brown saddles surrounded by black edges, and containing paler markings that lacks whitish rings and blotches (unlike O. maculatus) (Huveneers 2006).
As Orectolobus sp. nov. A, this was given a DISCARDED flag because is was an undescribed species assessed as LC; therefore it did not appear on the published Red List until 2009.

In New South Wales, O. maculatus is often confused with O. halei, but differs from O. halei by having more (6-10 dermal lobes at the posterior preorbital group) and saddles containing whitish rings and blotches (unlike O. halei).

In Western Australia, O. maculatus was previously synonymised with O. parvimaculatus. Taxonomic revision of Western Australian species showed that O. maculatus differs from O. parvimaculatus by having have relatively smaller and less densely distributed ocelli and dorsal fins lacking dark markings (blackish marginal blotches present in O. parvimaculatus). The dorsal fins of O. maculatus are also smaller and less upright than those of O. parvimaculatus (Last and Chidlow 2008).
Records from Japan and the South China Sea are likely to be mis-identified O. japonicus or another undescribed species.

Orectolobus ornatus was previously synonimised with O. halei and was believed to be the juvenile form of O. halei. Taxonomic revision of New South Wales species showed that O. ornatus differs from O. halei in color pattern (more freckled in O. ornatus), an adult size smaller than 120 cm TL, fewer dermal lobes at the posterior preorbital group (3-4), precaudal vertebrae count (<106), spiral valve count (<25), and the absence of supraorbital knob. Morphometrically, O. ornatus has a longer pelvic fin to anal fin interspace, smaller pectoral fins, smaller head dimensions, and relatively smaller claspers in mature specimens (Huveneers 2006).

Assessment is complicated by taxonomic uncertainties based on the identification of the Papua New Guinea specimen. This species should at present be considered as an Australian endemic (L.J.V. Compagno, pers. comm.).

Orectolobus parvimaculatus has been confused in the literature with the larger O. maculatus (e.g., Compagno 1984, 2001, Last and Stevens 1994, Compagno et al. 2005, Hoese et al. 2006, Last and Chidlow 2008) and was believed to be juvenile O. maculatus. Taxonomic revision of Western Australian species showed that O. parvimaculatus differs from O. maculatus by having have relatively larger and more densely distributed ocelli, and dorsal fins with blackish marginal blotches (absent in O. maculatus). The dorsal fins of O. parvimaculatus are also taller and more upright than those of equivalent size O. maculatus (Last and Chidlow 2008).

The Northern Wobbegong (Orectolobus wardi) belongs to a subgroup of small, morphologically similar wobbegongs, termed the ‘wardi-complex’. This species complex contains at least three colour forms. All forms attain less than 100 cm total length and possess simple dermal lobes. Differences in colouration was initially thought to be intraspecific variation, however recent comparison of multiple specimens has shown that the forms differ consistently in colour, pattern and some morphological features. Further taxonomic and genetic research is required to elucidate the true number of species in the ‘wardi-complex’, their distributions and conservation status, but has not yet been possible due to the small number of specimens available for comparison. At this stage, the complex is considered to consist of the Northern Wobbegong, the Network Wobbegong (O. reticulatus) and one (or more) potentially undescribed species (Last et al. 2008, Last and Stevens 2009).

This species is distinct in shape from all other stingarees, resulting in its placement in the separate monospecific family, Plesiobatidae. There has never been a comparison of populations of this species, which needs to be undertaken to elucidate whether there is in fact more than one species.
There are two sympatric forms of this species which differ in colour pattern; the relationship between these forms requires study (Last and Stevens 2009).

Colour variation has been noted in this species with specimens from the northwest Pacific (Japan) noticeably darker in overall colour than those from the southwest Pacific (New Zealand) (Didier and Nakaya 1999). The distinction between R. atlantica and R. pacifica is problematic and solely based on the number of caudal tubercles, a highly variable and often overlapping characteristic (tends to be greater in R. atlantica). Resolution on the distinction of these two species will require examination of larger series of specimens and potentially molecular data (Compagno et al. 1990).

The Western Legskate (Sinobatis bulbicauda) was recently described by Last and Séret (2008). In the species description Last and Séret (2008) elevated Sinobatis to the rank of genus on the basis of the conservative intragroup clasper morphology of its member species, and its strong differentiation from Hulley’s (1973) other subgenera Anacanthobatis.

The medium-sized Western Legskate has affinities to the slightly smaller species the Borneo Legskate (S. borneensis) (South and East China Seas). Based on its description of the adult male holotype, S. borneensis has a filamentous (vs. bulbous) tail and the snout is relatively longer with preorbital length 6.5 times the interorbital length (vs. 3.9–4.8 in adult males and 3.4–5.7 in all types of S. bulbicauda) (Last and Séret 2008). Additionally, adult males of the two species are not identical in size, S. borneensis, 31.7 cm total length (TL) (vs. 42.9–43.3 cm TL in S. bulbicauda) and also differ in many morphometric characteristics including their relative disc widths, precloacal lengths, preoral lengths, orbit diameters, mouth width, and intergill distances which will aid in differentiating the two species (see Last and Séret 2008 for measurement ranges).

The name Squalus megalops has been used widely for what represents a species-complex, with the true S. megalops endemic to Australia. Squalus acutipinnis has recently been resurrected as a distinct species (Viana and Carvalho 2016), and S. mahia and S. margaretsmithae have been described as new species (Viana et al. 2018).

The Banded Stingaree is morphologically similar to the Yellowback Stingaree (Urolophus sufflavus) and genetics are nearly identical; further investigation is required to confirm that these are separate species (Last et al. 2016).
Further investigation is required to confirm the species' Pacific distribution (Last et al. 2016).
This and the other two species in the genus Centrolabrus were moved to the genus Symphodus, based on morphological and behavioural evidence (Almada et al. 2002).
This and the other two species in the genus Centrolabrus were moved to the genus Symphodus, based on morphological and behavioural evidence (Almada et al. 2002).

According to Larson (in press; WIO book), the Indian Ocean species, Gunnellichthys copleyi, may be synonymous with Gunnellichthys pleurotaenia. More research is needed on the taxonomy of this species.

The western Indian Ocean populations of this species have been recently recognized as a distinct species, Nemateleotris exquisita (Randall and Connell 2013). However, the status of this species requires further taxonomic study.
The distribution remains in question until further studies have been completed within the Eviota nigriventris complex.

The Indian Ocean subpopulation was recognized as a subspecies, Ptereleotris grammica melanota (Randall and Lubbock 1982). The taxonomic status of this subpopulation needs further investigation given its disjunct distribution from other populations identified as Ptereleotris grammica grammica.

Acanthoplesiops indicus, is sister to two allopatric West Pacific species, A. psilogaster to the north (Japan, Taiwan, Batanes) and A. echinatus to the south (southern Philippines and Moluccas) (Mooi and Gill 2004).
Pristigenys refulgens was recently resurrected from synonymy with P. niphonia (Iwatsuki et al. 2012).
C. unicolor may be a synonym of C. longimanus.
The Hawaiian Islands and Johnston Atoll populations are morphologicallydistinct from western Pacific populations (Mundy 2005).
This species is sometimes placed in the monotypic genus Zalanthias (FishBase).
This binomial was recently resurrected from the synonymy of P. squamipinnis and P. fasciatus is a junior synonym of P. gibbosus (Heemstra and Akhilesh 2012)
Records from the Maldives and Mascarene Islands are now recognized as P. unimarginatus.

Randall et al. (2002) restricted the name Pseudogramma australis to the individuals found at Easter Island, and provided a replacement name for the individuals previously identified as P. australis in the western Pacific Ocean (Pseudogramma xantha). Therefore, the specimens reported as P. australis in FishNet2 are regarded as P. xantha (accessed through the FishNet2 Portal, www.fishnet2.net, 14/06/2016).

The Pseudogramma polyacantha species complex was recently split into four valid species: P. polyacantha, occurring from French Polynesia to South Africa; P. brederi from Hawaii to Mauritius; and P. galzini and P. paucilepis, both known only from French Polynesia (Williams and Viviani 2016).

Randall et al. (2002) restricted the name Pseudogramma australis to the individuals found at Easter Island, and provided a replacement name for the individuals previously identified as P. australis in the western Pacific Ocean (Pseudogramma xantha). Therefore, the specimens reported as P. australis in FishNet2 are regarded as P. xantha (accessed through the FishNet2 Portal, www.fishnet2.net, 14/06/2016).
This species may be a synonym of Arnoglossus brunneus (Hensley and Amaoka 2001), but is treated as a valid species until additional evidence is available.
This may be a junior synonym of Bothus leopardinus (Hensley 1995, Grove and Lavenberg 1997); further research is needed to clarify its status.

Most systematists working with flatfishes (Pleuronectiformes) now recognize the Rhombosoleidae as a family (Chapleau and Keast 1988, Chapleau 1993, Guibord 2003, Munroe 2015). 

James (1972) noted significant variation in body proportions for specimens purportedly of Peltorhamphus latus from Blueskin Bay. He considered these differences to represent population variation within the species P. latus. Munroe (2015) examined these and other specimens and found other morphological differences that indicated an undescribed species (Peltorhamphus sp. A) was represented among the specimens from Blueskin Bay. Munroe (2020) provided a formal description of this species, and named it Peltorhamphus kryptostomus.
Most systematists working with flatfishes (Pleuronectiformes) now recognize the Poecilopsettidae as a family (Chapleau and Keast 1988, Chapleau 1993, Guibord 2003, Munroe 2015).
