Enneanectes flavus replaces E. matador in Venezuela, Aruba, Bonaire, Curacao, Tobago and up to St. Vincent, and both species occur at St. Vincent (Victor 2019).
There is taxonomic uncertainty associated with this recently described species. According to Prokofiev (2010), this species is a junior synonym of Chiasmodon lavenbergi.

The family Cheilodactylidae has long been the subject of taxonomic debate. Cheilodactylus nigripes has been considered part of the subgenus Goniistius, however some authors defend it should be excluded from it (Burridge and White 2000). Recently, Ludt and colleagues (2019) performed extensive taxonomic sampling analyzing morphological characters and molecular data to resolve taxonomic issues with the families Cheilodactylidae and Latridae. It was concluded that this species belongs to the family Latridae and to the new, monotypic genus Pseudogoniistius; therefore, Pseudogoniistius nigripes (Richardson 1850) is a valid species (Ludt et al. 2019).
There is taxonomic uncertainty associated with this species. According to Melo (2009), Chiasmodon lavenbergi Prokofiev 2008, is a synonym of C. pluriradiatus Parr 1933.
This species can be easily misidentified as Pseudoscopelus scutatus (Prokofiev and Kukuev 2007, Melo 2010).

According to Melo (2010), Pseudoscopelus parini and P. vityazi are the same species that was described twice using the same diagnostic characters. However, Prokofiev (2011) still regards P. vityazi as a valid species. According to Eschmeyer's Catalog of Fishes, P. vityazi is currently considered a synonym of P. parini (Fricke et al. 2019); therefore, for the purposes of this Red List assessment, all records of P. vityazi will be treated as P. parini.
There is taxonomic uncertainty associated with this species. According to Prokofiev (2011), Pseudoscopelus paxtoni is a synonym of P. altipinnis.

Achirus zebrinus Clark 1936 was described on the basis of a single specimen. It was not until 1977, when Castro-Aguirre et al. listed a second capture for this species. And, in 1999, Castro-Aguirre et al. reported that this species was poorly represented in museum collections. They also commented that the taxonomic status of this nominal species is uncertain. Supporting this hypothesis is the fact that this species was not included in three major works on the fish fauna of the tropical eastern Pacific (Allen and Robertson 1994, Krupp 1995, Robertson and Allen 2015). However, numerous specimens identified as this species are listed in several ecological works on fishes of the Gulf of Tehuantepec (e.g. Tapia-García and Mendoza-Rodríguez 2005, Martinez-Muñoz et al. 2016) and some of these specimens are listed in museum databases (accessed via iDigBio portal, https://www.idigbio.org/, 2021 March). Provided that these ecological works have correctly identified specimens as Achirus zebrinus, then it appears that this species is more abundant than historical literature indicates and possibly that this species has a rather restricted distribution off southern Mexico.
This species was previously confused with Anodontostoma chacunda.

Diagnosis:

  • Dorsal with 12-13 banched rays; anal with 37-43 branched rays; pectoral with 12-13 branched rays; pelvic with seven banched rays. 41-44 body along scales.
  • Body is long and very compressed. Short head. Snout is obtuse and short. Mouth extending to head.
  • One average dorsal fin with one small spine in anterior. Anal fin is long. Pectoral is quite large. Pelvic fin is small and short.
  • Scales are round and easy leave. Axillary scale in pectoral and pelvic fins. No lateral line.
  • Belly with 23 to 26 keeled scutes from isthmus to anus. Tip of snout above level of eye center, usually about level of upper rim of eye. Maxilla short or moderate; first supra-maxilla small, oval. A dark blotch behind upper part of gill opening.
Hilsa kelee was originally described as Clupea kelee by Cuvier (1829) from Vishakhapatnam, Andhra Pradesh, India.

Sardinops sagax has historically comprised five geographically isolated subpopulations that were given taxonomic names at some time in their history. There has been considerable confusion as to what rank these subpopulations should be recognized. The current version of the Catalog of Fishes (Eschmeyer et al. 2018) accepts three valid species within this complex: S. sagax (Jenyns 1842), S. melanosticta (Temminck and Schlegel 1846) and S. ocellatus (Pappe 1853). However, the most recent global analyses found no morphological or genetic differentiation between any of the five subpopulations (Parrish et al. 1989, Grant and Leslie 1996). Therefore, for the purposes of this assessment, we are treating S. sagax as a single species with five geographically isolated subpopulations.

Several sub-species of Sprattus sprattus have been recognized, which are distinguished by small differences, mainly in numbers of post-pelvic scutes; S. sprattus sprattus; S. sprattus phalericus (Mediterranean, Adriatic, Black Sea); S. sprattus balticus (Baltic Sea). The subspecies S. sprattus balticus ranges from southern Skagerrak, and Mecklenburg and Kiel Bays to Kvarken in the Gulf of Bothnia, and to Kornstadt in the Gulf of Finland (FAO 2017). However, no genetic evidence for a subspecies in the Baltic Sea or the occurrence of one subspecies in the Mediterranean and the Black Sea has been found (Debes et al. 2008). Rather, population analysis using the mT Control Region supported four genetically distinct groups of S. sprattus, which fall under two major phylogroups; Phylogroup 1: Northern group (Baltic Sea, North Sea and Bay of Biscay) and Gulf of Lyon group; and Phylogroup 2: Adriatic Sea group and Black Sea group (Bosporus and Black Sea: Debes et al. 2008). The Strait of Sicily, with water temperatures of 24-25 oC, acts as a dispersal barrier between eastern and Western Mediterranean.

Sardinella gibbosa is often confused with S. fimbriata in Indian waters (Whitehead 1985). There is at least one cryptic species present in the northern Philippines that has been called S. gibbosa (Thomas et al. 2014).
It is commonly misidentified which may make some of the data unreliable.
This species may be misidentified as Spratelloides gracilis and S. delicatus.

The validity of Alosa pontica is questioned in the literature. Some refer to this species as a synonym of A. immaculata (Kottelat 1997, Bogutskaya and Naseka 2004, Parin et al. 2014); others recognize it to be a valid species (Svetovidov 1973, Whitehead et al. 1984, Whitehead 1985, Hoestlandt 1991, Kolarov 1991, Coad 1995, Vasil'eva 1996, Reshetnikov et al. 1997, Dorofeeva 1998, Coad 1998, Bilecenoglu et al. 2002, Vassilev and Pehlivanov 2005, Eschmeyer et al. 2017).  For the purposes of this assessment, Alosa pontica will will be treated as valid.
This species can easily be confused with Coilia borneensis (Whitehead et al. 1988).

The most recent global analysis of the world's clupeoid fishes treated Engraulis australis (Shaw 1790) as valid (Whitehead et al. 1988), but noted the similarities between this species and the four other Old World anchovies, E. capensis Gilchrist 1913, E. encrasicolus (Linnaeus 1758), E. eurystole (Swain & Meek 1884) and E. japonicus Temminck & Schlegel 1846; further taxonomic study may conclude that these five similar species which are treated as valid are perhaps one species with five geographically isolated subpopulations (Whitehead et al. 1988). As this species is currently considered valid in the Catalog of Fishes (Eschmeyer et al. 2018), for the purposes of this assessment Engraulis australis is considered a valid species distributed along the southern coast of Australia and off New Zealand.

The validity of this species is uncertain according to the literature (Whitehead, 1985). Engraulis capensis Gilchrist 1913 was originally described from South Africa with no type specimen known. This species has previously been considered a junior synonym of E. japonicas Temminck & Schlegel 1846 by Whitehead and Wongratana (1986) and E. encrasicolus (Linnaeus 1758) by Whitehead (1990). The most recent global analysis of the world's clupeoid fishes treated this species as valid (Whitehead et al. 1988), but noted the similarities between these three species and two other Old World anchovies, E. eurystole (Swain & Meek 1884) and E. australis (Shaw 1790); further taxonomic study may conclude that these five similar species which are treated as valid are perhaps one species with five geographically isolated subpopulations (Whitehead et al. 1988). However, as all five species in the encrasicolus group (E. australis, E. capensis, E. encrasicolus, E. eurystole and E. japonicus) are currently considered valid in the Catalog of Fishes (Eschmeyer et al. 2018), for the purposes of this assessment, Engraulis capensis is considered a valid species distributed along the southern coast of Africa.

The most recent global analysis of the world's clupeoid fishes treated Engraulis japonicus Temminck & Schlegel 1846 as valid (Whitehead et al. 1988), but noted the similarities between this species and the four other Old World anchovies, E. australis (Shaw 1790), E. capensis Gilchrist 1913, E. encrasicolus (Linnaeus 1758) and E. eurystole (Swain & Meek 1884); further taxonomic study may conclude that these five similar species which are treated as valid are perhaps one species with five geographically isolated subpopulations (Whitehead et al. 1988). As this species is currently considered valid in the Catalog of Fishes (Eschmeyer et al. 2018), for the purposes of this assessment Engraulis japonicus is considered a valid species distributed off the coasts of Japan, Korea and Taiwan as well as parts of China and Russia; records of this species in the western Indian Ocean (e.g., Madagascar) are considered to be in reference to E. capensis.

Randall and DiBattista (2012) proposed Etrumeus acuminatus as a valid species. According to the Catalog of Fishes, the name was valid in Eschmeyer and Herald (1983); but not in Whitehead (1985). This species was considered Etrumes teres, but was changed back to the older name Etrumeus sadina. All accounts of either Etrumeus teres or E. sadina in the eastern Pacific are most likely Etrumeus acuminatus (Randall and DiBattista 2012). DiBattista et al. (2014) provided molecular evidence that this species is valid and distinct from other species of Etrumeus from the Pacific Ocean.
This species is often referred to as Chascanopsetta prognathus.
This may be the senior synonym of Crossorhombus kanekonis and of Engyrosopon kanekonis (Hensley and Randall 1993, Shao et al. 2008).
Scaeops ui Tanaka 1918, reported as Engyprosopon ui (Tanaka 1918), is a junior synonym of Crossorhombus kobensis (Hensley and Amaoka 2001).

The nominal species Anticitharus annulatus Weber 1913 was historically considered a junior synonym of Asterorhombus intermedius (Bleeker 1866). It was recognized as a valid species in the genus Asterorhombus by Amoaka and Mihara (2001), but during the generic revision of Asterorhombus (Hensley 2005), it was transferred to the genus Engyprosopon. However, its general appearance is different from most species of Engyprosopon and its generic placement remains in question (Hensley 2005).

This species was originally described as Arnoglossus bleekeri Macleay 1881 based on a young specimen (Amaoka and Arai 1998). It was later placed in the genus Asterorhombus (Hensley and Randall 2003), but during the generic revision of Asterorhombus it was transferred to the genus Engyprosopon (Hensley 2005).
This species was originally described as the subspecies Arnoglossus aspilos praeteritus Whitley 1950, and later considered a junior synonym of Arnoglossus aspilos (Amaoka and Last 2014).

Uncertainty has surrounded the taxonomic status of Laeops lanceolata Franz 1910. This nominal species was synonymized with Laeops kitaharae by Amaoka (1969). Later authors (e.g., Li and Wang 1995, Voronina 2016) treated L. lanceolata as valid; however, in a personal communication, Amaoka (2019) still maintained that L. lanceolata was not a valid species. In the most recent revision of the genus Laeops by Voronina et al. (2020), Laeops lanceolata is considered to be a valid species. Additionally, L. kitaharae was placed in the synonymy of L. parviceps. These decisions are followed herein.

Ho et al. (2009) determined that the type series of Laeops tungkongensis Chen and Weng 1965 could be identified as L. clarus Fowler 1934 using the taxonomic key of Hensley and Amaoka (2001). However, as Ho et al. (2009) were unable to examine the type series of L. clarus, they made no further comparisons and made the taxonomic decision to regard L. tungkongensis as valid.

Later, Amaoka and Ho (2019) examined types of Laeops tungkongensis Chen and Weng 1965 and Laeops kitaharae Smith and Pope 1906. They determined L. tungkongensis to be a junior subjective synonym of L. kitaharae.

Voronina et al. (2020), in a revision of the genus Laeops, examined types of L. tungkongensis and L. clarus and determined that L. tungkongensis Chen and Weng 1965 is a junior synonym of L. clarus Fowler 1934. They also determined that L. kitaharae Smith and Pope 1906 is a junior synonym of L. parviceps Günther 1880. These conclusions are followed herein.

Laeops parviceps Günther 1880 was described based on three specimens collected during the voyage of the H.M.S. Challenger in 1873-1876. Voronina et al. (2020) determined that two of the three syntypes, collected off Twofold Bay, New South Wales, Australia, were not members of the genus Laeops; thus, Voronina et al. (2020) designated the third syntype (BMNH 1879.5.14.98), collected in the Arafura Sea, as the lectotype of Laeops parviceps.

Species of Lophonectes exhibit ontogentic and sexually dimorphic variation (Munroe 2015). Lophonectes mongonuiensis has been considered a junior synonym of L. gallus, but differs in meristic and morphological characters and is therefore considered a valid species (Munroe 2015).

Species of Lophonectes exhibit ontogentic and sexually dimorphic variation (Munroe 2015). Lophonectes mongonuiensis has been considered a junior synonym of L. gallus, but differs in meristic and morphological characters and is therefore considered a valid species (Munroe 2015).

Symphurus trewavasae Chabanaud 1948 was described from specimens collected off Cape Frio, Brazil. In his revision of western Atlantic Symphurus, Ginsburg (1951) suggested that S. trewavasae was possibly not distinct from S. plagiusa (Linnaeus 1776). Subsequent authors (Menezes and Benvengú 1976, Munroe 1998) provided data warranting recognition of these as distinct species.

Mystus gulio was described from the higher parts of the Gangetic estuary by Hamilton (1822). Although it is often regarded as a species widely distributed throughout South and Southeast Asia, there is some evidence to indicate that the populations from Southeast Asia constitute one or more species that are distinct from populations in the Indian subcontinent (H.H. Ng pers. comm.). A taxonomic reappraisal of this species based on material from throughout its entire distribution is badly needed.

Based on recent genetics studies, the taxonomic status of this species in the Black and Marmara seas is somewhat uncertain. According to Turan et al. (2019), Scophthalmus rhombus is a distinct species in the region, but Firidin et al. (2020) concluded it is not distinct from S. maximus in the region. For purposes of this assessment, and based on past literature (e.g., Giragosov et al. 2012), S. rhombus, though rare, is considered to represent a distinct species in the Black and Marmara seas.

The taxonomic history of this species is complicated in the Black Sea region (Parin et al. 2014). Scophthalmus maeoticus has been considered a junior synonym of S. maximus with uncertainty by some workers (Chanet 2003, Suzuki et al. 2004, Nielsen et al. 2004, Bailly and Chanet 2010). Scophthalmus maeoticus has also been considered as a subspecies of S. maximus by some (Parin et al. 2014), but both cytogenetic and population genetic data suggest that these two nominal species are part of the same species (Bouza et al. 1995, do Prado et al. 2018). 

Currently, the subpopulation in the Black Sea is very likely isolated from other residual Mediterranean subpopulations due to the high temperature of the Mediterranean waters. A notable genetic differentiation has been reported in the subpopulation inhabiting the Black Sea, but this differentiation is similar to that of other residual subpopulations in the Mediterranean Sea (do Prado et al. 2018). This has prompted some authors (Turan et al. 2019) to claim that S. maeoticus and S. maximus are different species. A study by Firidin et al. (2020) that used mitochondrial DNA concluded that only S. maximus occurs in the Black Sea. Based on evidence provided in Firidin et al. (2020), it is concluded that S. maeoticus is a junior subjective synonym of S. maximus even if sampling conditions differed from those reported in Turan et al. (2019) (B. Chanet and T. Munroe pers. comm. 2020). 

This species is still frequently referred to in the literature as Psetta maxima, but the proper generic placement and nomenclature is Scophthalmus maximus (Bouza et al. 1995, Bailly and Chanet 2010). Different scientific names are used for this species in the coastal countries of the Black Sea. For example, in Russia, the name S. maeoticus is used, while in the Ukraine, both S. maximus and Psetta maeoticus are used. The region-level stock assessment conducted by the General Fisheries Commission for the Mediterranean (GFCM) primarily refers to this nominal species as S. maximus (V. Shlyakhov pers. comm. 2020).
This species was reviewed by Larson (2001). It was often previously referred to as Mugilogobius fontinalis (Jordan and Seale 1906).

In the past, Citharoides macrolepidotus has been considered by some authors to be a junior synonym of Paracitharus macrolepis (e.g., Norman 1934). 

Hubbs (1915) described Citharoides macrolepidotus. Earlier, Gilchrist (1904) had described a species macrolepis that he placed in the bothid genus Arnoglossus. Regan (1920) determined that A. macrolepis was not a member of this bothid genus, so he described a new genus, Paracitharus, for this species.

Norman (1934) considered Paracitharus as a junior synonym of Citharoides and also synonymized P. macrolepis with C. macrolepidotus. He considered there to be only a single genus and species with the name Citharoides macrolepis (Gilchrist 1904). Hubbs (1945) recognized both species and genera as valid based on differences in the canal shape on their posterior lateral line scales. Hoshino (2001), based on this character and other morphological data, confirmed these observations and agreed that both species and genera were distinct from each other. 

Following the morphological data of Hubbs (1945) and Hoshino (2001), Paracitharus is herein recognized as a valid genus, distinct from Citharoides, and C. macrolepidotus is recognized as a valid species, distinct from P. macrolepis.

This species was long considered to have two forms, one was characterized by having two lateral lines and the other by having three lateral lines. Yokogawa et al. (2008b) examined isozymes and demonstrated these forms are genetically distinct at the specific level. The species with two lateral lines was identified as Cynoglossus interruptus, while the form with three lateral lines was described as the new species, Cynoglossus ochiaii (Yokogawa et al. 2008b).

Menon (1977) considered Cynoglossus lighti Norman 1925, C. tenuis (Oshima 1927) and C. tshusanensis Chabanaud 1951 as junior subjective synonyms of Cynglossus joyneri. Cynoglossus tenuis is known only from the holotype, collected in Taiwan, and this specimen has subsequently been lost. Cynoglossus tshusanensis was described on the basis of three specimens collected off China. It has been regarded as a junior subjective synonym of C. joyneri by most authors that have dealt with this nominal species. Cynoglossus lighti has been considered a valid species by several authors working with this nominal species, but the prevailing opinion is that this is a junior subjective synonym of C. joyneri (see Fricke et al. 2020 for relevant literature).

Cynoglossus interruptus was long considered to have two forms, one was characterized by having two lateral lines and the other by having three lateral lines. Recently, isozymic analysis demonstrated these forms are genetically distinct at the specific level. The species with two lateral lines was identified as Cynoglossus interruptus, while the form with three lateral lines was described as the new species, Cynoglossus ochiaii (Yokogawa et al. 2008). Thus, data from prior to the description of C. ochiaii, data for the two species were intermingled.

Bleeker (1879) described Aphoristia orientalis on the basis of a unique holotype that was subsequently lost (Lee et al. 2013). Limited diagnostic characters and loss of the holotype led to confusion regarding the identity of this and other, similar tonguefishes in the Indo-Pacific (Lee et al. 2013). Lee et al. (2013) examined morphological and molecular characters of a large series of specimens collected in Taiwanese and Japanese waters, redefined Symphurus orientalis (Bleeker 1879), and redescribed the species based on these specimens. They also designated a neotype for S. orientalis.
This species is presently under revision (Larson and Hammer in prep.).
This species was recently reviewed by Larson (2010); it has often been identified as Redigobius roemeri.
Revisonary work is required for the genus Stenogobius. This species name may be a senior synonym to S. blokzeyli (Larson in prep.).
Revisonary work is required for the genus Stenogobius.
Further study is required for the genus Stenogobius. This species is similar to four others in New Guinea and the Pacific.
Further study is required for the genus Stenogobius.
Eviota fallax closely resembles E. natalis (Greenfield and Allen 2012).
This species is closely related to Eviota sebreei (Tornabene et al. 2016).

This species is commonly confused with Oligolepis stomias and the two species may occur together (Larson in prep.). In southern Africa, records of this species is confused with those of Oxyurichthys keiensis. There appears to be at least one undescribed species which may be confused with this species. The genus is in need of revision.

The species name is often misspelled as 'acutipinnis'.
The taxonomy of this species has recently been reviewed by Larson (2010).

This species is easily confused with Mulloidichthys vanicolensis, which is a congener and shoals together with M. ayliffe. The Pacific sister species is M. mimicus. Both mimic the Indo-Pacific snapper Lutjanus kasmira (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).

The taxonomic concept for Bigeye Sixgill Shark (Hexanchus nakamurai) has been revised and the Atlantic Sixgill Shark (Hexanchus vitulus) has now been resurrected to a separate species that occurs in the Western Central Atlantic Ocean (Daly-Engel et al. 2019).

authority: Grace, Doosey, Denton, Naylor, Bart & Maisey, 2019
taxonomicNotes: This species is known only from the holotype collected in 2010. It is distinct from Mollisquama parini Dolganov, 1984, the only other member of the genus (Grace et al. 2015, Grace et al. 2019).

Upeneus randalli was initially misidentified as U. margarethae, which was only known from a single record in the Arabian/Persian Gulf. It is clearly distinguished from other goatfish species in this region (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
It is easily confused with Syacium ovale (Murakami and Amaoka 1992).
This species is very similar to the congener Syacium ovale (Murakami and Amaoka 1992).
<span>The taxonomy of this species requires revision (Bogutskaya and Naseka 2013).
Appeared in the IUCN Red Lists from 1996 to 2006 under the name Stizostedion marinum.

Some debate has surrounded the placement of Paralichthodes algoensis Gilchrist 1902. Previously, it was classified as belonging to the subfamily Samarinae of the Pleuronectidae (Regan 1910). Regan (1920) erected the family Paralichthodidae for this species. In 1929, Regan reduced its rank to the subfamily Paralichthodinae within the Pleuronectidae. This classification was retained by Norman (1934), Hubbs (1945), and Evseenko (2004). In contrast, Nelson (1976) reassigned P. algoensis to the Samarinae. Sakamoto (1984) considered this species as a member of the subfamily Pleuronectinae within the Pleuronectidae. However, more recent works based on both morphological and molecular evidence (e.g., Cooper and Chapleau 1998, Pardo et al. 2005, Campbell et al. 2019) classify P. algoensis as the only member of the family Paralichthodidae.

Taxonomic uncertainty associated with Atheresthes evermanni and A. stomias was resolved with the genetic study (Ranck et al. 1986) that confirmed their validity as separate species. The two species are also well distinguished from one another by external morphology (Yang 1988, Mukhametov and Orlov 2002).

Due to high similarity in both appearance, ecology and distribution, there was much taxonomic uncertainty associated with Atheresthes evermanni and A. stomias until genetics studies in the mid-1980s (Ranck et al. 1986) and morphological differences (Yang 1988) confirmed their validity as separate species.

The genus Hippoglossoides, including Hippoglossoides robustus, H. elassodon and H. dubius, has been the subject of recent taxonomic uncertainty (Parin et al. 2014, Vinnikov et al. 2018). Kartavtsev et al. (2008) concluded that H. robustus is a junior synonym of H. elassodon; however, this was later refuted by additional genetic studies (Roje 2010, Parin et al. 2014). According to Vinnikov et al. (2018), the phylogenetic and taxonomic status of H. robustus are not yet fully resolved, and additional sampling of specimens from throughout the entire geographic range is needed. Some genetic studies are currently underway, and preliminary results suggest that they are separate species (I. Spies pers. comm. 2020).

Cleisthenes herzensteini (Schmidt 1904) is considered a junior synonym of C. pinetorum Jordan and Starks 1904 according to Vinnikov et al. (2018), but these authors mention uncertainty remains concerning this taxonomic decision and that further sampling across the entire range inhabited by these two nominal species is required.

The genus Hippoglossoides, including Hippoglossoides robustus, H. elassodon and H. dubius, has been the subject of recent taxonomic uncertainty (Parin et al. 2014, Vinnikov et al. 2018). Kartavtsev et al. (2008) concluded that H. robustus is a junior synonym of H. elassodon; however, this was later refuted by additional genetic studies (Roje 2010, Parin et al. 2014). According to Vinnikov et al. (2018), the phylogenetic and taxonomic status of H. robustus are not yet fully resolved, and additional sampling of specimens from throughout the entire geographic range is needed. Some genetic studies are currently underway, and preliminary results suggest that they are separate species (I. Spies pers. comm. 2020).

Orr and Matarese (2000) recognized that specimens previously identified as Lepidopsetta bilineata actually represent two species. In addition to L. bilineata, they described a second species, Lepidopsetta polyxstra, within the genus Lepidopsetta. Distribution records, ranging from the Salish Sea north to the Bering Sea, documented prior to recognition of two species in Lepidopsetta, may represent mixtures of the two species.

Orr and Matarese (2000) recognized that specimens previously identified as Lepidopsetta bilineata actually represent two species. In addition to L. bilineata, they described a second species, Lepidopsetta polyxstra, within the genus Lepidopsetta. Distribution records, ranging from the Salish Sea north to the Bering Sea, documented prior to recognition of two species in Lepidopsetta, may represent mixtures of the two species.

This species was originally described as Pleuronectes aspera by Pallas (1814). Later, this species was transferred to the genus Limanda by Bean (1882). Some authors (Sakamoto 1984a) placed this species back in the genus Pleuronectes. However, in the very same year, Sakamoto (1984b) considered this to be a member of the genus Limanda. There has been considerable debate regarding the number of species to be placed in the genus Limanda (Cooper and Chapleau 1998, Roje 2010, McCusker et al. 2013, Voronina and Chanet 2014, Busby et al. 2017, Vinnikov et al. 2018). Throughout this history, Pleuronectes aspera Pallas 1814 has more consistently been placed in the genus Limanda, except for the classification proposed by Sakamoto (1984a) and literature accepting this classification. A revision of the genus Limanda is needed, as recent data on larval morphology (Busby et al. 2017) and DNA sequences (McCusker et al. 2013) suggest that the genus is not monophyletic. Based on the morphological evidence (Norman 1934, Cooper and Chapleau 1998, Roje 2010, Voronina and Chanet 2014) and molecular data (Roje 2010, McCusker et al. 2013, Vinnikov et al. 2018), Pleuronectes aspera is regarded as a member of the genus Limanda Gottsche 1825.

This species was originally described as Limanda proboscidea by Gilbert (1896). This species has been variously placed in the genera Limanda (Cooper and Chapleau 1998, Roje 2010, Voronina and Chanet 2014), Pleuronectes (Sakamoto 1984 and literature following this placement), and Myzopsetta (Sheiko and Fedorov 2000, Fedorov et al. 2003, Mecklenburg and Steinke 2015, Vinnikov et al. 2018). Most frequently, it has been considered a member of the genus Limanda (e.g., Cooper and Chapleau 1998, Roje 2010, Voronina and Chanet 2014), but there has been considerable debate regarding the number of species to be placed in that genus (Cooper and Chapleau 1998, Roje 2010, McCusker et al. 2013, Voronina and Chanet 2014, Busby et al. 2017, Vinnikov et al. 2018). A revision of the genus Limanda is needed, as recent data on larval morphology (Busby et al. 2017) and DNA sequences (McCusker et al. 2013, Mecklenburg and Steinke 2015) suggest that the genus is not monophyletic. The most recent studies consider this species to be a member of the genus Myzopsetta (Sheiko and Fedorov 2000, Fedorov et al. 2003, Mecklenburg and Steinke 2015, Vinnikov et al. 2018). Herein, Limanda proboscidea Gilbert 1896 is regarded as a member of the genus Myzopsetta.
A taxonomic revision of the genus Limanda is needed (Busby et al. 2017, Vinnikov et al. 2018).

Liopsetta putnami (Gill 1864) has been treated as a junior subjective synonym of L. glacialis (Pallas 1776) by some, but most workers consider them to be separate species (Mecklenburg et al. 2018). Voronina and Chanet (2014) commented that additional genetics work is needed to resolve the relationships of species assigned to Liopsetta. Vinnikov et al. (2018), based on molecular data, recognized L. putnami and L. glacialis as distinct species. This species can be easily confused with smaller individuals of Winter Flounder (Pseudopleuronectes americanus).

According to Parin et al. (2014), conclusions by Vinnikov et al. (2006) and Kartavtsev et al. (2007) that Pseudopleuronectes schrenki is a synonym of P. yokohamae were not fully supported and required further examination of syntypes. Tsukagoshi et al. (2015) concluded that these are two separate species based on mitochondrial DNA analysis. Vinnikov et al. (2018) also found strong molecular evidence that these two species are indeed separate and should be considered sister species.
Guibord and Chapleau (2002) synonymized Poecilopsetta megalepis Fowler 1934 with Poecilopsetta plinthus (Jordan and Starks 1904) after analyzing the holotype and only specimen of P. megalepis.

Comparing specimens of two similar flatfishes from Australia and New Zealand, Nielsen noted that New Zealand specimens agreed with all of the characters defining Azygopus and further observed that, although the New Zealand specimens shared characteristics with A. pinnifasciatus from Australian waters, several morphological features were different between fishes from the two locations (Nielsen 1961). Even though he could distinguish New Zealand specimens from Australian A. pinnifasciatus based on a number of characters, Nielsen (1961) was influenced by the overall similarities between specimens from Australia and New Zealand and, following taxonomic conventions of that time period (J. Nielsen pers. comm. as cited in Munroe 2012), chose not to recognize the New Zealand specimens as a distinct species, instead describing them as a distinct subspecies (A. p. flemingi). Munroe (2012) distinguished it as a separate species and this was followed in various checklists and in the book The Fishes of New Zealand (e.g. Munroe 2015, Roberts et al. 2015, 2020).
Mihara and Amaoka (1995) synonymized Samariscus fasciatus Fowler, 1934 with Plagiopsetta glossa Franz, 1910 after analyzing the holotype and only known specimen of S. fasciatus.

The taxonomic status of this species and Zebrias maculosus needs to be investigated (T. Munroe and R. Nair pers. comm. 2019). At present, both nominal species are considered valid (Eschmeyer et al. 2019).

In a recent redescription of the soleid Brachirus aspilos (Bleeker 1852), Okamoto and Motomura (2021) regarded B. dicholepis (Peters 1877), B. heterolepis (Bleeker 1856), B. marmoratus (Bleeker 1853), and B. sorsogonensis (Evermann and Seale 1907) as junior, subjective synonyms of B. aspilos. This taxonomic conclusion is followed herein.

Chabanaud (1931) described Achirus rautheri on the basis of a single specimen taken from Port Darwin, Northern Territory, Australia. Clark and George (1979) and Desoutter et al. (2001) considered this species to be a junior synonym of Pardachirus hedleyi Ogilby 1916, whereas Larson and Williams (1997) treated it as a junior synonym of P. poropterus (Bleeker 1851). However, Randall and Johnson (2007), in a revision of the genus Pardachirus, concluded that P. rautheri (Chabanaud 1931) is a valid species.

Soleichthys microcephalus was originally described by Günther (1862). Munroe and Menke (2004) redescribed this species because they discovered that specimens in collections previously identified as S. microcephalus actually represented three species (S. microcephalus, S. oculofasciatus, and S. serpenpellis). As such, specimens identified as S. microcephalus before 2004 may be incorrect.

McCulloch (1916) described a new species of sole from Australian waters as Synaptura craticula. Later, this species was transferred to the genus Zebrias. To agree with the masculine gender of Zebrias, the specific epithet for this species was changed to craticulus. Not all authors have agreed with the spelling of this epithet, instead they continued to use craticula (Allen and Swainson 1988, Allen 1997, Hutchins 2001, Larson et al. 2013) or craticulatus (Hoese and Bray 2006). However, according to the Catalog of Fishes (Fricke et al. 2021) and ETYFish (Scharpf and Lazara 2020), the correct spelling of the species epithet is craticulus.
Gomon (1987) designated Zebrias scalaris as a replacement name for Synaptura fasciata Macleay 1882, which is preoccupied in Zebrias by Solea fasciata Basilewsky 1855.

This species, along with the rest of the family Hemitripteridae, was included for a long time in the family Cottidae, but the monophyly of the family Hemitripteridae was established in the 1980s leading Mecklenburg (2003) to consider its taxonomy well established.

Hexagrammos superciliosus is sometimes considered a subspecies of Hexagrammos lagocephalus or of Hexagrammos decagrammus (Gomelyuk 2000). Furthermore, the sexual dimorphism is so strong in this species that males and females were originally described as different species, females as Chirus guttatus and Chirus maculoseriatus, and the males as Chirus constellatus (Mecklenburg and Eschmeyer 2003).

Hexagrammos lagocephalus has long been considered a separate species from Hexagrammos superciliosus, however molecular data does not support this hypothesis and H. superciliosus is now considered a junior synonym of H. lagocephalus (Crow et al. 2004).

Shinohara (1994) and Crow et al. (2004) consider the genus Oxylebius to belong to the family Zaniolepididae, but Mecklenburg and Eschmeyer (2003) place it in the family Hexagrammidae. As this latter placement has been followed by recent authors (e.g., Kells et al. 2016, Pietsch and Orr 2019), we treat this species as a member of the Hexagrammidae. Further research is needed to clarify familial placement of this genus.
This species is currently considered to be the only species of the family Rhamphocottidae, however in past years it was considered part of the family Cottidae (Mecklenburg 2003).
This species is frequently misidentified as Symphurus elongatus (Mahadeva and Munroe 1990).
This species is frequently misidentified as Symphurus chabanaudi (Mahadeva and Munroe 1990).

Symphurus leei Jordan and Bollman 1890 was named after Professor L.A. Lee and Mr. Thomas Lee. According to Fricke et al. (2021), the appropriate spelling of the specific epithet should be leeorum because this is the correct form when the species was named after two people (ICZN Article 31.1.2).
Munroe (1990) placed Symphurus seychellensis Chabanaud 1955 and S. sechurae Hildebrand 1946 into the synonymy of S. melanurus Clark 1936.
This species can be easily confused with the congener Parupeneus heptacanthus (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
This species is easily confused with Parupeneus heptacanthus (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
This species is easily confused with Parupeneus heptacanthus (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
This species was recently revised by Uiblein et al. (2019).
This species is may be confused with Upeneus vittatus (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).
This species may be confused with Upeneus vittatus (F. Uiblein pers. comm. 2019).

authority: Marceniuk, Molina, Caires, Rotundo, Wosiacki & Oliveira, 2019
Chao, Chang, Chen, Guo, Lin, Liou, Shen & Liu, 2019

taxonomicNotes: This species has recently been described as distinct from an A. filamentosus species complex. These two species have previously been confused (Iwatsuki and Heemstra 2018). This species has a blue lacrimal and preopercular flange and is commonly confused with A. spinifer that lacks the blue colouration of the head (Y. Iwatsuki pers. comm. 2019).
This species has recently been described as distinct from an A. spinifer species complex. The two species have been confused in the past (Iwatsuki and Heemstra 2018).
Work is underway that will consider Harpagifer palliolatus a synonym of H. bispinis (M. Hüne pers. comm. 2019).
As morphologically defined, Gymnogobius taranetzi has a polyphyletic origin (Sota et al. 2005) and therefore, the range of this species in Russia needs further clarification (Parin et al. 2014).
Although considered valid by Eschmeyer et al. (2018), this species is recognised in Japan as a species complex composed of a few species.
Two species have been confused under this species and some literature information may refer to the second species (Belobranchus segura).
Fricke et al. (2020) list this species in the genus Acentrogobius but it belongs in the genus Amoya (Z. Jaafar in prep).
The genus is presently under review and this species' distribution is uncertain.

It is likely that there is a species complex within Periophthalmus novaeguineaensis. Periophthalmus murdyi Larson and Takita, 2004, is a junior synonym. Type specimens of Eggert's original description (in 1935) include three specimens of P. darwini.

The specific name melanosticta has been treated as a noun by the original author and as melanostictus by some others. Here we follow the original spelling (melanosticta) as is being used in a revision of the genus (Larson and Hammer in press).
Allen (1991) described and illustrated this species, citing it as Stenogobius lachneri Watson, 1990, but Watson did not publish the name until 1994.
The genus Stenogobius is in need of revision.

Two subspecies are recognised (Collette 1974, 2004): Arrhamphus sclerolepis sclerolepis (southern Papua New Guinea and northern Australia) and A. sclerolepis kreftii (south-eastern Australia; south-east Queensland to Sydney, New South Wales).
Preliminary genetic investigations by P. Unmack and G.R. Allen indicate that this species contains several distinct populations that may warrant separate species status (G.R. Allen pers. comm. 2019).
This species was previously placed under the junior synonym of Lestrolepis luetkeni (Ho and Golani 2019).
This recently described species was previously identified as Squalus cf. mitsukurii (Daly-Engel et al. 2018).
Stiphodon is a problematic genus (Watson 1995). Other species have been misidentified as S. elegans.
There are no relevant taxonomic limitations.
There are no relevant taxonomic limitations.
There are no relevant taxonomic limitations.
This species is easily confused with Anoplocapros inermis (Matsuura 2008).

This speices was considered a junior synonym of Cephaloscyllium isabellum by Springer (1979) and of C. umbratile by Schaaf-da Silva & Ebert (2008), but resurrected as a valid species by Nakaya et al. (2013).

Delsman (1931) described Stolephorus baganensis proper (=S. baganensis baganensis) and Stolephorus baganensis var megalops from Indonesia; later, Dutt and Babu Rao (1959) described Anchoviella baganensis bengalensis from eastern India. Whitehead et al. (1988) and Wongratana et al. (1999) erroneously listed this species as S. b. macrops based off of Harenberg (1933). Whitehead et al. (1988) and Wongratana et al. (1999) considered S. b. macrops Delsman 1931 and A. b. bengalensis (Dutt and Babu Rao 1959) to be junior synonyms of S. baganensis. However, a recent morphological and genetic review of ten nominal species of Stolephorus concluded that S. b. megalops is a junior synonym of S. tri and S. bengalensis is a valid species (Hata et al. 2019).
This species has been confused in the past with Amblygobius stethophthalmus (museum records).
This species is closely related to Amblygobius bynoensis (Allen and Erdmann 2012) and has been confused with it.
Previously considered a widely distributed species and at times with two subspecies, it is now distinct from F. lentiginosus (Richardson, 1844) (Hoese and Larson 2008).
This species is similar to Valenciennea randalli (Hoese and Larson 1994).

Stolephorus bengalensis has long been treated as Stolephorus insularis (e.g. Whitehead et al. 1988; Wongratana et al. 1999). The name S. bengalensis, originally described as Anchoviella baganensis bengalensis by Dutt and Babu Rao (1959), has been regarded as a junior synonym of Stolephorus baganensis Delsman 1931. However, a recent morphological and genetic review of ten nominal species of Stolephorus concluded that S. insularis is a junior synonym of S. tri and S. bengalensis is a valid species (Hata et al. 2019).

Hata and Motomura (2019) recently described two new species, Thrissina cultella and T. serena, as distinct from T. vitrirostris. There remains some disagreement as to the validity of the genera Thryssa and Thrissina. Kottelat (2013) regarded the genus Thyrssa as a new spelling for, and a junior synonym of, Thrissa and gave precedence to Thrissina over simultaneous synonyms Xenengraulis and Scutengraulis. However, Thryssa is regarded as independent of Thrissa by Fricke et al. (2020), and for the sake of stability, retained the genus Thryssa.
The Bay of Bengal population may represent a separate dwarf Iago omanensis-like species (Fernando et al. 2019, Psomadakis et al. 2019).

Regional synonyms of this species include: Perca ciliata Cuvier, 1828 (Java); Dules guamensis Valenciennes, 1831 (Guam); Dules vanicolensis Valenciennes, 1831 (Santa Cruz Islands); Dules haswellii Macleay, 1881 (Queensland); Dules rupestris hedleyi Ogilby 1897 (New Caledonia); Kuhlia caerulescens Regan, 1913 (Solomon Islands).
This species is often confused with Butis amboinensis.

Recent molecular studies found all sea- and coast-spawing shads from the Aegean, Black and Caspian Sea basins to be very closely related and their taxonomy might be revised in the future. We follow the traditional species concept until this species complex will be resolved.

The species was reviewed by Allen and Burgess (1990) who noted that this species is frequently misidentified and some distributions may be suspect (e.g. it does not occur in Australia). It is often misidentified as Ambassis commersoni Cuvier, 1828, which is a synonym of Ambassis ambassis Lacepède 1802.
The species was reviewed by Murdy and Shibukawa (2003). Previous records from Australia were a different species.
Bathygobius fuscus was originally described as Gobius fuscus by Rüppell (1830) from the Red Sea.
This species was reviewed by Allen and Burgess (1990).
In Australia, Butis butis is often confused with this species.

This species is the senior synonym of Awaous melanocephalus (Bleeker 1849). Bleeker described the two species in the same publication, based on a male (A. melanocephalus) and a female (A. grammepomus). Awaous melanocephalus was first synonymised with A. grammepomus by Gunther (1861), although both names are still often used. Species of the genus Awaous are in need of revision.

Prior to the recent species description, this species previously included Neotrygon kuhlii (Last et al. 2016a). The Neotrygon genus has recently been split and currently includes at least 11 species. It is difficult to distinguish some members of the genus based solely on morphology, thus the true distribution and overlap of species is not currently known. More work is required to fully understand where each member of the Neotrygon genus occurs,
There may be some taxonomic overlap of Centropomus armatus, C. robalito, and C. unionensis. Further taxonomic study is needed.
Chelonodon laticeps is morphologically similar to C. patoca (Matsuura 2002).
Atelomycterus erdmanni is closely related to A. baliensis and A. marmoratus, being sympatric with the latter (Fahmi and White 2015).
The species is distinguished from Philippine Guitarfish (Rhinobatos whitei) and Goldeneye Guitarfish (R. sainsbury) by colour, morphology, and meristic characters (White et al. 2016).

It is thought that there are at least four different subpopulations of A. marmorata based on morphological and genetic characters, in the North Pacific, South Pacific, Indian Ocean and Micronesia (Minegishi et al. 2008, Watanabe et al. 2009). Although, some studies using genetics have identified five (Ishikawa et al. 2004). Watanabe et al. (2008) suggested that total number of vertebrae indicated four morphological groups, but five different subpopulations in the North Pacific, South Pacific, Indian Ocean, Micronesia and Tahiti. Anguilla marmorata is thought to have between 100-110 vertebrae and can reach up to 2 m in length.

Previously, this species included two subspecies: P. o. occidentalis and P. o. sonoriensis. These subspecies are now recognised as separate species: P. occidentalis and P. sonoriensis. The previous entry for P. occidentalis on the IUCN Red List (LR/nt, 1996) does not refer to the current concept of P. occidentalis as that assessment included data for both subspecies, while the current assessment refers only to the population that was previously referred to as P. o. occidentalis.

Concha et al. (2019) synonymised the genus Zearaja with Dipturus based on morphological and molecular analyses, thus assigning species formerly in the genus Zearaja to Dipturus. The species Dipturus chilensis formerly was considered as occurring in both the Southeast Pacific and the Southwest Atlantic. However, Gabbanelli et al. (2018) resurrected Raja brevicaudata Marini, 1933 from Argentina out of synonymy with D. chilensis and Concha et al. (2019) described Dipturus lamillai Concha, Caira, Ebert & Pompert, 2019 as a distinct species from the Falkland Islands (Malvinas), Southwest Atlantic. Therefore, D. chilensis is restricted to the Southeast Pacific, from central Chile to the Strait of Magellan, and references to D. chilensis in the Southwest Atlantic refer either to D. brevicaudatus or D. lamillai.
This species concept has been revised to incorporate the taxonomic revision of Psammobatis parvacauda (Mabraganã et al. 2020)
This species has been confused with other Johnius species.

In the past, there has been confusion arising from the use of the names D. acuta and D. elopsoides. Records of D. acuta in the eastern Mediterranean may refer instead to D. elopsoides (Whitehead 1985). However, this confusion has since been resolved (H. Hata pers. comm. 2017).


Additionally, Dussumieria albulina (Fowler 1934) was formerly regarded as a junior synonym of Dussumieria acuta Valenciennes 1847 but is now regarded as a valid species and is redescribed based on morphological characters (e.g. lacking parasphenoid teeth, higher gill raker counts, slender body, presence of melanophores on mid-part of pectoral fin) and mitochondrial cytochrome oxidase I (COI) gene analysis (Hata et al. 2020). All previous accounts of this nominal species (D. acuta) from Indonesia and the Philippines refers to the newly redescribed D. albulina. For the purposes of this Red List Assessment, D. acuta is distributed along the Eurasian Continent from the Persian Gulf to the Chinese coast and D. albulina is distributed from India, Indonesia, and the Philippines. These two species occur sympatrically in the eastern Indian Ocean from the southern coast of India to Singapore (Hata et al. 2020).

Dussumieria albulina (Fowler 1934) was formerly regarded as a junior synonym of D. acuta Valenciennes 1847. Hata et al. (2020) redescribed D. abulina based on morphological characters (e.g. lacking parasphenoid teeth, higher gill raker counts, slender body, presence of melanophores on mid-part of pectoral fin) and mitochondrial cytochrome oxidase I (COI) gene analysis, validating it as a separate species. All previous accounts of the nominal species, D. acuta from Indonesia and the Philippines refers to this newly redescribed species (D. albulina). For the purposes of this Red List Assessment, D. acuta is distributed along the Eurasian Continent from the Persian Gulf to the Chinese coast and D. albulina is distributed from India, Indonesia, and the Philippines. These two species occur sympatrically in the eastern Indian Ocean from the southern coast of India to Singapore (Hata et al. 2020).
This species was previously mistaken for the similar Bathyraja brachyurops (Díaz de Astarloa and Mabragaña 2004) and reported elsewhere as Bathyraja sp. (J. Pompert pers. comm).

Torpedo peruana Chirichigno, 1963 is tentatively recognised as a synonym of Tetronarce tremens (de Buen, 1959) (Carvalho et al. 2002). Torpedo microdiscus is also now included as a synonym of T. tremens (Carvalho et al. 2016).

Prior to 2018, the literature referred to this species as Squalus mitsukurii or S. cf. mitsukurii. Further, this species is sometimes confused with Squalus cubensis and may be confused with recently described or undescribed species in the South Atlantic (C.F. Cotton unpubl. data 2020). Prior western Atlantic records of Squalus blainville may refer to this species (Kiraly et al. 2003, Pfleger et al. 2018), however eastern records of S. blainville represent a different species (Pfleger et al. 2018). Old records of S. acanthias in the Gulf of Mexico (and its junior synonyms S. fernandinus and S. barbouri) likely refer to this species (C.F. Cotton unpubl. data 2020).

This species has been split from Gymnura micrura and is morphologically similar but can be distinguished on the basis of internal diagnostic characters such as the contour of the hyomandibula (Yokota and de Carvalho 2017).
